<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Condren, Zito Seek 3rd Derby Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- William Condren is content. He's in  
Kentucky in the spring with a Derby hopeful, and he is involved 
with two men he calls friends. 
</P>
<P>
	One is George M. Steinbrenner, the boss of the New York Yankees,  
who sold Condren an interest in Wondertross, who was bred in 
Kentucky by Steinbrenner's Kinsman Farm. 
</P>
<P>
	The other is trainer Nick Zito.  
</P>
<P>
	``Nick knows a lot about the first Saturday in May,'' Condren  
said Wednesday outside of Zito's barn at Keeneland. 
</P>
<P>
	If Wondertross, second by a nose to Vicar in the Florida Derby  
March 13, runs well in the Toyota Blue Grass on Saturday, on May 1 
he will parade to the strains of ``My Kentucky Home.'' Condren and 
Zito will wait anxiously to see if the colt can put them into the 
Derby winner's circle for a third time. 
</P>
<P>
	It would be a first Derby victory for Steinbrenner, who has  
owned three starters and co-owned another. 
</P>
<P>
	Zito won the race in 1991 with Strike the Gold and in 1994 with  
Go for Gin. Condren co-owned both colts. 
</P>
<P>
	It's doubtful if anybody gets more of a kick out of the Derby  
than Zito, who grew up on the streets of New York. Some trainers 
will tell you, or try to tell you, the Derby is not that big a 
deal. Zito is not one of them. 
</P>
<P>
	Zito can get emotional just talking about the Derby.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to finish off the `90s the right way,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	That would be by snapping a tie with trainers Bob Baffert and D.  
Wayne Lukas for the most Derby wins in the 1990s. Baffert, of 
course, won the last two Derbies with Silver Charm and Real Quiet. 
Lukas won with Thunder Gulch in 1994 and with Grindstone in 1996. 
He also won with the filly Winning Colors in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Finishing off the `90s the right way for Zito might not be the  
right way for Condren and Steinbrenner. 
</P>
<P>
	Zito could also win the Derby with Stephen Go Even, owned by  
Stephen Hilbert. Stephen Go Even has won all three starts this 
year, including an impressive win in the Gallery Furniture.com 
Stakes on March 27 at Turfway Park. His next start will be in the 
Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert has two Derby starters in General Challenge and Prime  
Timber, 1-2, respectively, in last Saturday's Santa Anita Derby. 
Lukas has Charismatic, fourth at Santa Anita, in the Derby and he 
probably will have Cat Thief, who will start in the Blue Grass. 
</P>
<P>
	Condren got into this year's Derby picture because of Zito and  
Steinbrenner's son, Hank, who runs his father's racing and breeding 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	After Wondertross finished second in the Remsen on Nov. 28 at  
Aqueduct in the final start of his four-race 2-year-old campaign -- 
during which he won twice -- Steinbrenner got offers to sell an 
interest in the colt. 
</P>
<P>
	``George was not interested in a partnership,'' Condren said.  
``But Hank convinced his father that it was commercially prudent to 
sell a portion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Condren recalled that Steinbrenner told his son, ``Call Nick  
Zito,'' with whom Steinbrenner has had horses. Zito called Condren, 
and when Condren bought an interest in Wondertross, the colt was 
taken from trainer John Tammaro Jr. and given to Zito. 
</P>
<P>
	Under his deal with Steinbrenner, Condren said, ``I am the  
managing co-owner and the horse runs in my colors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Should Wondertross win the Kentucky Derby, you can bet Condren's  
colors would look like pinstripes to his partner -- the Boss. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
