<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslavia Says Kosovo War Is Over  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslavia urged refugees to return  
home today, declaring ``peace has prevailed in Kosovo'' and saying 
its 14-month war against ethnic Albanian separatists was over. But 
Western officials feared those same refugees would be used as human 
shields against NATO attacks. Meanwhile, NATO jets continued 
unleashing fierce attacks against Yugoslavia early Friday on the 
16th day of the U.S.-led air assault. President Clinton earlier 
today insisted that NATO can still win in Kosovo without sending in 
ground troops. 

</P>
<P>
	Negotiator Arrives in Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A former Cypriot president arrived  
here today to try to win the release of three American prisoners of 
war. Although the government has made no promises, senior officials 
greeted Kyprianou warmly and showed no sign of wanting his mission 
to fail. He is expected to meet with President Slobodan Milosevic 
tomorrow. But Serbia's hard-line vice premier, Vojislav Seselj, 
tried to throw a damper on the visit, saying that releasing the 
three Americans to Kyprianou was ``out of the question'' and they 
should be tried as ``terrorists.'' 

</P>
<P>
	China Premier Denies Spying  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji today denied that  
his country has been involved in nuclear-weapons spying, but he 
promised President Clinton to cooperate in investigations of 
alleged espionage. Zhu also rejected U.S. charges of human rights 
abuses in China as ``unfair'' and an intrusion in its internal 
affairs. But the two leaders claimed important progress on the 
contentious issue of trade. Clinton then hosted an official White 
House dinner for Zhu featuring musical performances -- one of their 
shared passions. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Sides With NAACP in Fla. Case  
</P>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Daytona Beach's plan to restrict traffic  
during this weekend's Black College Reunion is unconstitutional, 
U.S. District Judge Patricia C. Fawsett ruled today. Fawsett agreed 
with the NAACP and three Daytona Beach residents that the city 
unfairly singled out the event. The NAACP and the residents argued 
that the city had never taken such restrictive action against Bike 
Week or spring break, two largely white gatherings that draw larger 
crowds. The judge banned the city from enforcing the restriction, 
which would allow beach access only to residents, hotel guests and 
those conducting business. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Push Patients' Rights  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prodding Congress to pass a ``patients bill of  
rights,'' President Clinton will use a Philadelphia pep rally 
tomorrow to extend new health care protections to federal workers. 
Figures that Clinton intends to release show that a package of 
several new benefits for 9 million federal employees will cost less 
than $10 per person each year. The president will also announce a 
new ``Internet petition,'' where computer users can register their 
support for new regulations that would mandate that HMOs and other 
managed care plans provide the same benefits to all covered 
patients. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM To Offer All PC Products Online  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM plans to offer its entire PC product line  
for sale over the Internet as it goes directly after the small 
business and consumer market. Code-named Project Odyssey, IBM's 
plan focuses on luring small businesses and consumers as new 
customers, a company spokesman said. IBM already enjoys substantial 
revenues from its Web site -- an estimated $38 million a day. 

</P>
<P>
	31 Acts Announced for Woodstock '99  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Woodstock '99 will be busting with bands like  
The Dave Matthews Band, Jewel, Metallica and Alanis Morissette -- 
appealing to an audience not even born when the original concert 
took place in 1969. Organizers expect about 250,000 people. The 
festival is scheduled for July 23-25 at Griffiss Park, an abandoned 
Air Force base west of Albany. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Up in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices opened sharply higher Friday.  
The Nikkei gained 213.26 points to 17,059.95 in early trading. In 
New York today, the Dow industrials gained 112.39 to 10,197.70, a 
record high. The Nasdaq also set a record, rising 28.96 to 
2,573.39. 

</P>
<P>
	Jazz Coach Bounced From Game  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Jazz coach Jerry Sloan has been ejected  
from tonight's game against Golden State, the second time in as 
many games Sloan has been tossed. Referee Ronnie Nunn called 
consecutive technical fouls on Sloan during the second quarter. 
Utah trailed Golden State 29-21 at the time. Sloan also was ejected 
from Utah's 106-93 victory over the Los Angeles Lakers on Tuesday. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
