<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress To Reconvene Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite the NATO bombing in Yugoslavia,  
Democrats are planning a renewed push for legislation dealing with 
health care, campaign finance and an increase in the minimum wage 
when Congress reconvenes next week after a two-week spring break. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton and several lawmakers are expected to travel  
to Philadelphia on Friday to sign an online petition calling on 
Republicans to pass a ``patients bill of rights'' bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Democratic-aligned organizations, including the AFL-CIO and  
Families USA, have posted the petition on their Web sites. It 
includes a call for access to out-of-network medical specialists, 
as well as the right to sue HMOs. 
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans have said they intend to bring health  
legislation to the floor this year, although they have no immediate 
plans to do so. The right to sue has been a sticking point in the 
past, with Clinton and the Democrats insisting on it and 
Republicans objecting. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The White House is planning an extensive series of briefings on  
Yugoslavia for lawmakers next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Several congressional officials say they expect the top leaders  
of both parties in both houses to meet with Clinton at the White 
House Monday night for an update on the air campaign against 
Yugoslavia and efforts to deal with the flood of refugees from 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	A larger group of lawmakers is expected to be invited to meet  
with the president at the White House on Tuesday. In addition, 
administration officials are likely to be dispatched to the Capitol 
later in the week to brief rank-and-file lawmakers in both houses. 
</P>
<P>
	The bulk of the air campaign has taken place since the House and  
Senate began their two-week break last month. Senior lawmakers have 
had briefings in the interim with national security adviser Sandy 
Berger and other top administration officials. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats intend to shine the spotlight on campaign finance  
reform next Wednesday, the first day lawmakers are free to sign a 
petition demanding the measure be brought to the House floor by the 
Republican majority. Sponsors of the bill -- designed to shrink the 
amount of money spent in political campaigns -- say they expect a 
substantial majority of rank-and-file Democrats to sign the 
petition. 
</P>
<P>
	It takes signatures of a majority of all House lawmakers, or  
218, for the petition to succeed, a numerical impossibility unless 
some Republicans join the effort. 
</P>
<P>
	The House's most prominent GOP advocate of a campaign finance  
overhaul, Rep. Christopher Shays of Connecticut, isn't expected to 
sign, at least for the time being. A spokesman, Eric Friedman, said 
Shays is ``still working with the (GOP) leadership about getting to 
the floor.'' Shays signed a similar petition last year, as did 
other Republicans, and Democrats say they expect they would again 
if it is necessary to force the legislation onto the House floor.	   Last year, then-Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., agreed to bring 
the legislation to the floor only after the petition neared the 
218-signature mark. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic aides say there also have been discussions with the  
White House in recent weeks about staging a public ceremony with 
the president to dramatize the call for an increase in the minimum 
wage, now $5.15 an hour. GOP aides have held a series of meetings 
recently to try to prepare for what some Republicans believe will 
be an inevitable vote to increase the wage floor. Rep. Jack Quinn, 
R-N.Y., who has ties to organized labor, has proposed legislation 
that would increase the minimum wage at the same pace as inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic proposal is for a 50-cent-an-hour increase this  
year, followed by a similar increase in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans are hoping to reach a House-Senate agreement quickly  
on their budget for the next fiscal year. Both houses want to set 
aside the entire Social Security surplus, but must agree on the 
specifics. Clinton's budget, by contrast, would spend some of the 
Social Security surplus on domestic programs. GOP House leaders had 
been scheduled to trumpet their own budget during a two-day tour of 
the Midwest this week, but they scrapped the plan at the last 
minute, citing the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The emerging GOP budget also leaves room for a large tax cut  
over the next several years. Clinton's signature is not required on 
the budget, which establishes guidelines for later tax and spending 
bills. Passage of the budget would pave the way for work on 
individual spending bills, where the White House would have the 
customary leverage of a veto threat. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans also hope to reach House-Senate agreements over the  
next few weeks on bills on education and a missile defense system 
that Clinton will sign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
