<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Sides With NAACP in Fla. Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Daytona Beach's plan to restrict traffic  
during this weekend's Black College Reunion is unconstitutional, a 
federal judge ruled Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Patricia C. Fawsett agreed with the National  
Association for the Advancement of Colored People and three Daytona 
Beach residents that the city unfairly singled out the event. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge banned the city from enforcing the restriction, which  
would allow beach access only to residents, hotel guests and those 
conducting business. Others would have to park their cars and take 
a shuttle. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAACP and the residents argued that the city had never taken  
such restrictive action against Bike Week or spring break, two 
largely white gatherings that draw larger crowds. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said the city's plan violated the First Amendment's  
guarantees that the right of assembly not be tied to a person's 
economic or status or residence. She did not rule on the 
allegations of racial discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	``Defendants have not proffered a rational explanation for why  
BCR as an event should be singled out and subjected to greater 
restrictions than other events,'' Fawsett wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 100,000 people are expected for the weekend  
gathering, where the crowds transform the main beachside road into 
a street party. It is scheduled to begin Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 01:24:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Everglades Restoration Moved Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Trying to placate environmentalists, the Army Corps  
of Engineers has released a new, $7.8 billion plan that calls for a 
speedier cleanup of the Everglades. 
</P>
<P>
	``We guess there are more people now happy about the plan than  
the first one,'' Jacquelyn Griffin, spokeswoman for the corps in 
Jacksonville, said Wednesday. ``Everyone is so delighted. ... We 
have something for the common man and agriculture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new plan was changed after environmentalists and scientists  
complained the original proposal, announced by Vice President Al 
Gore, took too long. Under the new plan, many key components would 
be completed by 2020 rather than 2025. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress will debate the corps' plan in July after the public  
and government officials discuss the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan aims to restore traditional water flow through the  
Everglades to save the animal population that has dipped by 90 
percent among some species. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 50 years ago, engineers for the corps built a water  
management system using a series of canals and levees throughout 
South Florida. That process endangered the Everglades by allowing 
water from nearby farms and development to flow into the wetlands. 
</P>
<P>
	The corps now must balance the water management needs for the  
area while still protecting the Everglades. 
</P>
<P>
	Nathaniel Reed, environmentalist and former assistant interior  
secretary, said the plan is scientifically sound and must go 
forward without delay. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot wait until we have all the details and all the  
answers,'' Reed said. ``If we become paralyzed by this desire and 
fail to act immediately, we will miss what is very likely our last 
golden opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Environmental groups like the Sierra Club hail the accelerated  
timetable but say the plan still lacks toughness. It doesn't call 
for buying land from sugar cane growers, said to be one of the 
major polluters of the Everglades. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why is sugar so quiet?'' asked Rodrick Tirrell, the Everglades  
co-chair for Florida Sierra Club. ``The happier they are with this 
plan, that throws a question mark in my mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Buker, a vice president of U.S. Sugar Corp. in Clewiston,  
said the company welcomes the changes if they don't compromise the 
success of restoration. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want it done as fast as possible, but you don't want to  
build something too quick that doesn't work,'' he said. ``We assume 
the engineering will be there.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 19:12:44 </DATE_TIME>
