<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Higher; Dow Up 117.94 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher Thursday, sending the Dow  
Jones industrials further into record territory, as a drop in 
European interest rates calmed investor worries about upcoming 
earnings reports. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow was up 117.94 at 10,203.25,  
taking the index past the closing high of 10,085.31 it set 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators today were also higher. The  
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index shook off early losses and 
was up 18.17 at 2,562.60. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders attributed the rally, which followed a mostly flat  
morning, to two interest rate cuts in Europe. The Bank of England 
lowered short-term rates to 5.25 percent from 5.5 percent, while 
the European Central Bank cut its main refinancing rate to 2.5 
percent from 3 percent, a greater cut than had been anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks, which are sensitive to changes in interest  
rates, rose on the expectation that the cut by the British central 
bank would help keep U.S. rates low as well. The cut also drove 
bond prices higher, which helped feed the rally in stocks, analysts 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Citigroup rose 1 5/16 to 73 and American Express advanced 2 1/2 at  
128 15/16. Both are Dow components. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo!'s strong earnings reported Wednesday and the bond market  
rally were the two biggest factors in the stock market rally, said 
Barry Berman, head trader for Robert W. Baird &AMP; Co. in Milwaukee. 
``We see signs that the economy is growing and most pre-earnings 
announcements are out of the way,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! fell 7/16 to 208 after running up sharply earlier in the  
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart was up 3 13/16 at 101 5/16, rose after reporting an 11  
percent increase in sales from stores open at least a year during 
March. 
</P>
<P>
	General Electric, which reported earnings in line with analysts'  
expectations, up 3/8 to 114 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell Computer fell 1 1/4 to 45 3/16. Intel fell 1 3/16 to 130  
15/16, as microchip stocks dropped in response to a disappointing 
earnings outlook from Advanced Micro Devices, which fell 7/8 to 15 
5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	But traders were still cautious about upcoming earnings reports.  
</P>
<P>
	HMOs were among the biggest losers after Humana, down 4 7/16 to  
11 3/4, warned it would fall short of first quarter earnings 
estimates. PacifiCare dropped 5 7/8 to 61 7/8 and United Healthcare fell 
4 13/16 to 45 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you disappoint, you're taken out behind the barn and  
spanked,'' said Alfred Goldman, chief of market strategy for A.G. 
Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street received more good news about the economy. The Labor  
Department reported the number of Americans claiming unemployment 
benefits rose last week but remained at less than 300,000 for the 
10th consecutive week, the longest such stretch in 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 15.23 at 1,342.12.  
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues were slightly ahead of decliners on the New  
York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 673.7 million shares, up 
slightly from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 7.31 at 623.54 and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 1.64 at 718.94. 

</P>
</TEXT>
