<HEADLINE> British American Tobacco OKs Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Shareholders of British American Tobacco PLC, the  
maker of Lucky Strike, Kent and other cigarettes, voted 
overwhelmingly Thursday in favor of acquiring rival Rothmans 
International BV in an $8.1 billion deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger between the world's second- and fourth-largest  
cigarette companies must still get regulatory approval from 
agencies in the U.S. and Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	BAT chairman Martin Broughton said the company has received one  
of two clearances it needs from U.S. authorities and expects the 
other approval shortly. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Commission has already approved the deal.  
Discussions with Australia's Competition and Consumer Commission 
are continuing. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies announced their planned merger in January. The  
companies would have a combined market share of more than 16 
percent, second to Philip Morris Cos., which has 17 percent of the 
world market. 
</P>
<P>
	BAT did not provide a breakdown of the shareholder vote, and  
calls seeking information from the company's offices went 
unanswered Thursday evening. 

</P>
</TEXT>
