<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslavia: Kosovo Offensive Over  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslavia urged refugees to return  
home today, declaring ``peace has prevailed in Kosovo'' and saying 
its 14-month war against ethnic Albanian separatists was over. But 
Western officials feared those same refugees would be used as human 
shields against NATO attacks. The United States pledged that NATO 
will press ahead with the bombing campaign. Meanwhile, a former 
Cypriot president arrived in Belgrade to try to win freedom for 
three captured U.S. soldiers. His task could prove difficult: A 
hard-line Serbian vice premier ruled out any release as long as the 
NATO bombardment continued. 

</P>
<P>
	Cohen to Airmen: NATO Will Prevail  
</P>
<P>
	AVIANO AIR BASE, Italy (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen  
assured American pilots and support crews their efforts in the 
Balkans would lead to victory. Cohen's Aviano audience included 
pilots just back from bombing runs over Yugoslavia. They mentioned 
encountering considerable anti-aircraft fire, particularly during 
night flights. But a 32-year-old F-15E pilot said morale is high 
even though the missions are dangerous. Members of Congress 
traveling with Cohen suggested there should be planning, at least, 
for sending ground troops. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton, Zhu Hold White House Talks  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and Chinese Premier Zhu  
Rongji met at the White House today, then sparred at a joint news 
conference that ranged from trade to human rights. Despite China's 
efforts at political reform, it must ``give citizens greater 
freedom'' to enhance their lives, Clinton said. Zhu denied that 
China's spies have stolen secrets from American research 
laboratories or that its agents funneled campaign contributions to 
Democrats. Clinton said they made progress on trade issues during 
their meeting and he hopes obstacles blocking China's entry into 
the World Trade Organization could be cleared away by year's end. 

</P>
<P>
	N.J.'s Whitman Launches Senate Bid  
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Gov. Christie Whitman, one of the stars of  
the Republican Party, launched a bid for the Senate with the 
formation of a fund-raising committee. Barred by law from seeking a 
third term as governor, she announced today that she intends to run 
for the Senate seat being vacated by three-term Democrat Frank 
Lautenberg. Whitman is a social moderate who supports abortion 
rights, something that may hurt her on the national stage but is 
considered an asset in a Senate run in New Jersey. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Leaders Fear Message Not Heard  
</P>
<P>
	WILLIAMSBURG, Va. (AP) -- Republican activists gathering for a  
meeting of state GOP chairmen complained that the party's appeals 
to voters are being drowned out -- first by impeachment and now by 
war. Talk of tax cuts, Social Security reform and better schools 
were lost in the debate over Clinton's fate in the Monica Lewinsky 
investigation and are playing second-fiddle to the conflict in 
Kosovo, they said. The Republican state chairmen's association 
sponsored more than a dozen strategy sessions today designed to 
improve the GOP's communications efforts nationwide. 

</P>
<P>
	FAA To Test Y2K Computer Fixes  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration will try the  
first live test of its Year 2000 air-traffic computer fixes this 
weekend. Late Saturday and early Sunday, the agency plans to split 
the computers controlling air traffic around Denver International 
Airport and spin the clock ahead to Jan. 1, 2000, in half of the 
systems. The radar systems will track both commercial flights and 
an FAA Lear Jet flying over Colorado. The likely result of the Y2K 
glitch is that air traffic controllers will spread planes apart to 
enlarge existing safety buffers, creating flight delays. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes at Record 10,197.70  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks surged higher today, lifting the Dow  
Jones industrial average by 112.39 points to another record high -- 
10,197.70. A drop in interest rates eased investor fears about U.S. 
earnings reports. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,702-1,261. The 
Nasdaq was up 28.96 at 2,573.39, also a record. 

</P>
<P>
	Pizza Mogul Creates Catholic School  
</P>
<P>
	ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Domino's Pizza mogul Tom Monaghan, who  
sold the business to devote himself to Roman Catholic causes, is 
spending $50 million to establish a new law school stressing 
traditional Catholic values. One-time Supreme Court nominee Robert 
Bork has signed on as its first professor. The Ave Maria School of 
Law is to open in fall 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	Trio Leads Masters Golf  
</P>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Davis Love III, Scott McCarron and Brandel  
Chamblee held the lead at the Masters golf tournament today after 
shooting three-under-par 69s. There were five players in at 2-under 
70: Andrew Magee, Colin Montgomerie, Jeff Sluman, Jose Maria 
Olazabal, and Justin Leonard. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  
</P>
