<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FAA To Study Engine Backfiring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Backfiring Pratt &AMP; Whitney jet engines,  
which power hundreds of passenger jets worldwide, have raised 
concern among pilots and attracted the scrutiny of federal 
inspectors. 
</P>
<P>
	No crashes have been blamed on the backfiring, which reportedly  
have happened during takeoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Although some of the backfiring is mild, others have caused  
balls of flame to shoot out of the engines and forced pilots to 
shut down power. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration said Thursday it is stepping  
up scrutiny of the engines. 
</P>
<P>
	The East Hartford company has been working on the problem with  
the PW4000 engines since 1993. While the incidents of backfires 
have decreased, the problem is not fixed, according to the FAA. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA already has ordered that modified engines be installed  
by June 30. It is preparing a second order regarding methods to 
determine whether the engine should remain flying, said Robert 
Guyotte, manager of the FAA engine certification branch in 
Burlington, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 170 backfires of PW4000s have been reported since  
1992, and less than 20 of those happened with engines that Pratt 
has modified since the problem was reported, Guyotte said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was after series of violent backfires by a PW4000 engine that  
a United Airlines 747 lost power on takeoff from San Francisco and 
nearly struck San Bruno Mountain last June. 
</P>
<P>
	Although pilot error was determined to play a role in the  
near-crash, the PW4000 has been implicated in other near-disasters 
since then. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the same engines on a China Airlines jet backfired a  
month later during takeoff from a Taiwan airport. The same engine 
was responsible for two backfires on Delta Air Lines jets in the 
last six months. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, four United Airlines jets equipped with the PW4000  
backfired while taking off from Indianapolis, New York, Dusseldorf, 
Germany and Montevideo, Uraguay. In each case, the planes landed 
safely. 
</P>
<P>
	The PW4000 was introduced in 1987. Since 1993, representatives  
of Pratt and the airlines that operate the engines have been 
working as a team to study needed improvements, Pratt spokesman 
Mark Sullivan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a problem,'' Sullivan said. ``Reducing the number of  
surges in jet engines is something we've been working on since we 
started making jet engines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the past three years, about 85 percent of the estimated 2,000  
engines in service have been modified, Sullivan said. The remainder 
must be modified by June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1993, Pratt has reduced its occurrence of backfires from  
one surge per 8,000 flights to one surge per 32,000 flights, 
Guyotte said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The design changes that Pratt has made has reduced the rate,''  
said Guyotte. ``They weren't as effective as we had hoped they 
would be in reducing the number of surges.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There are nearly 2,000 PW4000 engine in service, powering almost  
600 Boeing 747s, 767s and MD11s and Airbus A300s and A310s spread 
among 60 airlines. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 23:12:13 </DATE_TIME>
