<HEADLINE> Young, Thrifty Chisox Set To Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- This year's marketing slogan for the Chicago  
White Sox is a simple one: ``The Kids Can Play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But will anyone come and watch?  
</P>
<P>
	The young White Sox -- young, if you don't count 30-year-old  
Frank Thomas and 35-year-old Darrin Jackson -- play their home 
opener Friday against the Kansas City Royals, following an 
impressive three-game opening series in Seattle where they won two 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	Surly Albert Belle and his frown went off to Baltimore, and  
clubhouse leader Robin Ventura headed to the New York Mets. The 
subtractions of their big contracts helped the Sox chop its payroll 
to $24 million. 
</P>
<P>
	And when they hit the field Friday, the White Sox will feature a  
team with only five players making $1 million or more, including 
Thomas' hefty $7 million and another $5 million to one of 
baseball's most underachieving pitchers the last two years -- Jaime 
Navarro. That's in contrast to the cross-town Cubs, whose 
opening-day payroll featured 15 players making at least $1.1 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The White Sox drew just 1.39 million fans last season to new  
Comiskey Park that opened in 1991, a facility that lacks the charm 
and flavor of today's retro stadiums. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no neighborhood ambiance, no taverns and restaurants  
like the ones that surround Wrigley Field and attract the Yuppie 
crowds. So the White Sox are counting on a hustling, aggressive 
brand of baseball and a youth movement to bring the fans back. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's average age is 26.2, second youngest in the majors  
behind the Florida Marlins (25.9), and the Sox have 20 players 
making under $300,000 -- a bargain in today's baseball market. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortstop Mike Caruso, who is 21, made 35 errors a year ago as a  
rookie but has shown improvement after working on a new throwing 
motion this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Caruso was also a .306 hitter last season after making the huge  
one-year leap from Class A. 
</P>
<P>
	Age, he says, should not be a factor in performance.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are a young team, but that doesn't matter,'' Caruso said.  
``I don't want to ever use that as an excuse if we lose a game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, in his second stint with the Sox, is an exception on  
the roster in terms of in age. But the veteran will keep playing as 
long as he hits like he did in Seattle, where he was 9-for-13 with 
a pair of homers in the three games against the Mariners. 
</P>
<P>
	``As hot as Darrin in, I'll go with him as long as I can,'' Sox  
manager Jerry Manuel said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
