<DOCNO> APW19990408.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 22:52:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chemotherapy, Exhaustion Explored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- They say they are ``bone-tired,'' so fatigued  
their arms and legs feel heavy. Simple things like taking a shower, 
even eating a full meal, are exhausting. 
</P>
<P>
	Most cancer patients will feel this extreme fatigue for weeks or  
months. This feeling is considered the No. 1 side effect of cancer 
and largely is caused by the chemotherapy or radiation necessary to 
fight the disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet few patients seek or receive treatment for fatigue, a lapse  
cancer specialists now are trying to remedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like an iceberg sitting there underneath the surface.  
It's a lot bigger problem than people seem to appreciate,'' said 
Dr. Tejpal Grover of M.D. Anderson Cancer Center. The Houston 
center just opened a comprehensive fatigue clinic to uncover what 
causes each patient's exhaustion and help them fight back. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want patients to say, 'Gosh maybe there's something that  
could be done, and I need to talk to my doctor about that,''' said 
Chicago nurse Marnie McHale of the Oncology Nurses Society, which 
this week started a campaign to educate patients and their 
caregivers about cancer fatigue. 
</P>
<P>
	Fatigue long was discounted as a serious problem and only now is  
being researched aggressively. Studies suggest that over 75 percent 
of cancer patients suffer serious fatigue. It limits their ability 
to work, attend school or perform daily activities. 
</P>
<P>
	There is a mental toll -- ``chemo brain'' some call it -- where  
patients cannot concentrate, are forgetful or depressed. It even 
can hinder rigorous cancer therapy. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet a recent survey of 379 cancer patients found only 9 percent  
of those who suffered fatigue were treated with prescription drugs 
or blood transfusions. While medication is not always appropriate, 
experts say that number should be higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the problem is dispelling the myths that there is no  
help for fatigue, or that fatigue only could mean the cancer is 
worsening so patients are scared to mention it, says the Oncology 
Nursing Society. 
</P>
<P>
	Patients and doctors also may not communicate well.  
</P>
<P>
	Patients have different degrees of fatigue, caused by different  
problems that require customized, comprehensive care that 
oncologists may be too busy battling the tumor to offer, Grover 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Anemia is a leading culprit, because radiation and many powerful  
chemotherapy drugs that kill cancer cells also kill blood and 
bone-marrow cells. Medicines, such as Epogen or Procrit, that boost 
blood-cell production or blood transfusions may help. 
</P>
<P>
	Undertreated pain is another big cause, limiting patients'  
sleep. 
</P>
<P>
	Some new studies suggest mild exercise programs help, because  
constant rest actually makes patients quickly lose muscle strength, 
thus worsening fatigue. 
</P>
<P>
	At M.D. Anderson's fatigue clinic, doctors are finding patients  
who were so busy fighting cancer that nobody noticed they also have 
thyroid problems or other energy-sapping diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	Tumors can compete for a body's nutrients at the same time that  
chemotherapy-caused nausea depletes calories and spurs dehydration. 
There are medicines to minimize nausea, and nutritionists may 
suggest easier-to-tolerate, high-nutrient meals. 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes help can be creative: Put a seat in the shower or a  
rolling stool in the kitchen to conserve energy. 
</P>
<P>
	There are not solutions for all patients and doctors do not  
fully understand cancer fatigue. That is frustrating to patients, 
as is finishing treatment and still being fatigued. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Cancer Institute notes that some cancer survivors  
can take years to regain energy. Still, ``patients put high 
expectations on themselves'' to get back to normal, and may lose 
family support once treatment ends, McHale said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new campaign, oncology nurses are educating patients  
and caregivers about fatigue, helping them plan ways to conserve 
energy and cope with cancer treatment and urging them to seek 
medical care when fatigue strikes. For more information, nurses 
will answer e-mailed questions at www.cancerfatigue.org. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lauran Neergaard covers health and medical  
issues for The Associated Press in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:58:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Push Patients' Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prodding Congress to pass a ``patients bill of  
rights,'' President Clinton will use a Philadelphia pep rally 
Friday to extend new health care protections to federal workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The president will also announce a new ``Internet petition,''  
where computer users can register their support for new regulations 
that would mandate that HMOs and other managed care plans provide 
the same benefits to all covered patients. 
</P>
<P>
	Figures that Clinton intends to release show that a package of  
several new benefits for 9 million federal employees will cost less 
than $10 per person each year. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the new provisions requires health plans to release a  
host of information about how they pay doctors, customer 
satisfaction and the quality of doctors and hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	The other requires plans to let patients stay with their doctors  
for 90 days, even if the doctor is dropped from the network, if 
they are in the middle of a treatment or pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has already extended the same provisions to patients in  
Medicare and Medicaid. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House hopes that the real-life experience with federal  
workers will blunt GOP arguments that new requirements drive up 
costs. The 285 health plans that serve federal workers also serve 
private citizens, officials note, and they are providing these 
guarantees for just a few dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	``The world has not stopped turning,'' said Chris Jennings,  
Clinton's top health policy aide. ``The same things can be applied 
for all Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton will be joined in Philadelphia by about 18 congressional  
Democrats pushing his ``patients bill of rights'' legislation. 
Another 90 Democrats plan similar events in 32 states. 
</P>
<P>
	``Democrats are going to take this fight on the road,'' said  
Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn. ``We're going to use the latest 
technology, this information superhighway, to give voice to the 
people in this country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The most controversial -- and most expensive -- provision that  
Democrats are pushing would give patients the right to sue health 
plans and collect damages when they withhold treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	An equally contentious provision that would require health plans  
to pay for ``medically necessary'' care, as determined by doctors. 
Clinton doesn't have the power to unilaterally extend either of 
those provisions to the federal workforce. 
</P>
<P>
	But the administration already has required that health plans  
covering government workers pay for reasonable emergency room trips 
and allow patients to see specialists outside the network if needed 
and obstetricians-gynecologists without a referral. 
</P>
<P>
	A Senate committee approved a more limited HMO bill last month,  
but there's been no action in the House yet. Democrats complain 
that bill would cover only about 48 million Americans who are in 
health plans regulated solely by the federal government. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of new federal legislation complained that any  
increase in costs is significant for many Americans and said the 
Democratic bill would simply ``open the door to more lawsuits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This helps trial lawyers who pocket most of the money, but  
does nothing to help patients get proper care when needed,'' said 
Dan Danner, chairman of the Health Benefits Coalition, which has 
run television ads in 19 states over the last two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The new petition Clinton is announcing is housed on the Web site  
of the consumer group Families USA. Up for about a week, it had 
more than 4,000 signatures Thursday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet address for the petition is  
http://www.familiesusa.org/pbr/ 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 17:08:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Serb: US Captives Won't Be Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Amid fears that refugees are  
becoming human shields now that Yugoslavia has sealed its borders, 
Serb media claimed today that ethnic Albanians were voluntarily 
returning to Kosovo. A Cypriot lawmaker arrived in Belgrade to seek 
the release of three captured U.S. soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	Spyros Kyprianou, speaker of the Cypriot parliament, said he  
planned to meet Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on Friday and 
that the Americans might be freed during the long Orthodox Easter 
weekend, starting today. 
</P>
<P>
	But the hardline Serbian vice premier, Vojislav Seselj, told  
reporters that freeing the three was ``out of the question'' and 
that the soldiers should be tried as terrorists. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States is leading an undeclared war against  
Yugoslavia,'' said Seselj, leader of the extreme nationalist 
Serbian Radical Party allied with Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	Before leaving for Belgrade, Kyprianou said the Yugoslav  
government expects NATO bombing to ease if it turns over the 
American soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, however, has ruled out any concessions to  
gain the soldiers' release, though NATO arranged for safe passage 
today of Kyprianou's flight. 
</P>
<P>
	As night fell today, several thousand people -- chanting  
``Yugoslavia, Yugoslavia'' -- gathered on two major bridges in 
Belgrade and the remaining Danube River bridge in Serbia's 
second-largest city, Novi Sad, serving as volunteer human shields 
against NATO attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Before dawn today, NATO warplanes and missiles took aim at the  
heart of Belgrade and against government troops in the hills of 
Kosovo in what the alliance said was a systematic bid to break the 
Yugoslav military machine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will prevail,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen told  
American pilots today at the Aviano air base in Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after Yugoslavia sealed its borders and choked off a flood  
of refugees from Kosovo, Serb media said ethnic Albanians were 
voluntarily heading back into the province. 
</P>
<P>
	Showing footage of long lines of cars and road signs pointing to  
destinations inside Kosovo, state TV said refugees had initially 
wanted to cross into neighboring Macedonia but had ``decided to 
return'' to their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly half a million Kosovars have fled or were driven out of  
Kosovo in the two weeks since the NATO bombing campaign began, the 
greatest mass displacement seen in Europe in half a century. Those 
reaching refuge in neighboring states have described a systematic 
campaign of terror against them by Serb troops and police. 
</P>
<P>
	Western military officials said the latest wave of air attacks  
focused on Serb police and army units scattered in rural areas of 
Kosovo. Small Yugoslav units have been blamed for most of the 
atrocities against ethnic Albanians, and targeting them in the 
hills and forests of the largely rural province has proven 
difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO airstrikes on roads and bridges in Kosovo are hampering the  
ability of Serb forces to get around the province, according to 
accounts today by French journalists who entered western Kosovo 
accompanied by members of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army. One of 
the accounts, on French RTL radio, said KLA forces are using a 
satellite telephone to help NATO identify Serb targets. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have attacked the nervous system, we have attacked the  
central system as well, that is to say a part of the brain that is 
conducting the operations,'' French Army Chief of Staff Gen. 
Jean-Pierre Kelche told reporters today. 
</P>
<P>
	Targets in the latest wave of attacks included Belgrade, where  
loud explosions rocked a densely populated neighborhood in the city 
center just before midnight. On a major artery leading from the 
main railway station, near the avenue where most foreign embassies 
are located, a huge plume of dust and smoke could be seen after the 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	A seven-story military building -- a vacant one -- was hit, its  
courtyard was demolished and interior walls smashed. Across the 
street, blue-smocked workers removed shattered glass from a hotel's 
window frames. 
</P>
<P>
	``NATO criminals ... hit the heart of Belgrade,'' said Belgrade  
TV, showing the scene. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the strike on Belgrade, overnight attacks on population  
centers were far less intense than on previous nights since the 
2-week-old air campaign began, Yugoslav media reports indicated. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO, meanwhile, said today it was not responsible for the  
widespread damage in Kosovo's capital, Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Commodore David Wilby, briefing reporters at NATO  
headquarters said that while NATO has attacked military targets 
around Pristina, including the police headquarters, televised 
photos showed much more widespread damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``NATO has certainly not caused the reported widespread and  
random damage which we believe has been orchestrated by Serbian 
forces,'' said Air Commodore David Wilby, briefing reporters at 
NATO headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Municipal officials in Pristina declared a day of mourning for  
what it said were 10 victims of NATO strikes early Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Conflicting reports continued to emerge, meanwhile, about the  
fate of 10,000 refugees declared missing after Macedonia emptied 
out a makeshift refugee camp on its border Tuesday night and early 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees still has not been able  
to account for them, spokeswoman Paula Ghedina said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonia challenged the UNHCR's account of a missing 10,000,  
saying today the aid agency had simply not properly estimated their 
numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	Refugee officials also did not know the fate of thousands  
apparently turned back by the Yugoslavs at Morini, the main 
crossing point into Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	The allies have vowed to keep up the pressure on Milosevic until  
he pulls back his forces from Kosovo and allows ethnic Albanian 
refugees to return under the protection of an international 
security force. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanians made up 90 percent of the 2 million prewar  
populace of Kosovo, a province in Serbia, the main republic in 
Yugoslavia. Milosevic's crackdown on ethnic Albanian separatists 
began 14 months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia's leadership announced a unilateral cease-fire with  
the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army effective Tuesday night in advance 
of Orthodox Easter, celebrated this weekend by Eastern rite 
churches. 
</P>
<P>
	But Western leaders vowed to continue the air campaign until  
Milosevic withdraws special police units from Kosovo and accepts 
the peace plan, which includes 28,000 NATO-led troops to enforce 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not possible to independently confirm the reports.  
</P>
<P>
	The latest air activity followed a dramatic move Wednesday by  
Yugoslav authorities to seal off the borders with Macedonia and 
Albania -- after forcing more than 450,000 refugees out of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of refugees who had been waiting on the Yugoslav  
frontier have been turned back to villages or towns said to have 
been ravaged amid the campaign of forced expulsions of the ethnic 
Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	Western officials including Germany's defense minister, Rudolf  
Scharping, and Britain's International Development Secretary Clare 
Short have voiced fears that the refugees were being forced back 
into Kosovo for use as human shields against NATO air attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Marshal Sir John Day, deputy chief of the defense staff,  
told a British military briefing that attacking NATO forces ``take 
every precaution'' to make sure they avoid targets where refugees 
may be used as human shields, but ``at the end of the day the 
responsibility is Milosevic's.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 17:08:53 </DATE_TIME>
