<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Same-Sex Harassment Ruling Appealed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- A company is appealing a judge's ruling  
that a female employee sexually harassed two female coworkers by 
calling them names that included derogatory terms for female body 
parts. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling was believed to be the first in the nation involving  
verbal sexual harassment between same-sex co-workers, an attorney 
in the case and a gay-rights group said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Supreme Court ruled last year that harassment can be  
illegal when the offender and victim are the same sex. That case, 
however, involved physical harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	The administrative law judge's ruling, made in January, stems  
from a complaint that two Ball-Foster Glass Container Co. workers 
filed with the state Equal Rights Division against the company in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Jayme Thiede and Marcia Graf, who work in the box shop at the  
company's Burlington plant, accused Ball-Foster of refusing to 
discipline a co-worker, Janet Koyen, for harassing them despite 
repeated complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	According to their complaint, Koyen repeatedly used abusive  
language that included words that also could have a sexual 
connotation. 
</P>
<P>
	State Administrative Law Judge Larry Jakubowski in Milwaukee  
ruled Jan. 11 that the women had been sexually harassed and ordered 
the company to pay them a total of $21,000 in legal fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Ball-Foster insists the women weren't sexually harassed because  
it involved an ongoing dispute that included little more than 
name-calling among co-workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``As rude and offensive as it might be for someone to walk in  
and call you a name, it's not against federal law,'' said Jeffrey 
Mallamad, an Indianapolis attorney for the Muncie, Ind.-based 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Thiede and Graf still work at the plant. Koyen was fired in  
October 1996 after she was accused of sending a threatening letter 
to the plant nurse in an incident unrelated to Graf and Thiede's 
complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	None could immediately be reached for comment Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
