<HEADLINE> LVMH Drops Bid for Gucci </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton plans no further  
talks to acquire Italy's Gucci fashion house, which on Thursday 
rejected a sweetened takeover bid by the French maker of luxury 
goods. 
</P>
<P>
	Board members at Gucci Groep turned down the $85 a share offer,  
which was increased from $81 a share, calling one condition of the 
proposal ``unacceptable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LVMH said it refrain from launching a formal takeover bid for  
Gucci until its lawsuit against the Italian company runs its 
course. 
</P>
<P>
	A hearing is scheduled for April 22 before a Dutch court to  
discuss LVMH's request for an investigation into Gucci's management 
practices. 
</P>
<P>
	LVMH hopes the findings of such an investigation would void the  
shares Gucci issued to its employees and to French retailer 
Pinault-Printemps-Redoute in an effort to dilute LVMH's existing 
stake in the company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
