<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bell Chiefs, FCC To Discuss Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- SBC Communications Corp. and Ameritech Corp.  
will talk to federal regulators about placing conditions on their 
planned merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Communications Commission Chairman Bill Kennard asked  
the chiefs of both local Bell telephone companies last week to do 
that after raising ``serious concerns'' about whether their merger 
would benefit consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are willing to meet with commission staff to explore the  
issues that you have identified,'' SBC Chairman Edward Whitacre Jr. 
and Ameritech Chairman Richard Notebaert said in a joint letter 
Wednesday to Kennard. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the chiefs said their companies have been providing  
detailed information about their merger to the FCC and continue to 
believe that the merger should be approved without conditions. 
Neither they nor Kennard said what conditions might be set. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard wants discussions to begin this month and to conclude by  
late June. The FCC could make a decision on the matter shortly 
thereafter. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC approval is the last major regulatory hurdle for the deal,  
which has been cleared by the Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger, valued at $57 billion when it was announced last  
year, would create the nation's largest local phone company. It 
would control 57 million, or one-third, of the nation's local phone 
lines spread across 13 states. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard, in letters to the companies' chiefs last week, wanted  
to know how the FCC can be assured that the public will receive the 
benefits the companies say will result from the union. He said 
Wednesday he was ``pleased'' the companies had decided to 
participate in the process he had outlined and looked forward ``to 
resolving this matter expeditiously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, Kennard asked how the commission can be  
assured that the merger won't interfere with the companies' 
willingness and ability to open their local phone markets to other 
companies that want to provide competing local phone and other 
communications services. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitacre and Notebaert, in their letter, said the merger ``can  
only increase our willingness to open our local markets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A key component of the merged company's strategy, the chiefs  
said, would be providing long-distance services to local phone 
customers. To obtain FCC permission to do that, the company must 
open its local markets to rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	The chiefs also said the merged company's plan to provide local  
phone and other services in 30 markets outside its combined 
13-state local region also would boost competition. Such a move 
would have SBC-Ameritech competing against fellow Bell companies. 
</P>
<P>
	By merging, the new company will become more efficient and  
financially able to invade markets outside its region, the chiefs 
said. It will also be in a stronger position to provide new 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	Ameritech and SBC representatives said they expect the FCC to  
approve the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The 13 states involved in the proposed merger are Arkansas,  
California, Connecticut, Kansas, Missouri, Nevada, Oklahoma, Texas, 
Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
