<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rise; Dow Up 97.68 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose Wednesday, taking the Dow Jones  
industrial average to a new high, after financial stocks received a 
boost from a cut in interest rates in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow was up 97.68 at 10,182.99,  
taking the index past the closing high of 10,085.31 it set 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators today were also higher. The  
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index shook off early losses and 
was up 16.34 at 2,560.77. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders attributed the rally, which followed a mostly flat  
morning, to the Bank of England's decision to cut short-term 
interest rates to 5.25 percent from 5.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks rose on the expectation that the cut by the  
British central bank would help keep U.S. rates low as well. 
Financial stocks, which benefit from lower rates, rose again after 
leading the market higher Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Citigroup rose 11/16 to 72 3/8 and American Express advanced 3 1/16  
at 129 1/2. Both are Dow components. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Dow stock, Wal-Mart, up 3 3/8 at 100 7/8, rose after reporting  
an 11 percent increase in sales from stores open at least a year 
during March. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the market's gains, traders were uneasy about earnings  
reports, which have started to trickle in. Investors seemed 
reluctant to make big commitments until they have a better idea 
about how companies fared in the just-ended quarter. Companies will 
begin reporting in earnest next week. 
</P>
<P>
	General Electric, which reported earnings in line with analysts'  
expectations, fell 15/16 to 113 9/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell Computer fell 7/8 to 45 9/16 on the Nasdaq market, as  
investors awaited the outcome of the company's analysts' meeting 
Thursday. Intel fell 1/2 to 131 5/8, as microchip stocks dropped in 
response to a disappointing earnings outlook from Advanced Micro 
Devices, which fell 1 to 15 3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	HMOs were among the biggest losers today.  
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street was skittish despite more good news about the  
economy. The Labor Department reported the number of Americans 
claiming unemployment benefits rose last week but remained at less 
than 300,000 for the 10th consecutive week, the longest such 
stretch in 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 14.36 at 1,341.25.  
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues were about even with advancers on the New York  
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 567.9 million shares, up 
slightly from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 6.50 at 622.73 and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 1.24 at 718.54. 

</P>
</TEXT>
