<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury To Decide McDougal Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Prosecutors say Whitewater figure Susan  
McDougal is a selfish woman who broke the law because she hated 
Kenneth Starr. Her lawyer maintains she justifiably refused to 
cooperate with Starr's investigation of President Clinton and his 
wife because of the independent counsel's ``Third Reich'' tactics. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges and countercharges were made Wednesday during  
closing arguments that capped an often contentious five-week 
criminal contempt and obstruction of justice trial for the woman 
who, along with her deceased former husband, James, was the 
Clintons' business partner in the Whitewater real estate dealings. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors were to begin deliberations today.  
</P>
<P>
	The judge's instructions to the panel state that in deciding two  
criminal contempt charges against Mrs. McDougal they may not 
consider whether she believed Starr wanted her to lie in order to 
``get'' the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	But jurors may consider Mrs. McDougal's concerns in deciding the  
single obstruction of justice charge. 
</P>
<P>
	To acquit her on the criminal contempt charges, jurors will have  
to find that Mrs. McDougal had what the judge's instructions call 
an ``innocent reason'' for refusing to answer questions. They also 
will have to find that Mrs. McDougal did not ``act corruptly'' to 
impede justice if they are to acquit her on the obstruction charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the courthouse Wednesday, prosecutors said ``lingering  
questions'' exist in the Whitewater investigation even though Mrs. 
McDougal finally answered during her testimony some of the 
questions she previously had refused to answer. 
</P>
<P>
	In closing arguments, Mrs. McDougal's attorney, Mark Geragos,  
mocked testimony from Whitewater prosecutors who said they only 
wanted the truth from Mrs. McDougal and were not out to get the 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something so offensive for them to say with a straight  
face they wanted to look to see if they could clear the president. 
How dumb do they think we are?'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal, who was convicted of four Whitewater-related  
felonies in 1996, testified that James McDougal later urged her to 
say she had sex with the president to mollify prosecutors eager to 
get Clinton for something and thereby escape further prosecution 
herself. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is something you expect to see in the Third Reich,''  
Geragos told the jury. Mrs. McDougal has denied any intimate 
relationship with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Julie Myers told jurors the suggestion that  
prosecutors wanted Mrs. McDougal to reveal a relationship with the 
president was an ``inflammatory allegation, an astounding 
allegation, an allegation that's absolutely unbelievable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She portrayed Mrs. McDougal as a chronic liar and  
publicity-seeker who reveled in telling a phony story of 
persecution in TV interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	``She craved the spotlight. She enjoyed the attention. And that  
was probably her real reason for not testifying, not those lame 
excuses,'' Myers told jurors. 
</P>
<P>
	Myers noted that Mrs. McDougal said she appreciated Clinton  
providing testimony at her 1996 trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``But when she had information that, according to her, would  
help demonstrate the president's innocence, she selfishly refused 
to provide it to the grand jury or to anyone,'' Myers said. 
</P>
<P>
	She also argued to jurors that they had to weigh Mrs. McDougal's  
credibility against that of two of Starr's prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who is more credible? Two career federal prosecutors versus  
the defendant who is convicted of four felonies?'' Myers asked, 
referring to her own co-workers on Starr's staff, Ray Jahn and 
Hickman Ewing, who testified in the trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
