<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Wins Support in Two Key States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush's Republican  
presidential bid picked up support Thursday in two key states -- New 
Hampshire and Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Hampshire, which holds the first presidential primary,  
Bush was endorsed by Sen. Judd Gregg. And Rep. Jim Nussle said he 
will support Bush in Iowa, where precinct caucuses are the first 
test of the 2000 campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need a leader in this country to renew the national spirit  
and bring pride back to the presidency,'' Gregg said. ``I believe 
George W. will do this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nussle said he liked Bush because, ``He brings people together,  
and he's not a Johnny-One-Note on an issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Polls have shown that Bush and Elizabeth Dole are far ahead of  
any other potential Republican candidates, including Gregg's 
colleague from New Hampshire, Sen. Bob Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who formed a presidential exploratory committee a month  
ago, has raised more than $7 million. He has promised to remain in 
Texas until the Legislature's scheduled adjournment in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Bush took heat in Texas for his stand on gay hate  
crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	The pastor of the world's largest gay church accused Bush of  
pandering to religious conservatives by opposing a proposed 
hate-crimes bill and adoptions by homosexuals. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants the world to believe that he is a compassionate  
conservative. We want the world to know that his compassion does 
not extend to all the citizens of Texas,'' the Rev. Michael Piazza, 
senior pastor of Cathedral of Hope, said on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said his views on both issues have remained consistent -- he  
wants children adopted by married men and women and opposes special 
rights based upon sexual orientation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
