<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Strikes Could Foil GOP Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The still-increasing costs of the U.S.  
confrontation with Yugoslavia are complicating Republican plans to 
deliver an election-year tax cut and their pledge to leave Social 
Security surpluses alone. 
</P>
<P>
	With private and government analysts saying the Kosovo crisis  
could cost the United States $2 billion or more, Congress will have 
to find a way to pay for it. Added to the price tag will be the 
expenses of moving 20,000 refugees to Guantanamo naval base in Cuba 
for what officials say may be a six-month stay. 
</P>
<P>
	The costs are likely to be dwarfed by the $111 billion federal  
surplus the Congressional Budget Office expects this year. But that 
surplus comes entirely from the Social Security trust fund -- money 
congressional Republicans have pledged not to use for anything 
other than helping senior citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're kind of stuck on their own rhetoric here,'' said  
Richard May, a consultant and former GOP staff director of the 
House Budget Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton is expected to propose using expected budget  
surpluses to pay the Yugoslavia expenses. But many Republicans are 
eager to avoid battling him over paying for troops even as they 
remain in the field, and numerous GOP aides predicted that Congress 
would go along and use the surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to be honest, that it's coming straight out of Social  
Security,'' said one Republican Senate leadership aide, speaking on 
condition of anonymity. The aide said Republicans could argue they 
promised to leave Social Security funds alone ``when we were not at 
war. You can't not pay for war.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But that viewpoint is likely to be contested. Conservative Sen.  
Rod Grams, R-Minn., said he would prefer to pay the Yugoslavia 
costs by making across-the-board cuts in other spending, even if it 
means a confrontation with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the one who ordered the bombing,'' Grams said. ``He  
should figure out a way to pay for it without putting the taxpayers 
in a hole.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the Yugoslavia crisis persists and Congress does not pay all  
the bills until fiscal 2000, which begins Oct. 1, Republicans face 
another problem. 
</P>
<P>
	They have promised an $800 billion, 10-year tax cut beginning in  
2000, as the presidential and congressional election campaigns are 
under way. Because virtually all of next year's surplus also will 
come from Social Security, Republicans have been planning a modest 
$15 billion tax cut for 2000 that would be paid for by raising 
revenue and cutting spending elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have been hoping to pump up the 2000 tax cut by  
using new, higher surplus estimates that are expected this summer. 
Concerned that the new surplus estimate for 2000 might be smaller 
than hoped for, Republicans now must worry that the costs of Kosovo 
might absorb much of the new money, leaving less for tax 
reductions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It may imperil the tax cut in the sense that it won't be as  
big as some of us hoped,'' said Stephen Moore, budget analyst for 
the conservative-leaning Cato Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been no official cost estimates yet for the Balkan  
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	One federal official who spoke on condition of anonymity said  
the Pentagon has told White House officials that the price tag 
already has hit $500 million and could reach $2 billion soon -- 
excluding a massive infusion of U.S. ground troops or the costs of 
the refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	The Center for Strategic and Budgetary Assessments, a private  
research organization, estimates the cost of the first two weeks of 
bombing at $450 million to $600 million, said budget analyst Liesl 
Heeter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
