<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Humana Expects Lower Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Shares of Humana Inc. plummeted 38  
percent today after the health maintenance organization warned that 
higher medical costs would mean lower-than-expected earnings for 
the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Louisville, Ky.-based company said operating earnings will  
be between 20 cents and 24 cents per share for the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street analysts were expecting 34 cents, according to a  
survey by First Call. Shares of Humana fell $6.06 to $10.13 in 
heavy trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Humana said it will record $90 million in additional medical  
claims expenses during the first quarter, largely because the HMO 
will have to pay considerably higher rates to hospital chain 
Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. as part of a new contract in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia, which owns more than 20 percent of Florida's  
hospitals, threatened to not contract with Humana in the state 
unless the HMO paid higher fees. But the two companies reached a 
deal last week, just hours before the old contract would have 
expired. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal affected Humana's 1.3 million members in Florida, who  
were in danger of losing coverage for using the 56 Columbia/HCA 
hospitals in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Humana's increased expenses also included $35 million to  
strengthen the company's medical claim reserve and a $5 million 
payment to Columbia/HCA to resolve disputes lingering from the 
companies' previous contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Columbia contract reflects the changed dynamics of our  
industry and the end of an era between Humana and Columbia,'' said 
Gregory H. Wolf, Humana's president and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although its immediate financial impact is adverse, the  
contract represents a new cost factor which we can address in our 
upcoming premium pricing actions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf defended Humana's deal with the hospital chain, saying its  
Florida members would have been ``greatly inconvenienced by a 
termination of services'' with Columbia/HCA and the possible 
disruption of their health care. 
</P>
<P>
	``Notwithstanding the hard decisions we made this quarter, our  
business is fundamentally sound,'' Wolf said. 
</P>
<P>
	Humana, one of the nation's largest managed health care  
companies, has about 6.2 million members in 15 states and Puerto 
Rico. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
