<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HMO Humana Stock Plunges 25 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Humana Inc.'s stock plunged 25 percent Thursday as the health  
maintenance organization warned that a sudden jump in medical costs 
would mean lower profits in the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the rising costs stem from last week's agreement to pay  
15 percent more for hospital care provided by Columbia/HCA 
Healthcare Corp. in Florida, where Humana has 1.3 million members. 
</P>
<P>
	The two health care behemoths settled an acrimonious contract  
dispute last week just hours before Humana members would have loss 
access to Columbia's 56 Florida hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	Humana, based in Louisville, Ky., said operating earnings will  
amount to between 20 cents and 24 cents per share for the first 
quarter, well below Wall Street forecast of about 34 cents, 
according to a survey by First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Humana fell $4 to $12.19 in Thursday's trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Humana said it will pay $90 million in additional medical  
expenses during the first quarter, largely because of the new 
Columbia contract. In past years, Humana only gave single digit 
increases to Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia, which owns more than 20 percent of Florida's  
hospitals, had threatened to not contract with Humana in Florida 
unless the HMO agreed to the 15 percent increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Humana's rising costs also included $35 million to strengthen  
the company's medical claim reserve and a $5 million payment to 
Columbia/HCA to resolve disputes lingering from the previous 
contract between the companies. The new contract is worth about 
$350 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Columbia contract reflects the changed dynamics of our  
industry and the end of an era between Humana and Columbia,'' said 
Gregory H. Wolf, Humana's president and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf said its Florida members will likely face higher premiums  
and a cut in benefits because his company is paying considerably 
more to keep Columbia's hospitals in its network this year. Wolf 
warned that Humana has made no promises to renew the Columbia deal 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf defended Humana's deal with the hospital chain, saying its  
Florida members would have been ``greatly inconvenienced by a 
termination of services'' with Columbia/HCA and the possible 
disruption of their health care. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if Humana had backed down to Columbia, Wolf said: ``We did  
the best thing for our members.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Humana, one of the nation's largest managed health care  
companies, has about 6.2 million members in 15 states and Puerto 
Rico. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 08:15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Missing Atheist Search Intensifies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The search for missing atheist leader Madalyn  
Murray O'Hair has intensified, and the arrests of two former 
cellmates on firearms charges may unlock the mystery of her 1995 
disappearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. O'Hair, whose 1963 Supreme Court case led to the ban on  
organized prayer in public schools, vanished from San Antonio with 
her son, granddaughter and $500,000 in gold coins. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the Easter weekend, the FBI and the Texas Department of  
Public Safety scoured a 5,000-acre ranch in Camp Wood, Texas, about 
100 miles from San Antonio, in a search a DPS spokesman said was 
connected to the disappearances. 
</P>
<P>
	The search apparently turned up nothing, the San Antonio  
Express-News reported today, citing unidentified sources. 
</P>
<P>
	The O'Hairs may have been dismembered and placed in 55-gallon  
metal drums buried at the site, the newspaper also reported. 
Investigators reportedly are focusing on a man who once leased the 
property. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the cellmates who has emerged in the investigation is  
David Waters, a convicted murderer who was the office manager for 
Mrs. O'Hair's organization, American Atheists, before the 
disappearances. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators say the other, Gary Karr, admitted helping to  
dispose of four bodies, one of which may have been a man who 
vanished after going to meet Waters. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI and prosecutors have not publicly linked either Karr or  
Waters to the O'Hair case. 
</P>
<P>
	But Waters' lawyer, Patrick Ganne, said Waters has been accused  
of being involved in the disappearance and denies it. Ganne said a 
federal prosecutor told him: ``Your client could get the death 
penalty. People are rolling over on your client and he better get 
right with God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. O'Hair became famous in the 1960s when she helped wage the  
Supreme Court battle that removed prayer from public schools. She 
later tried to remove the phrase ``In God We Trust'' from U.S. 
currency and stop potential jurors from saying ``so help me God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Mrs. O'Hair, her son Jon Murray and granddaughter Robin  
Murray vanished, authorities wondered whether they were victims of 
foul play or had merely run off with their organization's money. 
Others suggested that Mrs. O'Hair, who was 77 and ailing, had gone 
off to die quietly so Christians wouldn't pray over her. 
</P>
<P>
	Several tantalizing leads went nowhere.  
</P>
<P>
	Then, Karr and Waters were charged last month with violating a  
law barring felons from having weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI agent Bill O'Leary testified at a bail hearing last month  
that Karr, 50, of Novi, Mich., admitted helping to dispose of four 
homicide victims in Texas, including one with its head and hands 
hacked off. 
</P>
<P>
	A headless, handless body was found in a ditch near Dallas in  
1995, and DNA testing identified it as that of con man Danny Ray 
Fry, a friend of Waters'. Investigators and Fry's family say, 
before he disappeared, he had planned to meet Waters in Texas to 
work on a deal involving a lot of money. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Leary did not identify the four victims or mention the  
O'Hairs. But he said Karr flew from Texas to New Jersey with one of 
the four victims before money was wired from a Newark bank to 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Express-News reported that Jon Murray flew to Newark the  
week before he disappeared to expedite the wire transfer of 
$600,000 in atheist funds from New Zealand to San Antonio via New 
Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Leary did not say where the four bodies were buried, and  
Karr's lawyer, David Helfrick, would not comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Waters met Karr when the two were cellmates in Illinois. Waters,  
who had already served time for beating a teen-ager to death, was 
back in prison for assaulting his mother while Karr was in for 
kidnapping and armed robbery. 
</P>
<P>
	Water was released in 1987. He quit as the office manager of  
American Atheists in 1993 and admitted stealing $54,000 from the 
group's accounts. Waters was given probation and ordered to repay 
the money. 
</P>
<P>
	Karr was freed in 1995, four months before the O'Hairs  
disappeared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
