<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Ends Mitsubishi Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A Japanese unit of DaimlerChrysler AG has  
terminated an auto sales support venture with Mitsubishi Motors 
Corp. after a decade-long partnership. 
</P>
<P>
	The venture, Mercedes-Benz Auto Service Inc., was dissolved on  
March 31 when Mitsubishi Motors sold its 49 percent stake to 
DaimlerChrysler, a spokesman for the German automaker said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It had outlived its original purpose,'' said DaimlerChrysler  
Japan Holding Ltd. spokesman Isato Mochida, noting a recent 
expansion in the number of auto dealerships in Japan which handle 
Mercedes cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercedes-Benz Japan Co. and Mitsubishi Motors established the  
joint venture in 1998 to provide marketing support to dealerships 
selling Mercedes autos in the Japanese market. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the dissolution of the joint venture, Mercedes models  
will still be sold through Mitsubishi-linked dealerships, Mochida 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
