<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lottery Jackpot Still Unclaimed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- With no one stepping forward to claim the nation's  
second-largest lottery jackpot, the story going around Boston on 
Thursday was that the winner of the $197 million prize was an 
immigrant cab driver with a family to support. 
</P>
<P>
	That, at least, was what they were saying down at the Town Taxi  
garage, with which the winner -- supposedly a Nigerian immigrant 
known only as ``Patrick'' -- was said to be affiliated. 
</P>
<P>
	According to this rags-to-riches story, he drove a cab 60 hours  
a week, starting before daybreak, to support his family. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kicked back, quiet, never causes a bit of trouble,'' said John  
Ford, vice president of Town Taxi. 
</P>
<P>
	However, no one seemed to know Patrick's full name, where he  
lived or where he went Wednesday morning after driving from a cab 
stand at Logan Airport, a lottery ticket as his only companion. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one has come forward. It's totally speculation,'' said  
Susan Frigoletto, a lottery spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	The six-state Big Game drawing was held Tuesday night. All  
anyone seems to know for certain is that the winning ticket was 
sold at a store near the Town Taxi garage in Boston's Fenway 
neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said Patrick announced he held the winner after another  
cabbie recited the winning combination as cabs were lined up at the 
airport. At least two other taxi drivers supposedly saw his ticket 
before he drove off. 
</P>
<P>
	He never radioed Town Taxi, and dispatchers have not been able  
to reach him. Because he's an independent driver who leases his 
cab, he didn't have to return the car to the garage. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said one of the driver's friends called to say the cabbie  
had won the prize. Other than that, ``we just know he's hiding 
somewhere,'' Ford said. 
</P>
<P>
	The prize, after taxes, will pay either a lump sum of about $70  
million, or 26 annual payments of about $5.1 million. 
Massachusetts, Georgia, Illinois, Maryland, Michigan and Virginia 
take part in the Big Game lottery. 
</P>
<P>
	If the prize is claimed by one person, it will be the largest  
lottery jackpot ever won by an individual in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's biggest jackpot was won by 13 Ohio machinists who  
pooled their money and split a $295 million Powerball prize in 
July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
