<DOCNO> APW19990408.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 01:11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> W. Va. Voters To Decide on Casino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITE SULPHUR SPRINGS, W.Va. (AP) -- There are 650 spacious  
rooms, three golf courses, 20 tennis courts, a spa and even 
whitewater rafting at The Greenbrier resort. It's five stars, all 
the way. 
</P>
<P>
	Surrounding the 6,500 acres of lush opulence nestled in an  
Allegheny Mountain valley is the rest of Greenbrier County, with an 
annual per capita income of $17,559 and an unemployment rate among 
the highest in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	For Donna Linton, shelling out $768 for a night in one of  
resort's rooms, 121 estate houses or 33 suites may be beyond her 
means. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, as a county voter, she will help decide if the resort  
that has catered to politicians, business magnates, the occasional 
movie star and royalty for 221 years becomes even more exclusive -- 
by opening a casino available only for overnight guests. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not opposed to gambling or anything,'' Linton said as she  
walked along a downtown street. ``It might benefit the people 
higher up. Personally, it doesn't matter to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The choice facing Ms. Linton and the rest of the county's 34,700  
residents is between the promise of economic development and the 
side effects of introducing what would be West Virginia's first 
gambling hall. 
</P>
<P>
	Down the street from The Greenbrier's luxurious entrance on West  
Main Street are shuttered storefronts and boarded-up shop windows 
in one block after another. 
</P>
<P>
	With an annual payroll of about $46 million, the resort is the  
county's chief economic engine. The hotel staff grows to 1,600 
during peak seasons, making it by far the largest employer in a 
three-county area. 
</P>
<P>
	Joblessness and low pay are helping buttress economic arguments  
in support of the casino. The hotel says the casino will create 100 
jobs, and would help retain most of the 750 employees let go during 
slow winter months. 
</P>
<P>
	Wanda Lester, 46, an employee at the Stonehouse General Store in  
Lewisburg, 15 miles west of here, said a casino is ``another way to 
bring people to West Virginia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an opportunity to bring more business, more jobs,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents, however, talk about the addictive nature of gambling  
and the potential ill effect on families, including divorce, abuse 
and suicide. They argue crime and unemployment would increase. 
</P>
<P>
	As each drive to broaden gambling ``continues to nudge our  
culture, our culture will be the worse for it,'' said Julian 
Sulgit, co-pastor at the Lewisburg United Methodist Church. 
</P>
<P>
	The Legislature this year ended years of debate on the issue by  
authorizing a referendum on the casino in Greenbrier County. A vote 
has not been scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure authorizes the Lottery Commission to issue one  
license for a historic resort -- and only The Greenbrier, which is 
listed as a National Historic Landmark, fits the description. 
</P>
<P>
	The casino is expected to gross about $11 million a year,  
according to a Tax Division estimate. The Greenbrier would pay 
about $4.2 million in taxes and $740,000 to the state Lottery 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The remaining $6 million would go to the hotel, which estimates  
it will cost about $5.9 million to operate a casino. That leaves a 
$150,000 profit. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenbrier County would receive 4 percent of the gross proceeds,  
which County Commission President Woody Hanna said is ``not an 
extreme amount of money'' for the county's annual budget of less 
than $4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, a 2 percent tax on the casino's gross proceeds, included  
in the legislation authorizing the referendum, would pump $70,000 
into White Sulphur Springs' coffers. 
</P>
<P>
	Christine Wood, who owns The Tansy Shop, a clothing and antiques  
consignment store in Lewisburg, opposes relying on casinos for 
dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm personally against it,'' she said. ``Gambling in general  
creates an atmosphere and a situation where people would be 
vulnerable to it. There's enough with the lottery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A group of about 25 county residents has formed West Virginia  
Families Against Casino Gambling to consider ways to bar a casino. 
</P>
<P>
	For James Jones, the 33-year-old owner of Jones Hardware, the  
choice isn't easy: ``I'm religious, but at the same time, I think 
it's going to be a positive job source.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
