<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Major Ice Shelves Melting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Global warming has speeded the melting of two  
Antarctic ice shelves, which lost nearly 1,100 square miles of area 
in the last year, U.S. and British researchers say. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers at the University of Colorado and the British  
Atlantic Survey in Cambridge say regional warming has increased the 
annual melt season by up to three weeks over the past two decades, 
putting the Larsen B and Wilkins shelves on the Antarctic Peninsula 
in ``full retreat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Satellite photos show the Larsen B ice shelf has continued to  
crumble after an initial small retreat in the spring of 1998, the 
researchers said Wednesday. Since November, another 660 square 
miles of shelf area caved away. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side of the peninsula, the Wilkins ice shelf  
retreated nearly 420 square miles in early March 1998, said Ted 
Scambos, a research associate at the University of Colorado at 
Boulder's National Snow and Ice Data Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``The radar images showed a large area of completely shattered  
ice, indicating an ice front 35 kilometers (21 miles) back from its 
previous extent,'' said Scambos. 
</P>
<P>
	He said thousands of small icebergs had appeared, suggesting  
``that the shelves are essentially broken up in place and then 
flushed out by storms or currents afterward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Vaughan, a researcher with British Antarctic Survey, said  
ice shelves in the area have been in retreat for 50 years but those 
losses have only included about 2,700 square miles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Within a few years, much of the Wilkins ice shelf will be  
gone,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Vaughan said the meltdown has few implications for the  
environment. Birds and animals are not known to rely on the ice 
shelves and there would be no increase in sea levels ``because an 
ice shelf is floating anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since the 1940s, British researchers have reported an increase  
in mean annual temperature in the Antarctic of 4.5 degrees 
Fahrenheit. Summer temperatures now approach, and sometimes exceed 
32 degrees Fahrenheit. 
</P>
<P>
	Ice shelves are floating plates of ice that are still attached  
to continents, which form when large glaciers flow toward the ocean 
in polar areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Larsen B is about 2,700 square miles, the size of Delaware.  
Wilkins is nearly twice that size. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 06:02:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Strikes Yugoslav Armor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO is taking the fight in Yugoslavia to Serb  
military forces in the field, striking armored vehicles with ``tank 
killer'' A-10 warplanes that may be re-enforced in the days ahead. 
But there is growing Pentagon concern that ethnic Albanian refugees 
could get in the way. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of civilians there that are innocent  
civilians, particularly Kosovar Albanians,'' Maj. Gen. Charles 
Wald, a senior official with the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said 
Wednesday after Yugoslav authorities sealed off major border points 
in Kosovo to prevent refugee crossings. ``There aren't clear lines 
of where the bad guys are and the friendlies are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department listed nine Serb commanders whose troops  
may have committed war crimes, although U.S. officials said there 
was no specific evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Clinton administration is eager for the release  
of three U.S. soldiers who were captured last week on the 
Kosovo-Macedonia border. A Cypriot mediator was going to Belgrade 
today to consider an apparent offer from Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic to turn over the prisoners of war. 
</P>
<P>
	But Defense Secretary William Cohen declared today that the  
bombing will not be halted in order to secure their release. ``We 
are not going to have Mr. Milosevic ... use them to cause any 
cessation of hostilities. We are going to continue our campaign 
effort,'' he said on NBC's ``Today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They should be returned immediately. ... There can be no  
conditions attached to their release,'' Cohen said, echoing 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate to give anybody false hopes, but I think it is useful  
that the acting president of Cyprus is going there,'' Albright said 
Wednesday night on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' program. ``I would 
like to see them home. They are very brave Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spyros Kyprianou, speaker in the Cypriot parliament, was  
undertaking the mission for the release of Army Staff Sgt. Andrew 
A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; Spc. Steven M. Gonzalez, 21, of 
Huntsville, Texas, and Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of 
Smiths Creek, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials maintain the reconnaissance team was abducted  
illegally by Serb forces, who claimed the men had crossed into 
Yugoslavia territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Although NATO airstrikes won't come to a halt during Kyprianou's  
mission, the Pentagon suggested the allied forces can ensure his 
safe passage to Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Serb forces apparently shot down an unmanned U.S.  
Army reconnaissance aircraft over Kosovo in the second NATO 
aircraft loss since airstrikes began March 24. The first occurred 
March 27 when an F-117A stealth fighter-bomber went down outside 
Belgrade after it apparently was struck by a missile, although it's 
still under investigation. The pilot was rescued. 
</P>
<P>
	The twin-engine, unmanned aircraft, known as a Hunter, is used  
as a surveillance aid that can transmit real-time video images to 
battlefield commanders. It is smaller and less sophisticated than 
the Predator, the other U.S. unmanned surveillance aircraft flying 
over Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon is investigating the cause of the crash of the  
$300,000 to $350,000 drone. A defense official, speaking on 
condition of anonymity, said it appeared the Hunter was shot down. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO airstrikes, taking advantage of clear weather, began  
intensifying this week on Serb troops, tanks, armored vehicles and 
artillery in Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians remain under attack. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been performing operations in what we call the  
engagement zone,'' said Wald, vice director for strategic plans and 
policy for the Joint Chiefs of Staff. 
</P>
<P>
	An A-10 ``tank killer'' scored hits for the first time, hitting  
a column of armored vehicles, Wald said. Navy fighters from the USS 
Roosevelt aircraft carrier in the Adriatic Sea joined the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO planes also hit more fuel and ammunition dumps, roads,  
bridges, communications facilities, command and control sites, and 
barracks, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're taking the fight right to where they live,'' Wald said.  
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's supreme commander, has  
indicated he may ask for a relatively small number of additional 
aircraft, including more A-10s and refueling aircraft, a defense 
official said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Albanian government has given its approval for basing 24  
U.S. Army Apache helicopter gunships on its territory for missions 
over Kosovo, but the Army says it will take more than a week to get 
them there from Germany because of time needed to assemble support 
personnel and ground rockets, and the strain refugee relief is 
putting on the air transport system in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Sen. Bob Dole, who served Clinton as an envoy in  
Yugoslavia, said Wednesday he could not understand why it was 
taking so long to get Apaches in place and that it appeared 
military leaders were generally running into some political 
interference. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview, he said the U.S.-led NATO effort was suffering  
from poor preparation but appeared finally to be achieving some 
goals. But he also questioned why Clinton would rule out U.S. 
ground troops -- ``telegraph your punches'' -- at the outset of the 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Former President Gerald Ford said miscalculations by the White  
House have made the use of ground troops in Kosovo the only option 
short of NATO's defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration overemphasized the power of  
airstrikes and underestimated the magnitude of the humanitarian 
crisis, Ford said in a telephone interview Wednesday from his home 
in Rancho Mirage, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``The net result is they have two choices,'' he said. ``One  
choice is to go all-out and win the war with ground troops, or two, 
to quit and admit defeat.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
