<DOCNO> APW19990408.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 04:34:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A mass of clouds over the eastern Plains and Ohio Valley today  
brought the risk of severe storms, while winter lingered in parts 
of the West. 
</P>
<P>
	Low pressure moving through the Great Lakes toward New England  
should bring clouds and showers to the region, with Maine expected 
to bear the brunt -- including scattered wet snow. 
</P>
<P>
	Skies were expected to be mostly clear elsewhere in the  
Northeast, while partial clouds and isolated afternoon storms were 
forecast in the Southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	A storm system moving out of the central Rockies was expected to  
affect a large area from Kansas and Nebraska to the upper 
Mississippi Valley, reaching the Ohio Valley by evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Thunderstorms, some severe, were expected through the area,  
particularly in Missouri and eastern Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	In the West, widespread precipitation -- including snow in the  
mountains -- was forecast for Washington, Oregon and Northern 
California. The storm system was expected to reach Idaho and Nevada 
by evening. 
</P>
<P>
	The downtown Los Angeles high of 55 on Wednesday was 16 degrees  
below normal and a new record for lowest maximum temperature for 
the date. The old mark of 57 was set in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast in the 80s and 90s in south Texas, the  
Southeast and Atlantic coast as far north as New York City; the 60s 
and 70s from the desert Southwest across the central Plains to the 
eastern Great Lakes; and the 40s and 50s in the rest of the West, 
the northern Plains and New England. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures Wednesday ranged from 96 at Fort Stockton, Texas,  
to 14 at Stanley, Idaho. 
</P>
