<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Surging at Midday / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's benchmark stock index rose above 17,000  
points Friday morning for the first time in more than a year on the 
strength of bullish sentiment and another record finish on Wall 
Street. The dollar advanced against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average gained 230.34 points, or 1.37 percent,  
to 17,077.03 points at the end of the morning session, marking the 
first time since March 1998 that the key index had climbed above 
the 17,000-mark. On Thursday, the average closed up 292.19 points, 
or 1.77 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.18 yen at late morning, up 0.42 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo but below its level of 121.37 in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, continued buying by foreign investors  
helped support share prices, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market's sentiment is bullish due to gains in overseas  
markets (Thursday) and a continued favorable demand and supply 
picture,'' said Hiroichi Nishi, deputy general manager at Nikko 
Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average on Thursday rose 112.39 points,  
or 1.1 percent, to close at 10,197.70. The blue-chip index soared 
past its closing high of 10,085.31 set on Wednesday, marking the 
Dow's third record close this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 10.58 points, or 0.79 percent, to 1,355.65. 
The TOPIX closed up 20.43 points, or 1.54 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, traders said the dollar was higher against  
the yen early Friday in Tokyo, following Thursday's cuts in 
European interest rates, but later turned range-bound amid cautious 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Central Bank cut key interest rates by one-half  
percentage point to 2.5 percent in a measure to stimulate economic 
activity among the 11 nations that adopted the euro earlier this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Typically, countries or regions cut interest rates to spur  
lending and spending in a sluggish or recessionary economy. The 
downside, however, is that the lower rates also reduce the payoff 
on investments in the local currency and assets, making them less 
attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was traded at 130.18 yen at midday, lower than 130.40  
yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.630  
percent from Thursday's finish of 1.600 percent, pushing its price 
down to 101.48 yen from 101.74 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
