<HEADLINE> Mo Vaughn Placed on Disabled List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Mo Vaughn, the $80 million free agent  
signed by the Anaheim Angels, was placed on the 15-day disabled 
list Thursday night because of a sprained left ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	``An injury like that can take anywhere from two weeks to six  
weeks to heal,'' said Dr. Lewis Yocum, the Angels' team 
orthopedist. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughn was injured when he fell into the Cleveland dugout  
chasing a foul pop in the first inning of Tuesday's opener. The 
All-Star first baseman stayed in the game for five innings, but was 
noticeably limping and pulled. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughn has not played since being taken out. After two days with  
no significant improvement, the Angels decided to put him on the 
disabled list. 
</P>
<P>
	First baseman Chris Pritchett was recalled from Triple-A  
Vancouver to take Vaughn's spot on the roster. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughn hit .337 with 40 home runs and 115 RBIs for Boston last  
season, then signed a six-year contract with Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	The Angels, with a long history of injuries to key players, now  
have Vaughn, center fielder Jim Edmonds and shortstop Gary 
DiSarcina on the disabled list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
