<HEADLINE> Pizza Mogul Creating Law School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Former Domino's Pizza mogul Tom Monaghan plans to  
spend $50 million of his pizza fortune to create a new law school 
aimed at producing lawyers sensitive to the moral consequences of 
the law. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will be the West Point for Catholic laity in the  
years to come,'' said Monaghan, who recently sold Domino's Pizza 
for $1 billion. ``This is something I've wanted to do for some 
time, get out of the pizza business and get on to things that are 
more important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Ave Maria School of Law is scheduled to open in the fall of  
2000 in Ann Arbor with about 40 students. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Bork, the conservative legal scholar and one-time nominee  
for the U.S. Supreme Court, has signed on as the first professor. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernard Dobranski, dean of Catholic University's law school in  
Washington, will serve as Ave Maria's dean. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rule of law must be founded in a belief that there is an  
objective, moral order,'' Dobranski said in today's editions of the 
Detroit Free Press. ``This is something no law school does 
effectively.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
