<HEADLINE> Eight Indiana Auto Dealers Sue GM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Eight Indiana auto dealers filed a  
class-action lawsuit Thursday against General Motors Corp., 
alleging that its new marketing plan illegally collects money from 
dealers to boost sales in other parts of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit is the latest volley in a dispute between GM and  
some dealers over how $500 million in U.S. advertising money is 
spent. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit, filed in U.S. District Court in Indianapolis, alleges  
that the automaker is using ``funds not belonging to it to 
advertise new General Motors products outside the area from which 
they were collected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The real question hinges on whose money is it?'' said Ron  
Smith, an attorney representing the Indiana dealers. ``It's a 
diversion of money without any local (dealer) control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana GM dealers have run joint advertising campaigns since  
the 1970s to supplement each dealer's individual advertisements. 
</P>
<P>
	Such ad groupings -- there are about 900 such groupings  
nationwide -- were financed by payments member dealers made when 
purchasing new vehicles from GM. By the late 1980s, the assessments 
equaled about 1 percent of the sticker price of cars and trucks 
sold by dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting April 1, GM revamped the program, taking over how the  
money is spent. Among other things, GM is scaling back the number 
of advertising agencies used for local-advertising programs 
nationwide from about 60 to five or six. 
</P>
<P>
	GM also wants to spend more on advertising in areas of the  
country where sales are slow. 
</P>
<P>
	GM disagrees with the position of the auto dealers who filed the  
Indiana lawsuit, company spokeswoman Anne Marie Sylvester said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Various dealer lawsuits have been filed around the country,  
including one by 60 dealers in Illinois. A court settlement in 
Minnesota covered lawsuits filed in that state, western 
Pennsylvania and Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute comes at a time GM is under pressure to improve  
results. Even though the auto market has been strong for most of 
the decade, GM's share of the U.S. market has been steadily 
falling. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
