<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Plan Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- The International Air Transport  
Association has has rejected the revised financial rehabilitation 
plan of debt-laden Philippine Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Documents released Thursday by Manila's Securities and Exchange  
Commission show the industry group rejected the plan because it 
calls for a delay in the payment of some $32 million in IATA fees 
and payments to other airlines for about one year. The IATA wants 
the money sooner. 
</P>
<P>
	In September, IATA suspended cash-strapped Philippine Airlines'  
membership after it failed to pay its dues. The suspension resulted 
in all but one of IATA's 231 members refusing to accept transfer 
passengers carrying PAL's tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	Mired in debts of over $2.2 billion, the airline presented a  
revised rehabilitation plan to the SEC last month. The plan has 
already been tentatively approved by the airline's major creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippine Airlines' monthly billing arrears with IATA's members  
averaged $5 million, but a pilots' strike in June caused PAL to 
book thousands of passengers onto other airlines, which caused 
billing arrears to soar to record levels. 
</P>
<P>
	Being kept out of IATA could hinder PAL from securing transfer  
agreements for passengers and cargo with other airlines since IATA 
acts as clearinghouse for such ticketing and billing arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	IATA said that as a non-member, PAL could not ``as a practical  
matter provide such services to their customers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Approval of PAL's rehabilitation plan depends on the infusion of  
$200 million in fresh equity, which would give the new investor 
group 90 percent ownership in the carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL closed operations in September because of labor and  
financial problems. It resumed domestic flights a month later, and 
has gradually restored limited overseas services since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 11:05:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SSI Benefits Narrow Income Gap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Social Security benefits significantly help  
narrow the income disparities between women and men in old age, 
according to a study. 
</P>
<P>
	``Social Security cuts about in half the gap in poverty rates  
between elderly women and elderly men,'' said Robert Greenstein, 
executive director of the Center for Budget and Policy Priorities. 
</P>
<P>
	The nonprofit research center used 1997 Census data to measure  
the impact Social Security benefits have on lifting elderly 
Americans' incomes above the federal poverty level. 
</P>
<P>
	Elderly individuals were considered to be poor in 1997 if they  
had income below $7,698 a year; or below $9,712 for elderly 
couples. 
</P>
<P>
	Women get a particularly good deal from Social Security, the  
study found. Although women pay 38 percent of all Social Security 
payroll taxes, they get 53 percent of benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	In part, that's because women live longer than men, and Social  
Security benefits rise each year to keep up with inflation. Also, 
women make up the bulk of those who collect the special Social 
Security benefits that spouses, widows and widowers are entitled to 
receive even if they never worked themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Social Security generally provides bigger retirement checks to  
people who earned more during their working lives, and men tend to 
earn more than women. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the program somewhat mitigates that by taking into  
account a higher percentage of low-wage workers' earnings when 
calculating their retirement benefits -- and that does help women. 
</P>
<P>
	Those factors mean Social Security narrows the gap between the  
poverty rates for elderly men and women -- compared with what senior 
citizens would have if they didn't get any Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	Without monthly Social Security checks, 52.6 percent of women  
ages 65 and older would be poor, compared with 40.8 percent of men 
-- a gap of 11.8 percent, the study found. But with Social Security, 
14.7 percent of elderly women were poor, compared with 8.2 percent 
of men -- cutting the old-age poverty gap between the sexes to 6.5 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Women who are not married when they are elderly do not benefit  
as much, Greenstein said. Even with Social Security benefits, the 
poverty rate among elderly widows is 20.3 percent, and for single 
and divorced women it is 27 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The study also found that black and Hispanic Americans draw a  
larger percentage of their old-age income from Social Security than 
whites. Elderly blacks rely on Social Security the most, getting on 
average 43.4 percent of their income from the retirement program, 
compared with 41.4 percent for Hispanics and 35.8 percent for 
whites. 
</P>
<P>
	Whites are more likely to have retirement income other than  
Social Security. For example, they're more than twice as likely as 
minorities to have personal investments, the study found. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the study found that without income from Social  
Security, 47.6 percent of elderly Americans -- 15.3 million people -- 
would have been poor in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Social Security benefits, however, cut that poverty rate by  
three-quarters, to 11.9 percent, or 3.8 million senior citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 15:05:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Futures Hit Three-Year Lows  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Coffee futures tumbled Thursday to 3-year lows amid fears  
Colombia will devalue its currency, creating a flood of cheap 
exports. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy futures continued their sharp retreat, while cocoa  
plunged. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee fell for a second day on the Board of Trade of the City  
of New York, losing nearly 5 percent in a single session, amid 
growing complaints from Colombian officials that exports are being 
hurt by an overvalued peso. 
</P>
<P>
	Since coffee is sold for dollars, producers with a weaker local  
currency often step up sales when the dollar is rising. Devaluing a 
currency would immediately cause the U.S. dollar to jump in value 
and provide greater profits to Colombian exporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombia is the single-largest producer of the gourmet-blend  
arabicas favored by American and European consumers and the 
second-largest producer of coffee in the world behind Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said a decision to devalue the Colombian peso could  
produce a ripple effect in other Central American economies, 
prompting other devaluations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colombian talks come at a time when U.S. markets are being  
flooded with cheap coffee as a result of large harvests in Brazil 
and elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Supplies in U.S. exchange-approved warehouses jumped again  
Wednesday, rising by 3,750 bags weighing 132 pounds each to 254,177 
bags. Another 40,000 bags were waiting to be inspected. 
</P>
<P>
	Further pressuring prices Thursday were unconfirmed reports that  
Ethiopia had lowered prices on all grades of its coffee. 
</P>
<P>
	Arabica coffee for May delivery fell $4.90 to $97.70 a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil and refined crude products fell for a second day in  
futures trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange amid increasing 
skepticism about whether world oil producers will honor commitments 
to reduce output. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude retreated below $16 a barrel, giving back more of the  
gains that came after the Organization of Petroleum Exporting 
Countries and other oil producers agreed to cut 2.1 million barrels 
daily from world production beginning a week ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say it may take months to determine whether producers  
are complying, and many market participants are noting that the 
producers never fully met a round of cuts agreed to a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, several key refineries on the West Coast were coming  
back to full service, easing fears about spot gasoline shortages 
across the country before the heavy summer driving period. 
</P>
<P>
	Contracts for May delivery of light, sweet crude fell 20 cents  
to $15.83 a barrel; May unleaded gasoline fell 0.99 cent to 49.52 
cents a gallon; May heating oil fell 0.43 cent to 40.84 cents a 
gallon; May natural gas rose 3.6 cents to $2.060 for each 1,000 
cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures plunged to their lowest in five years on the New  
York Board of Trade amid reports of active selling out of Ghana, as 
world producers rush to unload plentiful crops before prices fall 
even farther. 
</P>
<P>
	With months to come before chocolate makers begin gearing up for  
a new candy season, analysts say the outlook for higher prices 
</P>
<P>
	May cocoa fell $55, or 4.8 percent, to $1,079 a ton.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 19:52:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Suspends Toronto's Johnson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Toronto Maple Leafs forward Mike Johnson has been  
suspended by the NHL for two games without pay for elbowing Ottawa 
Senators defenseman Janne Laukkanen in the head. 
</P>
<P>
	Laukkanen suffered a concussion from the blow, delivered in  
Toronto's 4-2 win over the Senators on Wednesday night. Johnson 
received a five-minute major penalty on the play. 
</P>
<P>
	Both players were to miss Thursday night's game in Ottawa.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson will also sit out Toronto's game against Florida on  
Saturday. Based on his $440,000 salary, he will forfeit more than 
$4,500. 
</P>
</TEXT>
