<DOCNO> APW19990408.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 05:05:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Critics Fault Anti-Smoking Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Critics are calling on Philip Morris Cos. to  
dump its anti-smoking commercials and to give the money to an 
independent group that can run harder-edged ads aimed at 
youngsters. 
</P>
<P>
	But Philip Morris, the world's biggest tobacco company and the  
maker of the best-selling Marlboro cigarette brand, said Wednesday 
it would continue running its own ads which carry the theme 
``Think. Don't Smoke.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ellen Merlo, a spokesman for Philip Morris' domestic tobacco  
arm, said the company feels the ``peer pressure message is one that 
is valid in reaching this group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't think there is any one single approach and we believe  
the approach that we have taken to the issue is a valid and 
worthwhile way of communicating this issue,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The critics, representing public health officials from 17 states  
and the American Cancer Society, said Wednesday the Philip Morris 
anti-smoking ads are not strong enough to convince youngsters most 
likely to start smoking to decide against doing so. 
</P>
<P>
	Some critics said the campaign is diluting the impact of  
stronger commercials such as one from California that shows a 
smoker inhaling a cigarette through a hole in her throat. 
</P>
<P>
	Gregory Connolly, director of the Massachusetts Health  
Department's tobacco control program, said he worries the Philip 
Morris approach ``could persuade policy-makers not to run the 
hard-hitting stuff'' as decisions are being made on a $1.45 billion 
national anti-smoking campaign expected to begin later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris announced last December that it would spend more  
than $100 million a year on a campaign to discourage youngsters 
from smoking. 
</P>
<P>
	About 70 percent of the first year's budget was earmarked for  
anti-smoking advertising. The ads showed groups of youngsters on 
the bus, at school and on a stairway outdoors talking about why 
they choose not to smoke. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't need to smoke to prove myself,'' a girl says in one  
ad. ``My coolness is not on trial here.'' A boy in another ad says 
``We don't have to smoke to be different. Being ourselves is 
enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But a new study conducted on behalf of three states that have  
been running their own anti-smoking campaigns suggested youngsters 
found the Philip Morris ads less compelling than ads from the 
states which often depicted the consequences of smoking in stark 
terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the ads shown to about 120 youngsters in 20 different  
groups was a California commercial that showed a woman smoking a 
cigarette through a hole in her throat and a Massachusetts ad that 
showed an actor who once played the Marlboro Man as he lay dying of 
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	The authors of the study, Teenage Research Unlimited, said teens  
rated the two ads from Philip Morris and a third ad from the state 
of Arizona called ``I Decide'' among the lowest every time. It said 
some teens said the ads failed to give them any good reasons not to 
smoke. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't say these ads (from Philip Morris) are terrible. We  
say they are not the kind of ads that are hard-hitting and are 
found to be effective with younger people,'' said Randy Schwartz, 
director of the division of community and family health for the 
state of Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwartz is also a co-chairman of a group that includes Maine,  
Massachusetts and 15 other states in an effort to stop smoking. 
</P>
<P>
	On behalf of the group, Schwartz wrote the head of Philip Morris  
Cos., Geoffrey Bible, asking the company to discontinue the ads and 
turn over funding for the campaign to an independent entity that 
would air ads more like those that the states were sponsoring. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
