<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Badge Is Favored in Wood Memorial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Joe Aquilino knows the streets of New York well.  
If he ends up traveling to the Kentucky Derby, the trainer will 
need directions. 
</P>
<P>
	Aquilino, a retired fireman from Engine House 234 in Brooklyn,  
trains Badge, the early-morning 3-1 favorite for Saturday's 
$600,000 Wood Memorial at Aqueduct. 
</P>
<P>
	A win, or at least a strong showing in the 1 1/8-mile Wood, would  
give the 62-year-old Aquilino his first shot at the Kentucky Derby 
May 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this business, getting a horse to the Derby is everybody's  
dream,'' Aquilino said Thursday. ``It just might be a 
once-in-a-lifetime thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Badge has won four of his last five races, including a 7 1/2-length  
victory in the Gotham Stakes March 21. Although he's not yet in the 
class of such top Derby contenders as Bob Baffert's duo of General 
Challenge and Prime Timber, or Carl Nafzger's Vicar, the 3-year-old 
son of Air Forbes Won is a horse to watch. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you saw the Gotham, you have to believe Badge won't have  
any problem getting two turns,'' Aquilino said. ``When we ran him 
the last time around two turns (Jan. 28), he ran third and seemed 
to flatten out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it was discovered Badge had a lung infection, which was  
treated with antibiotics, and the colt won his next race, the Best 
Turn Feb. 27. 
</P>
<P>
	``He still wasn't himself that day,'' said Aquilino, who worked  
for trainers John Tammaro, Howie Tesher and Frank LaBochetta while 
he was a fireman. ``But in the Gotham, he was 100 percent and you 
saw what he was able to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Badge, owned by Southbelle Stables and named for the Eric  
Clapton song ``Badge,'' will be ridden by Shaun Bridgmohan. The 
colt tops a mediocre field of 11 3-year-olds, all of whom will 
carry 123 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	In 74 previous runnings, the Wood winner has gone on to win the  
Kentucky Derby 11 times, the last being Pleasant Colony in 1981. 
The last Wood entrant to win the Derby was the Nick Zito-trained Go 
for Gin in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Zito, who will saddle Wondertross in Saturday's Blue Grass  
Stakes at Keeneland, has two horses in Saturday's Wood -- 
second-choice Adonis (4-1) and the Rick Pitino-owned The Groom is 
Red (15-1). 
</P>
<P>
	The field, from the rail out, is: Badge (3-1, Bridgmohan);  
Karly's Harley (8-1, Edgar Prado); Bugatti (15-1, Robbie Davis); 
Adonis (4-1, Jorge Chavez); Cliquot (9-2, Rene Douglas); The Groom 
is Red (15-1, Craig Perret); David (12-1, Aaron Gryder); Robin 
Goodfellow (20-1, Joe Bravo); Machine To Tower (20-1, Cornelio 
Velasquez); Best of Luck (12-1, Jean-Luc Samyn), and Swamp (6-1, 
Richard Migliore). 
</P>
<P>
	The Wood is one of three major Derby prep races Saturday. The  
others are the Blue Grass, with Wondertross the favorite over 
Florida Derby winner Vicar in an eight-horse field, and the 
Arkansas Derby, where Answer Lively is favored over Ecton Park in a 
seven-horse field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
