<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cincinnati Considers Stronger Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A reform movement early this century persuaded  
voters to toss out corrupt political bosses and hire professional 
city managers -- the ``weak-mayor'' form of government common across 
the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Next month, in a vote closely watched by other cities,  
Cincinnati residents will decide whether to give the mayor more 
clout. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the current system, the City Council member with the most  
votes assumes the largely ceremonial role of mayor. Under the 
proposed amendment, the mayor would be elected directly and would 
have authority to veto council actions. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's biggest cities follow the ``strong-mayor''  
approach, but the council-manager model -- also used in Phoenix, 
Dallas and San Diego -- is much more prevalent. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Cincinnati, Miami and Worcester, Mass., have proposed  
switching to the strong-mayor form of government. Oakland, Calif., 
recently made the change. 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati Mayor Roxanne Qualls calls the current system ``a  
lottery, very much like Russian roulette.'' There's no guarantee 
the top vote-getter will have the personality, background or party 
affiliation voters or the council want for the position. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we've observed is that with a lot of the mayors, it seems  
to be a little easier to be more innovative and get more 
accomplished if you have a strong mayor,'' said Katie Cullen of the 
U.S. Conference of Mayors. 
</P>
<P>
	But others suggest the change could generate unnecessary  
headaches. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this passes, the bickering will be like World War III,''  
said Tom Luken, a former council member, mayor and congressman. 
</P>
<P>
	The election of former California Gov. Jerry Brown as Oakland's  
first strong mayor shows the potential. Just several months after 
taking office, Brown had fired three city department heads, 
including the police chief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 12:15:25 </DATE_TIME>
