<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philip Morris Fires Miller Exec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Philip Morris Cos. is putting a veteran from its  
Kraft Foods division in charge of struggling Miller Brewing Co. and 
installed two top marketing executives from its industry-leading 
tobacco business to help. 
</P>
<P>
	John D. Bowlin, who has run Kraft Foods International since  
August 1996 and has 20 years experience at various Philip Morris 
food businesses, was named Wednesday as chief executive of Miller, 
the nation's second biggest brewer. 
</P>
<P>
	He replaced John N. MacDonough, who was fired after more than  
six years leading Miller. MacDonough, 55, had joined 
Milwaukee-based Miller from rival Anheuser-Busch Cos. in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowlin, 48, also gets the title of president, a post that had  
been vacant, while MacDonough's job as Miller chairman is being 
eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be Bowlin's second tour of duty at Miller, where he was  
president and chief operating officer under MacDonough for about 17 
months in 1993 and 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Emanuel Goldman, who follows Philip Morris for the investment  
firm Merrill Lynch, said Bowlin laid the groundwork for a 
turnaround in the Kraft Foods business and is highly regarded in 
the food industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes at Miller come after a year in which its profits  
edged up 1.3 percent to $451 million even as sales fell 2.3 percent 
to $4.1 billion and its share of the U.S. beer market dropped 0.7 
percentage points to 21.0 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Shepard, executive editor at Beer Marketer's Insights, said  
Miller's sales volume and market share has fallen for four years in 
a row. 
</P>
<P>
	``Philip Morris management hasn't been exactly happy with the  
evolution of Miller from a volume or profitability standpoint,'' 
said Goldman. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Miller has also suffered numerous advertising missteps  
even as Anheuser-Busch was scoring with its frog and lizard ads for 
Budweiser, the category leader, and with a succession of popular 
ads for Bud Light. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a month ago, Miller dumped a quirky and frequently maligned  
advertising campaign aimed at recruiting more young adult drinkers 
to its flagship Miller Lite brand. The campaign, which featured 
outrageous situations like a magician's assistant who wound up with 
a rat under her armpit, disappointed distributors who complained it 
didn't help them sell beer. 
</P>
<P>
	The new campaign echoes Lite's ``Tastes Great, Less Filling''  
campaign that helped establish light beers as a significant part of 
the beer industry in the mid-1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	The new ads use retired sports stars like baseball's Mitch  
Williams and Lee Smith and other celebrities debating whether the 
hops or the smoothness account for Lite's taste. 
</P>
<P>
	Under MacDonough's tenure, Miller acquired Molson USA and  
introduced brands like Red Dog and the ice beers Icehouse and 
Molson Ice. 
</P>
<P>
	But he also unsuccessfully tried to launch a new beer called  
Miller as the company's flagship brand. The beer is still available 
in select markets but fell short of expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Also dismissed on Wednesday were Miller's top marketing officer  
John P. Rooney and sales chief Christopher R. Moore. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris named two marketing executives from its domestic  
tobacco business to the top marketing and sales posts at Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Mikulay, 47, becomes senior vice president of marketing  
at Miller while James R. Mortenson was named Miller's vice 
president of sales and distribution. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller executives said Wednesday they viewed the selection of  
new executive talent being installed at Miller as a sign of Philip 
Morris' commitment to the brewer. Rumors have periodically 
circulated in recent years that Philip Morris would sell Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller recently acquired several regional beer brands, including  
Hamm's, when Pabst Brewing acquired Stroh Brewing Co., and it has 
contracts to make beer for Pabst under a deal that should keep its 
facilities busier than ever. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
