<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Continues Kosovo Air Assault  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Pressing on with its air campaign,  
NATO jets struck on Orthodox Good Friday against an oil storage 
depot east of Belgrade. Other attacks were reported near a Serbian 
television relay station near Jagodina and along an electric power 
relay system near Valjevo, 15 miles south of Belgrade. The attack 
appeared to make good on a NATO threat to go after Serbian 
television sites for allegedly spreading ``lies'' about the 
U.S.-led air assault. 

</P>
<P>
	Ground-Troop Option Gaining Support  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nearly all the lawmakers who accompanied  
Defense Secretary William Cohen to Europe for consultations on NATO 
airstrikes and to visit U.S. troops say the United States should 
not rule out a possible ground offensive in Kosovo. Cohen, whose 
delegation returned late Thursday after visits with NATO officials 
in Belgium and with American troops in Italy and Germany, said he 
would take that message to President Clinton. He reiterated the 
administration's position that ground troops would not be necessary 
to win the conflict against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's 
forces. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton, China Premier Meet Press  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In rejecting U.S. demands that China renounce  
the use of force against Taiwan, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji found 
an improbable ally -- Abraham Lincoln. Zhu recalled that Lincoln had 
resorted to force almost 140 years ago against secessionist 
Southerners to maintain the unity of the United States. No issue 
has caused more strains in U.S.-China relations than Taiwan and, in 
his joint news conference with President Clinton on Thursday, Zhu 
said he feared that China would be in a ``perpetual state of 
separation from the motherland'' if China were to rule out the use 
of force against the anti-communist bastion. 

</P>
<P>
	US Senator: Trial Benefits Cambodia  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Cambodia's plan to try a former Khmer  
Rouge leader with help from foreign judges and prosecutors can 
strengthen the country's institutions while providing 
accountability for the group's genocidal rule, a U.S. senator said 
Thursday. Sen. John Kerry, a Massachusetts Democrat, described the 
plan as a ``win-win'' situation. Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen 
agreed during a meeting Tuesday night with Kerry to have foreign 
participation in Cambodia's trial of former guerrilla commander Ta 
Mok. Human rights groups, the United Nations, the United States and 
other countries have said Cambodia's judicial system has neither 
the competence nor the political independence to hold a credible 
trial that will fully and fairly investigate Khmer Rouge crimes. 

</P>
<P>
	Crackdown on Illegal Viagra Sales  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Workers at two Manhattan businesses were  
arrested Thursday on federal charges they sold Viagra without a 
prescription, part of an effort to curb illegal sales of the male 
impotence drug. Yao Shen, Victor Yin and Wei Zhang were brought to 
U.S. District Court in Manhattan, where lawyers arranged their 
release on bail after a brief appearance before a U.S. Magistrate 
Judge. ``We're seeing more and more cases that involve Viagra,'' 
said a special agent in charge of the FDA office in Jersey City, 
N.J. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM To Offer All PC Products Online  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM plans to offer its entire PC product line  
for sale over the Internet as it goes directly after the small 
business and consumer market. Code-named Project Odyssey, IBM's 
plan focuses on luring small businesses and consumers as new 
customers, a company spokesman said. IBM already enjoys substantial 
revenues from its Web site -- an estimated $38 million a day. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Surging at Midday  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's benchmark stock index rose above 17,000  
points Friday morning for the first time in more than a year. The 
Nikkei gained 230.34 points to end the morning trading session at 
17,077.03 points. In New York Thursday, the Dow gained 112.39 to 
10,197.70, a record high. 

</P>
<P>
	SuperSonics 87, Trail Blazers 86  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Vin Baker, returning after missing 10 games with  
a thumb injury, scored 15 points as Seattle beat Portland 87-86 
Thursday night. The Sonics were 4-6 without Baker after going 12-11 
with him. Gary Payton had 20 points and Detlef Schrempf added 17 to 
help the SuperSonics beat the Trail Blazers for the seventh 
straight time in Seattle, including twice this season. Rasheed 
Wallace scored 14 points for the Blazers. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
</P>
