<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unabomber's Brother Meets Victim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) -- During the long drive home after the  
trial of the Unabomber, David Kaczynski stopped in Salt Lake City 
to have breakfast with a man his brother tried to kill. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Wright, the victim of the bomber's 11th attack, still picks  
pieces of shrapnel out of his face a decade later. He agreed to 
meet Kaczynski for breakfast that morning, and on Thursday the two 
met again -- this time, to demonstrate the power of forgiveness. 
</P>
<P>
	``The typical stereotype ... states that the victim and the  
perpetrator's family have to hate each other,'' Wright said at an 
anti-violence conference. ``It's my belief that there's an 
incredible amount of compassion and understanding that can be 
provided through a friendship with a person from the other side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was Kaczynski, an Albany, N.Y., social worker, who first  
tipped the FBI to the possibility that his brother, Theodore, might 
be the anti-technology terrorist known as the Unabomber. 
</P>
<P>
	In 16 attacks between 1978 and 1995, the Unabomber killed three  
people, injured 29 others and permanently changed such routine 
activities as opening the mail and boarding a plane. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI agents raided Theodore Kaczynski's remote Montana cabin in  
1996 and found a trove of damning evidence, including a bomb. He 
pleaded guilty in a Sacramento, Calif., federal court on Jan. 21, 
1998, and was sentenced to life in prison without the possibility 
of parole. 
</P>
<P>
	David Kaczynski reached out to his brother's victims, expressing  
his family's grief at the suffering they had endured. 
</P>
<P>
	Mostly, Kaczynski said, he wrote letters to victims and their  
families. But he had only a telephone number for Wright, so he 
called. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was so afraid I would get this blast of anger, and instead I  
got this kindness and encouragement,'' Kaczynski said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright was wounded in 1987 by a bomb disguised as a piece of  
wood left outside a Salt Lake City computer store. The attack 
generated the infamous sketch of a mustachioed suspect in a hooded 
sweatshirt and aviator sunglasses. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaczynski said Wright was so supportive that he was almost  
afraid to call him again. He worried that Wright might not be in 
such a forgiving mood the next time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to save this beautiful gift he had given me,''  
Kaczynski said. 
</P>
<P>
	But as Kaczynski drove his battered white pickup truck back  
across the country after the trial, he called Wright and suggested 
they meet. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talked for a while and I just had the sense of being  
immediately comfortable,'' Kaczynski said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright said he was raised in a family where ``if you apologize,  
that's it -- you have to accept it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That and the call itself led Wright to believe that Kaczynski  
possessed a quality he seeks in friends: honor. The impression was 
reinforced at their breakfast meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really felt I had a genuine person across from me, who was  
concerned with things outside of himself,'' Wright said. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, Kaczynski and Wright called for new bridges -- not  
merely reconciliation between victims and the families of 
perpetrators, but an understanding that violence makes victims of 
everyone. 
</P>
<P>
	``Forgiveness is a very complicated word,'' Wright said. ``I  
prefer to believe it means letting go -- not unconditionally 
accepting an act and not forgetting the event or the family member 
who is no longer with you, but allowing yourself to love 
yourself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The conference at Naugatuck Valley Community-Technical College  
is organized annually in the memory of Melanie Rieger, a teen-ager 
killed by her former boyfriend. 
</P>
<P>
	Bringing the families of victims and victimizers together is not  
easy, Kaczynski said, but it can lead to wisdom. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the best case, it's wisdom that has gone beyond knowledge  
and become hope,'' he said. ``There is a noble and generous quality 
in the human spirit that tells us that violence and cruelty don't 
have to win out in the end.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
