<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Power Plant Blast Kills 1, Hurts 45 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A thunderous explosion rocked a power plant  
Thursday morning, killing one worker and injuring 45 people, four 
critically. 
</P>
<P>
	The blast tore a huge section from a building holding the six  
coal-fired generators at the Tampa Electric Co. plant on the edge 
of Tampa Bay, two miles from downtown. The explosion was heard at 
least 35 miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I was going to meet my maker or go to hell, and it  
made me want to get right with God,'' said Robert Worley, a worker 
who escaped injury. 
</P>
<P>
	A leak of hydrogen gas was suspected as the cause of the blast,  
which happened as contractors tested a generator following routine 
maintenance, sheriff's deputies said. Hydrogen is used as a coolant 
for the generators. 
</P>
<P>
	TECO spokesman Steve Jenkins said the blast damaged just one of  
the generators. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnny Bass, 52, who worked for a contractor hired to give the  
unit its spring tune-up, was killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 45 injured, at least 35 were taken to hospitals, said  
TECO spokesman Steve Jenkins. Four victims were critically burned. 
Many of the others suffered cuts and smoke inhalation. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant, with a work force of about 250, was shut down after  
the blast. Jenkins said TECO would have to assess the damage before 
deciding when to fire up the plant again. 
</P>
<P>
	Electrical service to customers was not interrupted.  
</P>
<P>
	TECO supplies power for 500,000 customers. The plant accounts  
for about one-third of the utility's generating capacity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
