<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 19:12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miller Eyes Cardinals, Changes Agent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Outside linebacker Jamir Miller changed  
agents. He's hoping he won't have to change teams as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope that the Cardinals are interested in him,'' agent  
Leigh Steinberg said Thursday. ``It's the only team he's been with, 
so I would think that would be our starting point, and only if it 
was impossible to work something out would we take a look at other 
options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller fired agent Steve Baker and hired Steinberg on Wednesday.  
He did not return a telephone call to his home Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, Arizona's first-round draft pick in 1994, made $710,000  
last season while leading the Cardinals with a career-high 150 
tackles. 
</P>
<P>
	As one of the NFL's top young linebackers, the 25-year-old  
former UCLA star went into free agency anticipating that someone 
would offer him close to the $6.5 million-a-year salary of 
Baltimore's Ray Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, teams like Tennessee, Chicago and New England only  
nibbled at the bait. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals offered Miller a $6 million, two-year contract,  
then took back the offer and gave free agent Rob Fredrickson a $7.9 
million, four-year deal that left Miller's future with the team in 
question. 
</P>
<P>
	Fredrickson, who is 6-foot-4 and 240 pounds to Miller's 6-5 and  
260, was a first-round draft pick in 1994 and led the Detroit Lions 
in tackles (116) last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would describe him as confused and frustrated, because he  
felt the process was going to be a rapid one in free agency,'' 
Steinberg said. ``And to sit right there prior to the draft without 
a team was not his goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steinberg, who also represents quarterback Jake Plummer and has  
a good relationship with Arizona's front office, doesn't expect the 
negotiations to pick up steam until after the April 17-18 draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals have the Nos. 8 and 21 picks in the first round,  
and might have a shot at Chris Claiborne of Southern California or 
Andy Katzenmoyer of Ohio State, but they also need help at 
offensive left tackle, fullback and wide receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	After signing Plummer to a four-year contract extension that  
will pay him $13.25 million in bonus and salary this year, hiring 
Fredrickson, and anticipating a $5 million rookie pool after the 
draft, the Cardinals have little room left. 
</P>
<P>
	They could offer Miller either $1.5 million this season or $4  
million over two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to craft the best short-term solution here and maybe  
wait on the massive, long-term contract,'' Steinberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Ferguson, Arizona's vice president of player personnel, said  
the Cardinals expected to lose Miller when they decided to make 
wide receiver Rob Moore the designated franchise player. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've never shut the door on Jamir,'' Ferguson said. ``That's  
No. 1. But certain things have changed. But when you put a player 
out in free agency to start with, like we did, we never really 
thought we'd have an opportunity, even, to maybe bring him back. 
</P>
<P>
	``But the door is there. It's open to a degree, but there's got  
to be a meeting of the minds.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
