<HEADLINE> Stocks Modestly Higher; Dow Up 1.95 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were modestly higher today, with  
investors trading cautiously while they awaited first-quarter 
earnings reports. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up  
1.95 at 10087.26 after rising more than 48 points in earlier 
trading. The Dow closed at a new high of 10,085.31 Wednesday, but 
the overall market was mixed, reflecting a general mood of caution. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, broader stock indicators were up slightly. The  
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index shook off early losses and 
was up 1.27 at 2,545.70. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was uneasy about earnings reports, which have started  
to trickle in, and traders seemed reluctant to make big commitments 
until they have a better idea about how companies fared in the 
just-ended quarter. Companies will begin reporting in earnest next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow component IBM was down 1 7/8 at 184 5/8. General Electric, which  
reported earnings in line with analysts' expectations, fell 15/16 
to 113 9/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Dell Computer were down 7/8 at 45 9/16 on the Nasdaq, as  
investors await the outcome of the company's analysts' meeting 
Thursday. Shares of Intel were down 1/2 to 131 5/8, part of a decline in 
microchip stocks in the wake of a disappointing earnings outlook 
from Advanced Micro Devices, which fell 1 to 15 3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	HMOs were among the biggest losers today.  
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Humana Inc. fell 5 1/2 to 10 11/16 after the Louisville,  
Ky.-based HMO said its first-quarter earnings will fall more than a 
dime short of Wall Street expectations. The company blamed rising 
medical costs. Other HMOs fell in response to Humana's 
announcement, including Pacificare, which fell 4 1/2 63 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street was skittish despite more good news about the  
economy. The nation's biggest retailers, including Wal-Mart, Sears 
and Kmart, reported today their March sales jumped to 
better-than-expected levels. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported the number of Americans claiming  
unemployment benefits rose last week but remained at less than 
300,000 for the 10th consecutive week, the longest such stretch in 
25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 1.39 at 1,328.28.  
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues were about even with advancers on the New York  
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 368.54 million shares, down 
slightly from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 1.54 at 617.77 and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was down 0.52 at 716.78. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
