<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reports: Japan May Dissolve Kokumin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese financial regulators plan to dissolve a  
regional bank swamped with debt as part of a massive cleanup of the 
banking industry, news reports said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Supervisory Agency has found that the Tokyo-based  
Kokumin Bank has a capital deficit of $412 million (50 billion 
yen), Kyodo News service reported, quoting agency sources. 
</P>
<P>
	A capital debt is the depletion of a bank's capital resources to  
the point where its liabilities eclipse its assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless the bank can come up with funds from affiliated firms,  
the FSA and the Financial Reconstruction Commission, another bank 
regulator, will take action, the reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	That would involve either transferring the bank's operations to  
a public bridge bank or nationalizing it through a government 
purchase of its shares, the reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	FSA spokesman Noritaka Ono refused to comment on the report,  
while a statement released by Kokumin said the bank knew nothing of 
the government's plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't heard anything yet from the Financial  
Revitalization Commission or the Financial Supervisory Agency,'' 
the bank's statement said. ``Given that we haven't been informed of 
the result of the inspection, currently the report isn't true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other media, including national broadcaster NHK, also reported  
that officials were moving to dissolve the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank examiners found that Kokumin, with 40 domestic branch  
offices and a total of $4.3 billion on deposit, had amassed a huge 
capital deficit by September 1998, a report in the Nihon Keizai 
business daily said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kokumin Bank's huge prospective losses on its real estate loans  
have come to dominate its loan portfolio, leading the regulatory 
authorities to judge that it is insolvent, reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan is currently struggling to fight its worst recession since  
World War II, with many financial institutions trying to write off 
reams of bad loans left over from the late 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Last October, the FSA shifted the focus of its investigations  
from major banks to Japan's 64 regional banks and 60 second-tier 
regional banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Kokumin Bank will reportedly receive formal notification of the  
agency's findings next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
