<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Police in Brazil arrested a former  
legislator Thursday, hours after he was expelled from Congress 
under suspicion of ordering his predecessor's murder. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chamber of Deputies voted 427-29 that Talvane Albuquerque  
was guilty of ``lack of decorum,'' after a wiretap revealed his 
connections with a hired killer from his home state of Alagoas, in 
Brazil's poor northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	The unusual expulsion late Wednesday makes Albuquerque  
ineligible to hold public office for eight years and strips him of 
immunity from criminal prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrested Albuquerque in connection with the attempted  
murder of a radio reporter, then charged him with masterminding the 
shotgun slaying of Rep. Ceci Cunha, her husband and two in-laws in 
December. 
</P>
<P>
	Albuquerque, who was first runner-up in last October's  
congressional elections, took office in her place. He has denied 
any involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Former U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de  
Cuellar on Thursday criticized the United States and European 
nations for a lack of foresight in their airstrikes on Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to Peruvian radio station Radioprogramas from his home  
in Paris, Perez de Cuellar said the situation has deteriorated 
because the allied forces waited too long before acting and did not 
commit the ground forces needed to prevent Serb attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez de Cuellar, who led the United Nations from 1982 to 1991,  
also said that while the airstrikes are ``in one respect rigorously 
legal, they are a violation of the United Nations charter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the allies bypassed the U.N. Security Council because  
they knew Russia and China would have vetoed the airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN ANDRES LARRAINZAR, Mexico (AP) -- Hundreds of supporters of  
leftist Zapatista rebels stormed the town hall of this mountain 
village in southern Chiapas state Thursday and ran off the police 
who had seized the building a day earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The protest by masked rebel supporters, who shoved and shouted  
at police, signals the continued resistance to Chiapas Gov. Roberto 
Albores Guillen's plans to dissolve pro-rebel maverick town 
councils in the state, which the government says are illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	San Andres Larrainzar, 460 miles southeast of Mexico City,  
served as the base for peace talks between the Zapatistas and the 
government before negotiations broke off in August 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Rebel supporters seized the town hall about 11 months after the  
Zapatistas staged a brief armed uprising in January 1994, demanding 
greater democracy and Indian rights. 
</P>
<P>
	About 300 Chiapas state police occupied the building Wednesday,  
claiming the rebel supporters had abandoned it. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexican soldiers seized nearly 10 tons of  
marijuana hidden in trucks during two searches in the central state 
of Zacatecas, the Defense Ministry said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldiers at a checkpoint near Rio Grande found almost 6 1/2 tons of  
marijuana in a refrigerator box hidden among bags of limes Tuesday. 
They arrested the driver, who was headed north to Chihuahua, 235 
miles south of the U.S. border. 
</P>
<P>
	The same day, soldiers found 3 1/2 tons of marijuana in three  
pickup trucks at another Zacatecas highway checkpoint. The truck's 
three occupants were arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- The fight against drug trafficking  
must be a united effort that also respects each nation's 
sovereignty, officials from Latin American, Europe and the 
Caribbean said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fight must be based on cooperation, with respect to human  
rights and without interference in a nation's internal matters,'' 
German Health Minister Christal Nickels said. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials began a two-day meeting Thursday aimed at  
developing a common plan to fight drug trafficking, money 
laundering and related problems. The plan is to be presented later 
this year at a European-Latin American summit in Brazil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
