<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Leaders Fear Message Not Heard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILLIAMSBURG, Va. (AP) -- Republican activists complained  
Thursday that the party's appeals to voters are being drowned out -- 
first by impeachment and now by war. 
</P>
<P>
	Gathering for a three-day meeting of state GOP chairmen in this  
historic colonial village, party regulars sought ways to forge and 
communicate a winning message for the 2000 elections, when the 
White House and Congress are at stake. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll get it together for when it counts,'' said Mike  
McDaniel, chairman of the Indiana Republican Party and head of the 
GOP state chairmen's association. The group sponsored more than a 
dozen strategy sessions Thursday designed to improve the GOP's 
communications efforts nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet a number of Republicans predicted the work will do little  
good, at least for now, because few voters are paying attention to 
the GOP message. 
</P>
<P>
	Talk of tax cuts, Social Security reform and better schools were  
lost in the debate over Clinton's fate in the Monica Lewinsky 
investigation and are playing second-fiddle to the conflict in 
Kosovo, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no question that the Clinton scandals and the Clinton  
crises have dominated the public's attention for a very long 
time,'' said Cliff May, Republican National Committee 
communications director. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this escalates and we end up getting ground troops, it  
drowns everything else out,'' said GOP strategist Ralph Reed, who 
served on a panel discussion about GOP message problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't out-shout the war,'' McDaniel said. ``Let it play  
out. When this thing is over, we can sing our message from the 
mountaintops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republican pollster Frank Luntz warned that the problem goes  
deeper than the Kosovo crisis. He said the Lewinsky controversy 
turned Americans off to news from Washington, making it harder for 
Republicans to spread their political message -- even after the war. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to take some sort of economic calamity to change  
the atmosphere,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Democrats also compete with headlines from Kosovo,  
Republicans say their job is tougher because the GOP has lost 
ground in the communications battle to Democrats since 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we've lost (the GOP message), but we did sort of  
misplace it for awhile,'' said Peggy Noonan, speechwriter for 
President Reagan. After seizing the House in 1994, the party ``got 
a little off our footing, a little demoralized,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathy Watson, chairman of the Maine GOP, stopped short of  
criticizing her own leadership, but said, ``The Democratic Party is 
fortunate to be full of good communicators.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a show of unity, the party leaders signed a pledge to enforce  
Reagan's so-called 11th commandment: Thou shall not speak ill of 
another Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	Party chairman Jim Nicholson said he will speak out against  
``personal attacks, bringing up information that is not in the 
public domain'' and lying about a rival's record. 
</P>
<P>
	He insisted the hands-off drive is not intended to help or hurt  
any GOP candidate, though many party strategists view is as a 
benefit to early favorite George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor is preparing for attacks from conservative  
publisher Steve Forbes, a failed 1996 candidate who dipped into his 
personal fortune three years to to air ads against eventual nominee 
Bob Dole. 
</P>
<P>
	Party officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
Forbes' ads probably did not violate Reagan's doctrine because he 
was attacking Dole's legislative record. Dole, however, may have 
crossed the line when he called rival Pat Buchanan an extremist in 
1996, party officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson plans to meet privately with every GOP presidential  
candidate and urge them to comply with the Reagan doctrine. Having 
already talked with Buchanan, Nicholson will sit down during the 
chairmen's meeting with Forbes and potential candidate Tommy 
Thompson, the governor of Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Both are attending the meeting, with little hope of picking up  
support. Bush is expected to win the backing of a majority of state 
chairmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 11:55:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Workman Survives 90-Foot Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PENSACOLA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- A construction worker fell eight  
stories into 4 feet of dirty rainwater in a swimming pool, and 
survived with the help of a seventh-grader who pulled him out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like the luckiest man alive, baby,'' Joseph Sowell said  
upon being released from a hospital six hours after his fall 
Wednesday with his eyes bruised and swollen. 
</P>
<P>
	Sowell, 24, was helping renovate a closed, hurricane-damaged  
hotel when he fell 90 feet off the roof. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Owens, who was at the beach because his school was on  
spring break, pulled a dazed Sowell from the grayish-green water. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't even remember anything about it,'' Sowell said.  
</P>
<P>
	The boy was gone by the time authorities arrived, and a call to  
his home Thursday was not immediately returned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
