<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Forces Intensify Bombing  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO forces took advantage of clear weather  
earlier today, intensifying bombing attacks on Serb troops, tanks, 
armored vehicles and artillery in Kosovo. But there is growing 
Pentagon concern that ethnic Albanian refugees could get in the 
way. Yesterday, Serb forces apparently shot down an unmanned U.S. 
Army reconnaissance aircraft over Kosovo in the second NATO 
aircraft loss since airstrikes began March 24. The first occurred 
March 27 when an F-117A stealth fighter-bomber went down outside 
Belgrade after it apparently was struck by a missile, although it's 
still under investigation. The pilot was rescued. 

</P>
<P>
	Cyprus Lawmaker Tries to Free US GIs  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- A top official in Cyprus is off on a  
mission to free the three American soldiers taken captive by 
Yugoslavia. Spyros Kyprianou told reporters he was surprised at the 
positive reception to the proposal that the soldiers be released. 
But he said he has not yet had direct contact with Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic. He said he would fly to Belgrade 
today, with Greece providing a plane. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Meet Chinese Premier  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As he prepares for a meeting with Chinese  
Premier Zhu Rongji later today, President Clinton says U.S. ties 
with China have yielded security benefits for Americans on a range 
of foreign policy hotspots from northeast Asia to the Middle East. 
Aside from security issues, today's agenda included trade, Taiwan 
and human rights. 

</P>
<P>
	LA Mayor: Our Schools Have Failed  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mayor Richard Riordan declared the nation's  
second-largest public school system a ``total failure'' and blamed 
its leadership yesterday, a week before an important school board 
election. The mayor faulted the board of the Los Angeles Unified 
School District for stressing ``feel-good'' subjects over basic 
math and reading skills. 

</P>
<P>
	Witness Blames Talk Show for Death  
</P>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- A psychiatrist testifying yesterday in a  
$50 million wrongful death lawsuit blamed ``The Jenny Jones Show'' 
for the death of a gay guest who revealed a secret crush on another 
man. Jonathan Schmitz confessed to shooting Scott Amedure in 1995 
three days after the taping on the show, which never aired. Dr. 
Bernard Carroll, who testified for Amedure's family, said he 
thought the show deceived Schmitz, whom he said suffered from 
mental illnesses. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Amazon Rain Forest Fading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Amazon rain forest is being destroyed twice  
as fast as previously believed, according to a study published 
today that relies on new techniques for measuring deforestation. 
The researchers concluded that satellite images -- the traditional 
tool for gauging deforestation -- were missing much of the damage 
from logging and fires set to clear land for farming or pasture. 
Researchers put the loss at 17,000 square miles last year, or three 
times the official Brazilian estimate of 5,700. But 1998 was an 
especially bad year because of an El Nino drought, 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Plans New Windows Version  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft has postponed indefinitely its plans to  
merge its consumer-oriented Windows 95/98 operating system with the 
business-oriented Windows NT platform. Instead, the company plans 
to release a new version based on the Windows 95/98 operating 
system, Microsoft president Steve Ballmer said yesterday in a 
speech at the Windows Hardware Engineering Conference and 
Exhibition in Los Angeles. Microsoft officials had previously said 
that any new consumer versions of Windows would be built on the 
same technology as its Windows NT operating systems. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Finish Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's benchmark stock index rose today to its  
highest closing level so far this year on continued buying by 
foreign investors. The Nikkei gained 292.19 points to close at 
16,846.69. In New York yesterday, the Dow average rose 121.82 
points to close at 10,085.31. 

</P>
<P>
	Ripken Misses Start Due to Injury  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- After going 2,632 games without a day off, Cal  
Ripken is suddenly getting in the habit of watching from the 
dugout. For the first time since 1982, the Baltimore Orioles third 
baseman missed a game because of injury last night. Saddled with a 
stiff lower back, Ripken decided it would be better to take a seat 
than to take a chance. So he never picked up a bat and watched the 
Orioles lose to Tampa Bay 8-5. 

</P>
<P>
	Bruins Clinch Playoff Birth  
</P>
<P>
	SUNRISE, Fla. (AP) -- Anson Carter scored three goals as the  
Boston Bruins beat the Florida Panthers 5-2 last night and clinched 
a playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. Boston's fourth straight 
victory boosted its record to 36-28-13 for 85 points, and 
eliminated the New York Rangers from the playoff race. 

</P>
