<HEADLINE> Universal To Sell Propaganda Films </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Universal Studios plans to sell its interest  
in the commercial, music video and talent management businesses of 
Propaganda Films Holdings Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Entertainment entrepreneur Gary Beer, cable pioneer Jack Crosby  
and the investment fund SCP Private Equity Partners would buy 
Universal's share under the proposed deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms were not disclosed.  
</P>
<P>
	``This sale recognizes the value of Propaganda's nonfeature film  
assets, and is consistent with Universal's objective of focusing on 
its core movie business,'' said Rick Finkelstein, Universal's 
senior vice president for corporate development and strategic 
planning. 
</P>
<P>
	Propaganda Films is an independent Hollywood production company  
specializing in commercials, music videos, motion pictures and 
television programming. The company has offices in London, Chicago, 
and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's commercial division has produced television  
commercials for advertisers including Nike, Coca Cola and 
Microsoft. Its music video production are has worked with artists 
including Sting, Fiona Apple and the Rolling Stones. 
</P>
<P>
	Beer managed the Sundance Film Festival and was the chief  
executive officer and co-founder of the Sundance group of 
companies, including the Sundance Channel and the Sundance Cinema 
Circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	SCP Private Equity Partners is a $265 million private equity  
fund based in Wayne, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Montreal-based Seagram Co., the parent company of  
Universal Studios, sold its art house labels October Films and 
Gramercy Pictures and the remains of PolyGram Filmed Entertainment 
to media giant Barry Diller. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was yet another move to reduce the company's debt load  
since last year's $10.4 billion purchase of PolyGram's parent 
company PolyGram NV and to focus on its corporate movie business. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
