<DOCNO> APW19990408.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 12:45:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DC Transit Officials Warn of Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mechanical breakdowns and malfunctions on  
Washington's subway system, which led commuters and tourists to 
mutiny during a rush-hour delay this week, threaten dependable 
service, transit officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rail cars and other equipment on the 99-mile, 23-year-old system  
that extends into suburban Maryland and Virginia, are old, 
sometimes obsolete and plagued by deferred maintenance, said 
Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority officials. 
</P>
<P>
	New cars are on the way and the authority's governing board is  
considering a request for millions more for repairs and equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Repairs have been done piecemeal,'' said Lem Proctor, director  
of car maintenance. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem during Wednesday's evening rush hour focused  
attention on the system's mechanical troubles. 
</P>
<P>
	Back-to-back breakdowns along a key tourist route prompted what  
officials described as a mutiny by passengers forced to get off two 
trains and wade into crowded platforms. Shouts and pushing followed 
at the station serving the Smithsonian Institution museums on the 
National Mall. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of tourists joined weary commuters in an effort to  
board the first available train. It took 25 minutes for transit 
police to clear the train when it reached the next station. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they probably had a high level of frustration,'' said  
Richard White, the system's general manager. ``When we have a 
mechanical problem it does have a cascading effect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Transit officials said a malfunctioning door indicator led them  
to take the second train out of service, in accordance with a 
policy that safety indicators work properly when trains are in 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials have asked the authority's governing board of  
appointed regional officials to spend $47.3 million over the next 
five years for repairs and new equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	``That could cut delays and offloading by 50 percent,'' said  
Charles Thomas, deputy general manager for operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 300 of the 764 cars have traveled more than a million  
miles, and another 366 will reach that point by 2002. Delivery of 
110 new cars is expected over the next 26 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Also targeted for replacement is an automatic car identification  
system, now outdated, used to track train movement. 
</P>
<P>
	``The system is old and obsolete and the parts needed cannot be  
obtained anymore,'' Proctor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since March 11, the Washington system has ordered train  
operators to run their trains on manual controls because of 
concerns about aging switching and signal relays. Transit officials 
said Thursday they did not know when the system might return to 
faster automatic operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 13:15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Hawaii Five-O' Headed for Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Film 'em, Danno.  
</P>
<P>
	The TV series ``Hawaii Five-0'' will be made into a movie now  
that a rights dispute between CBS and the estate of the show's 
creator has been resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	The movie's producer, George Litto, and the widow of show  
creator Leonard Freeman prevailed in a 21-month arbitration battle 
with the network over film rights to the story about the island 
adventures of no-nonsense cop Steve McGarrett. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a major franchise,'' Litto said Wednesday. ``It's the  
kind of television show that became part of the fabric of society. 
McGarrett became the symbol, the epitome of the tough, honest, 
dedicated cop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Litto said he has a script and a large line of credit. He plans  
to approach studios and stars about getting a big-budget project 
off the ground. He hopes to be on location in Hawaii as early as 
this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS said in a statement: ``We believe it would have been better  
for the project if we had prevailed in the arbitration, but 
obviously we did not. We wish Mr. Litto all the best with his 
project.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The series ran on CBS from 1968 to 1980.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
