<HEADLINE> Hoiles Takes Orioles' Coaching Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Former Baltimore Orioles starting catcher Chris  
Hoiles, who was released three days before the season, has accepted 
the team's offer to become a roving catching instructor. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoiles, who will be paid $3.75 million this year, will travel to  
the club's minor-league affiliates and work with young catchers on 
their mechanics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll go down and help some young kids fulfill their dreams,''  
he said during a pregame visit to the clubhouse. ``I'll go there 
and share the situations I know about, the experience I have -- and 
possibly help someone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hoiles admitted that watching the Orioles' first two games on TV  
from his home was difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``Watching all the activities that opening day brings was  
hard,'' he said. ``Being a part of it for nine years, that was the 
toughest thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he also found a silver lining while watching the Orioles  
fall behind Tampa Bay on Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least I have an option now -- I can turn to `Saturday Night  
Live' or Letterman or something,'' said Hoiles. ``Before, I was 
drinking coffee at 11 o'clock. Now I'm ready to go to sleep.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
