<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> O'Meara Stays Focused at Masters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Defending champion Mark O'Meara had that  
special feeling again Thursday standing over a birdie putt on the 
18th hole in the Masters. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, O'Meara holed a 20-foot birdie putt on the last hole  
to win his first green jacket. 
</P>
<P>
	This time it was an 8-footer that would give him a hard-earned  
2-under-par 70 to conclude a weather-delayed round that took 6 1/2 
hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't quite as nervous today as I was last year,'' O'Meara  
said. ``But I felt good over the putt like I did last year. It 
brought back memories knowing I could do it when I had to. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a good way to end what turned out to be a long, hard  
day. It was nice to get off to a good start.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Meara was only a shot behind those who finished their round.  
Four groups were still on the course when play was suspended. 
</P>
<P>
	Not many fans followed O'Meara although he was defending  
champion. He was ``third-fiddle'' behind David Duval and Tiger 
Woods when the first round began. 
</P>
<P>
	He had about 150 faithful followers while most fans trooped  
after Duval, the No. 1 player in the world, and Woods, ranked No. 
2. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Meara survived the day in his typical grinding style to prove  
once again it's foolish to overlook the man who won the Masters and 
British Open in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it was a difficult day to stay focused.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was pleased with my composure, the way I hung in there,''  
O'Meara said. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Meara's group didn't tee off until 1:12 p.m. and because  
officials decided to play threesomes the afternoon dragged along. 
</P>
<P>
	It took O'Meara's group of amateur Hank Kuehne and Lee Westwood  
one hour to play three holes. 
</P>
<P>
	Then O'Meara hooked a tee shot on the par-3 No. 4 after the long  
delay and made bogey. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just had to realize it was going to be one of those kind  
of days where you had to survive it,'' O'Meara said. ``I hit some 
good shots. I hit some bad shots. But I putted pretty well and that 
kept me going.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
