<DOCNO> APW19990408.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 06:08:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Macedonia Abruptly Empties Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) -- For tens of thousands of Kosovo  
Albanians stranded in a fetid no-man's land between their homeland 
and Macedonia, deliverance came at a speed that left their last few 
belongings -- and their lives -- scattered. 
</P>
<P>
	People who had already lost their homes, lands and livelihoods  
in the forced flight from Kosovo found in rescue that they had 
still more left to lose. 
</P>
<P>
	``My father, brothers and mother, and one child,'' said one  
woman, who gave her name only as Dita, listing the loved ones from 
whom she had been separated after Macedonia's decision to empty out 
a makeshift refugee camp on its border overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	By dawn Wednesday, Macedonian authorities had dispersed 35,000  
or more of the refugees from the squalid, septic border enclave. 
The majority were sent to NATO tent camps inside Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonia sent 10,000 to neighboring Albania and 5,500 to  
Turkey, the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees said. The UNHCR was 
still trying to account today for 10,000 refugees bused to a 
destination still unknown to international aid workers, spokeswoman 
Paula Ghedina said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Brazda refugee center in Macedonia, Dita looked for her  
relatives. ``I think maybe they're here, but I don't see them,'' 
she said. ``I'm very worried about them. I don't know where to find 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonia had been stung by international criticism of its  
slowness in moving refugees from the border. 
</P>
<P>
	Serb forces have been accused of expelling hundreds of thousands  
from Kosovo in response to the NATO bombing campaign, although the 
Yugoslav government says the refugees fled NATO airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Aid agencies said the camp had been rife for an epidemic.  
Journalists, although kept back from the scene by Macedonian 
forces, counted scores of graves appearing in the hills. 
</P>
<P>
	When Macedonia finally acted, it acted quickly, shipping the  
refugees out on buses at a speed that caught humanitarian workers 
by surprise, leaving them mystified for much of Wednesday as to the 
refugees' whereabouts. 
</P>
<P>
	One refugee said he left his family to get bread, and came back  
to find them gone, hustled on to buses before he could say goodbye. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a nightmare,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Within 24 hours, the NATO camps in Macedonia swelled by 25,000,  
to about 44,000. 
</P>
<P>
	At the camps, the newly arrived refugees sought out their  
families, some sobbing in the confusion. 
</P>
<P>
	Western aid workers had been anxious to see refugees escape the  
filthy conditions at Blace, but still were critical of the way the 
evacuation was carried out by Macedonian authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we can attest to is the fact refugees usually do not  
leave the few items they have in their possession -- meaning tents, 
blankets, baby food, passports. And evidence of these were found in 
Blace,'' Ghedina said. ``So we do have quite a bit of concern that 
there was some degree of pressure placed on these refugees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Serbs allegedly destroyed the Kosovo Albanians' documents before  
expelling them, and the UNHCR had been working to register the 
refugees -- not an easy task. 
</P>
<P>
	Norwegian Foreign Minister Knut Vollebaek, chairman of the  
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, praised 
Macedonia for allowing the refugees' entry and clearing out the 
unhealthy border enclave. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, he acknowledged that some refugees at Blace  
were filmed being taken away against their will. ``Forced removal 
is unacceptable,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
