<HEADLINE> Farrakhan Released From Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan was  
released from the hospital after an eight-day stay. His doctors 
said this week he is free of cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan left Howard University Hospital on Wednesday. A  
university spokeswoman, Donna Brock, said she could not say where 
he was going. He lives in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan, 65, underwent surgery March 30 to correct an  
inflammation caused by cancer treatment to his prostate. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, his doctors held a news conference to say Farrakhan,  
who was first diagnosed with prostate cancer in 1991, was free of 
the disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Abdul Alim Muhammad, health minister for the Nation of Islam,  
said then that Farrakhan had ``absolutely no evidence of cancer,'' 
and suggested he had been cured. 
</P>
<P>
	Nation of Islam officials said Farrakhan would continue his  
three-month sabbatical and would use his experience to spread the 
word that prostate cancer is more common and aggressive in black 
men. 
</P>
<P>
	During his hospital stay, published reports said Farrakhan's  
condition was more serious than Nation of Islam officials were 
revealing. Muhammad said the news conference Tuesday was held to 
dispel the stories that Farrakhan was gravely ill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
