<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: NATO Is Going To Prevail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AVIANO AIR BASE, Italy (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen  
told U.S. pilots today that the bombing missions they are flying 
over Yugoslavia will pay off. 
</P>
<P>
	``NATO is going to prevail,'' he declared.  
</P>
<P>
	Standing beside an F-16 fighter in a hanger, Cohen continued:  
``It's going to be difficult. It's going to be hard. But we will 
persevere. The reason is because of you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen visited the air base, from which hundreds of missions have  
been launched over Yugoslavia, along with a bipartisan 
congressional delegation. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Joseph Ralston, vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,  
told the pilots and support crews that they were engaged in ``a 
tremendously complex effort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said it was particularly difficult ``with the entire world  
watching to see if you do it right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen accused Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic of sending  
``hooded thugs'' to Kosovo to engage in rape, murder and other 
atrocities ``on the scale of which we not seen since World War 
II.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``And now he holds up his bloody hand and says, `NATO made me do  
it,''' Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense secretary and his party were flying to Ramstein Air  
Base in Germany later today for similar meetings with U.S. air 
crews there, as well as with officials from other NATO countries 
involved in the air campaign against Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	One 32-year-old Air Force pilot from Aviano, said those flying  
daytime missions had not encountered much anti-aircraft fire, but 
those flying at night had. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are doing our job destroying targets,'' he said. ``Asked  
about the issue of ground forces, the pilot said, ``As a pilot, I 
can't put myself into the mind of Slobodan Milosevic. We're going 
to continue to do what our leaders tell us to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon officials asked reporters not to use the names of  
pilots for security reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the bipartisan congressional delegation praised the  
professionalism of the NATO military planners in Brussels and 
asserted that NATO nations seemed united behind continuing the 
effort -- at least for now. 
</P>
<P>
	But few minds seemed to be changed, and those who had advocated  
a ground troop option before, continued to call for one. ``The 
differences remain between me and the administration on whether we 
should exercise the ground option,'' said Sen. John McCain of 
Arizona, a senior member of the Armed Service Committee and a GOP 
presidential aspirant. 
</P>
<P>
	``You cannot rule out any options and still be credible,'' said  
McCain, a former Navy pilot who spent years as prisoner of war in 
North Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	Otherwise, he said, borrowing a phrase from that era, ``The  
light at the end of the tunnel may turn out to be a train.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain said that when he and other lawmakers brought up the  
ground troop argument, they were greeted with politeness -- but 
little enthusiasm -- from NATO military officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., another who favors planning for  
a ground force, said such a strategy would show Milosevic ``he 
can't wait us out on this bombing campaign. We have to keep the 
option of ground forces on the table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., a Senate Foreign Relations  
subcommittee chairman, told reporters that failing to at least plan 
for a ground war would be foolhardy. ``If NATO countries lose the 
stomach after two or three months, we will not only have lost the 
war, we will have lost Europe,'' he said. ``You can't win a war 
hoping for the best, you have to plan for the worst.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Ike Skelton of Missouri, senior Democrat on the House Armed  
Service committee, said he was impressed with the level of support 
the air operations had among the various NATO nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was looking for weak knees. I didn't see any,'' Skelton  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Jack Reed, D-R.I., was supportive of the administration but  
said after the briefings, ``They have to start planning something 
else.'' Reed said it was important to build a consensus in the 
United States and that bringing congressional members along on the 
trip was a good gesture toward keeping channels of communication 
open with Congress. For one thing, Reed said, he was impressed with 
the commitment of European allies to the air campaign. ``They seem 
to be sincerely committed to this,'' Reed said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., senior Democrat on the House  
International Relations Committee, said he strongly supports the 
administration's current policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're better off with an air campaign you can sustain than  
with a ground campaign you can't initiate,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	There was wide praise among the congressional delegation for  
gen. Wesley Clark, the top NATO commander. ``He didn't overstate 
his case,'' said Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
