<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Food Lion CEO Announces Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALISBURY, N.C. (AP) -- Tom E. Smith, who led Food Lion's growth  
into one of the nation's largest supermarket chains and supervised 
damage control after a TV network's investigation of the company's 
sanitation and food-handling practices, is retiring. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, who kept a relatively low profile as Food Lion's  
president and chief executive officer but frequently appeared in 
folksy television commercials, said Wednesday that he is leaving 
the company on a sound footing. 
</P>
<P>
	``After almost 30 years of dedication and hard work, it is time  
to retire and give the company a new management team to lead it 
into the next millennium,'' Smith said in a prepared statement. ``I 
can think of no better time to make these changes than the present 
as Food Lion is in excellent shape, financially and 
operationally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Smith's recommendation, the company's board of directors  
named Bill McCanless his successor. McCanless has served as senior 
vice president of administration, chief administrative officer and 
secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	Pierre-Olivier Beckers, chief executive officer of Delhaize ``Le  
Lion'' Group, the Belgium-based supermarket chain that is Food 
Lion's largest shareholder, was named chairman of the board. 
</P>
<P>
	When Smith was appointed CEO nearly 30 years ago, the company  
had 317 stores with sales of $1.9 billion and profits of $47.6 
million. During his tenure, sales have quadrupled to $10.2 billion, 
store count has grown to 1,223, and profits have increased to 
$272.6 million, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	One dark spot in Smith's tenure was ABC's 1992 undercover report  
on the supermarket chain's food-handling practices, which resulted 
in Food Lion suing ABC over the way it gathered information for the 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	In December 1996, a U.S. District Court jury in Greensboro ruled  
that ABC committed fraud and trespass and that its reporters, who 
used hidden cameras and lied to get jobs, breached the loyalty they 
owed their temporary employer. In January 1997, the jury awarded 
Food Lion punitive damages of $5.5 million, but a federal judge cut 
the award to $315,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith turned down ABC's offer to appear on the ``PrimeTime  
Live'' segment and did not testify during the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	With 1998 sales in excess of $10 billion, Food Lion is one of  
the nation's largest supermarket chains, serving more than 10 
million customers per week at supermarkets in 11 Southeast and 
Mid-Atlantic states. 
</P>
<P>
	The company plans to open 80 new stores and remodel 140 others  
in 1999. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
