<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Deliberates in McDougal Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Jurors deliberating Susan McDougal's  
fate asked on Thursday whether they can consider an ``innocent 
reason'' for her refusal to testify in the Whitewater investigation 
of President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	In a note to the judge, jurors asked a question that goes to the  
heart of Mrs. McDougal's defense: She feared prosecutor Kenneth 
Starr would charge her with perjury unless she falsely implicated 
the president and first lady in wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge George Howard Jr. responded to the jurors'  
question by letting them sort out the issue for themselves, 
referring the panel back to the instructions he read them earlier 
in the day. Jurors adjourned for the day without reaching a 
verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	Before deliberations began Thursday, Howard instructed the jury  
that Mrs. McDougal would be guilty of criminal contempt if she 
``willfully'' violated a court order to testify and did not act 
``by accident, mistake or other innocent reason.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Howard also stated Mrs. McDougal's defense that Starr was  
trying to get her to lie could be applied only to an obstruction of 
justice charge against her, not to the two contempt charges. 
</P>
<P>
	In closing arguments Wednesday, Mrs. McDougal's lawyer, Mark  
Geragos, emphasized to the jury that she did have an ``innocent 
reason'' for not testifying. Referring to her assertion that Starr 
wanted her to lie, Geragos said the prosecutors' tactics were 
``something you expect to see in the Third Reich.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Mark Barrett said that ``innocent reason'' does not  
include the fact that a defendant does not like the prosecutor. 
Barrett said an example of an ``innocent reason'' for not 
testifying would be if the witness got laryngitis. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Julie Myers portrayed Mrs. McDougal as a chronic liar  
and publicity-seeker who refused to testify because she hated Starr 
and enjoyed the attention she was receiving as a grand jury 
holdout. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal is charged with two counts of criminal contempt  
for her refusals to testify to the grand juries in 1996 and 1998. 
The obstruction charge alleges that she seriously impeded Starr's 
probe and would carry a maximum 10-year prison term. Prison terms 
for criminal contempt are left to the judge's discretion. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal entered the courtroom smiling and seemingly  
relaxed, propping her feet on a chair while waiting for jurors to 
arrive. Asked whether she was relieved the trial was ending, she 
answered, ``You can't imagine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the courthouse, prosecutors said ``lingering questions''  
exist in the Whitewater investigation even though Mrs. McDougal 
testified at her trial, finally answering some of the questions she 
previously had refused to answer. 
</P>
<P>
	She says she did not tell the president about a fraudulent  
$300,000 loan that was used in part to prop up the Whitewater real 
estate venture and that as far as she knows, Clinton testified 
truthfully at her 1996 trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Convicted of four felonies regarding the fraudulent federally  
backed $300,000 loan, Mrs. McDougal testified that her ex-husband, 
James, told her that if she testified that she had sex with the 
president, she could write her own ticket with Starr's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the courtroom, Mrs. McDougal denied any intimate  
relationship with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial featured an unusual lineup of witnesses: three grand  
jurors, three Whitewater prosecutors and a defendant from another 
case Starr is bringing. 
</P>
<P>
	The grand jurors testified that they did not think Starr was out  
to get the Clintons and that they felt Mrs. McDougal should have 
testified. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutors said they did their jobs in an evenhanded  
manner. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr deputy Hickman Ewing also testified that he had drawn up a  
draft indictment of Hillary Rodham Clinton and circulated it inside 
the prosecutor's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Regarding the truthfulness of Mrs. Clinton's July 1996 testimony  
in the Whitewater probe, Ewing said he told colleagues that he 
would have given her a grade of ``about an `F.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Defendant Julie Hiatt Steele said she had been victimized by  
Starr's office because she -- like Mrs. McDougal -- wouldn't tell the 
prosecutors a story that implicated Clinton in wrongdoing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
