<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Revlon To Sell Some Divisions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Cosmetics company Revlon is in line for a  
makeover, though whether its potential new look is a success 
remains to be seen. 
</P>
<P>
	Billionaire Ronald O. Perelman on Wednesday announced plans to  
sell one or more of Revlon's struggling businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The news wasn't a complete surprise to investors, who have sent  
shares of Revlon soaring 70 percent over the past two weeks amid 
rumors the company was a takeover target. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation of potential bidders has included Unilever NV, the  
maker of Calvin Klein and Elizabeth Arden cosmetics and fragrances, 
and Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., which owns the Max Factor and Cover Girl 
lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Exactly what kind of sale would be undertaken remains unclear.  
The company did not elaborate on its plans, and spokesman Walter 
Montgomery said, ``It's premature to speculate on any specific 
course of action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Revlon makes Revlon and Almay makeup, Flex shampoo and Charlie  
perfume. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one analyst believes the whole company will be sold  
rather than splitting apart its businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's much more likely they would sell the whole company,''  
said Tim Drake, a senior equity analyst at Banc One Investment 
Advisors, which owns about 350,000 shares of Revlon. ``The true 
value of the company is in the Revlon brand and the Revlon name.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The money from any deal would be used to pay down Revlon's $1.66  
billion in debt, much of it borrowed when Perelman bought the 
company in 1985 for $1.83 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in 1934 by Charles Revson and Joseph Lachman, the  
company made its name in the business by introducing nail polish 
and matching lipsticks in fashion colors. 
</P>
<P>
	Revlon, which now uses model Cindy Crawford to hype its new  
shades, is a dominant player at cosmetic counters in drugstores 
like Eckerd and Rite Aid, and discount stores like Target and 
Wal-Mart. 
</P>
<P>
	But the competition is cutthroat.  
</P>
<P>
	Crowding the market with L'Oreal and Estee Lauder are aggressive  
rivals such as Procter &AMP; Gamble, which is launching a makeup line 
for its Oil of Olay brand, and Johnson &AMP; Johnson, which just 
introduced a Neutrogena-brand makeup. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, companies like Gap and Victoria's Secret are  
launching their own makeup and body care lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a whole new market share war going on,'' said Allan  
Mottus, editor of The Informationist, an industry trade 
publication. Revlon's ``business has slowed down, and they have to 
invest more in new products and advertising to compete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's hard for debt-laden Revlon to do, having earned just $8.5  
million from continuing operations last year on flat sales of $2.25 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the recent run up in Revlon's stock, the shares remains  
58 percent below where it stood last April. 
</P>
<P>
	Perelman, chairman and chief executive of Revlon, owns 83  
percent of the company's stock through his firm MacAndrews &AMP; 
Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	For Perelman, who started as a small businessman in Philadelphia  
and became one of the richest men in America, Revlon is the latest 
in a string of problems. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to a costly and high-profile custody battle with his  
third wife, Perelman's investments in Marvel Comics, Sunbeam and 
Consolidated Cigar have all had their troubles. 
</P>
<P>
	What's more, despite Perelman's efforts to restructure Revlon,  
the company seems to attract unflattering press. 
</P>
<P>
	The cosmetics company was in the news recently after George  
Fellows, Revlon president, paid for the New York Police 
Commissioner to fly to Hollywood for the Oscars during the 
investigation of the shooting death of Amadou Diallo, an unarmed 
immigrant, by four policemen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
