<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Envoy Seeks Release of U.S. Troops  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO arranged for safe passage today of a  
flight by a former president of Cyprus to Yugoslavia that is 
intended to secure the release of three American soldiers held 
captive in Belgrade, U.S. officials said. Pentagon spokesman 
Kenneth Bacon told reporters that no allied bombing missions will 
interfere with the plane carrying the Cypriot, Spyros Kyprianou. 

</P>
<P>
	Serbs Say Refugees Return Willingly  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Amid fears that refugees are  
becoming human shields now that Yugoslavia has sealed its borders, 
Serb media claimed today that ethnic Albanians are voluntarily 
returning to Kosovo. NATO warplanes and missiles, meanwhile, took 
aim at the heart of Belgrade in what it said is a systematic bid to 
break the Yugoslav military machine. ``We will prevail,'' Defense 
Secretary William Cohen told American pilots today in Italy. 

</P>
<P>
	VOA Plans Broadcasts to Serbia  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Voice of America and Radio Free Europe  
plan to begin round-the-clock broadcasting tonight to provide news 
to people living in Serbia. Marc Nathanson, president of a board 
that oversees the two stations, said a ring of five or six 
transmitters is being erected on a rush basis in countries 
bordering Serbia to transmit Serbian and Albanian language 
programs. ``We're all concerned about the media blackout imposed'' 
by Milosevic, he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Welcomes Chinese Premier  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton welcomed Chinese Premier Zhu  
Rongji to the White House today and said the United States can best 
achieve its hopes for the next century through the creation of a 
``strategic partnership'' with China on such issues as 
nonproliferation, free trade and the mutual embrace of political 
freedom. In his comments, Zhu spoke effusively about 
Chinese-American relations, asserting that the friendship between 
the two countries ``cannot be undermined by anybody.'' 

</P>
<P>
	U.S., China: No Deal on Trade  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and China have been unable  
to resolve differences on eliminating Chinese trade barriers, an 
administration official said today, making it unlikely that U.S. 
approval for China's membership in the World Trade Organization 
will come during Premier Zhu Rongji's visit. The official said the 
United States has achieved one of its major objectives -- a separate 
deal with China, effective immediately, to remove barriers to the 
sale of American beef, wheat and citrus. 

</P>
<P>
	Quayle To Announce Candidacy  
</P>
<P>
	HUNTINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Former Vice President Dan Quayle will  
announce his candidacy for the Republican presidential nomination 
at a political rally next week in his hometown. Quayle, 52, will be 
joined on stage at Huntington North High School by his wife, 
Marilyn, and numerous elected officials, his campaign committee 
said. Quayle was George Bush's vice president and running mate in 
1988 and 1992. 

</P>
<P>
	Port Huron, Mich., Mayor Resigns  
</P>
<P>
	PORT HURON, Mich. (AP) -- Gerald ``Ajax'' Ackerman resigned as  
mayor following his arraignment on 14 counts of sexual misconduct 
involving children -- which sent shock waves through this city an 
hour north of Detroit. Mayor Pro Tem Steven Miller confirmed this 
morning that the city has received Ackerman's letter of 
resignation. If convicted, Ackerman would likely face a 
16-to-23-year prison sentence, St. Clair County Assistant 
Prosecutor Mona Sayed said. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Sees More Global Internet Use  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- Worldwide use of the Internet is likely to grow  
rapidly over the next several months leading up to the year 2000, 
according to a United Nations report released today. The Internet 
connected 25 to 30 million users in more than 140 countries at the 
end of 1998, and is likely to reach over 200 million users by the 
year 2000, according to the UN Economic and Social Commission for 
Asia and the Pacific. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 94, Nasdaq Up 3  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 1 p.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 94.35 points at 10,179.66. Decliners on the New York 
Stock Exchange lead advancers 1,391 to 1,380. The Nasdaq Composite 
Index was up 3.10 at 2,547.33. 

</P>
<P>
	Lindros Doubtful for Playoffs  
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Eric Lindros hasn't ruled out returning  
to the Philadelphia Flyers for the NHL playoffs, though he said his 
status will be determined by what doctors say about his recovery 
from a collapsed lung. He plans to check out of the hospital this 
afternoon and fly back to Philadelphia. Doctors have said Lindros 
will need at least 3-4 weeks to regenerate the blood he lost during 
the ordeal that began with an injury last Thursday in a 2-1 victory 
over the Nashville Predators. The playoffs begin April 21. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
