<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Hampshire To Create New Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Working under a court order to find a fair  
way to fund schools, New Hampshire legislators agreed to raise all 
sorts of taxes as a solution, but refused to create a widely 
loathed income tax. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislative leaders would not consider either an income tax or  
general sales tax, all but ensuring the state with the license tag 
that reads ``Live Free or Die'' remains one of two states with 
neither. 
</P>
<P>
	Alaska is the other.  
</P>
<P>
	The state is a week late to meet the state Supreme Court's  
deadline for a new, fairer system to pay for schools. The state now 
relies on widely varying local property taxes, which the court 
ruled unconstitutional in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	A rash of new taxes would be created under a bipartisan plan  
introduced by House leaders Thursday as a counterproposal to a plan 
put forth by Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, which also steered clear of an 
income or general sales tax. 
</P>
<P>
	The House plan would create a statewide property tax, and would,  
for the first time, also tax services; auto sales, rentals and 
leases; and entertainment, such as movie tickets and health club 
memberships. 
</P>
<P>
	Ski lifts were exempt. Cigarette taxes would be increased, as  
would property transaction fees. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate is considering a plan introduced by Shaheen, a  
Democrat, that also relies on a statewide property tax, but also 
would expand business taxes and a capital gains tax. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the new proposed taxes would be repealed if voters  
adopted a constitutional amendment permitting the use of varying 
local property taxes to fund education. 
</P>
<P>
	As lawmakers have wrestled with the issue, two Wall Street bond  
rating firms have said the state's debt is at risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine states have no income taxes: Alaska, Florida, Nevada, New  
Hampshire, South Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Washington and Wyoming. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
