<DOCNO> APW19990408.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 15:05:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Announces Viking Exhibit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton announced a  
millennium museum exhibit Thursday on the Vikings, who may have 
been not only the first Europeans to see America, but also the 
first to create parliamentary government more than 1,000 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit called ``Vikings: The North Atlantic Saga,'' will  
open in Washington at the National Museum of Natural History on 
April 29, 2000, and make a two-year tour of the continent, 
including New York, Los Angeles, Houston, Chicago and Ottawa. 
</P>
<P>
	``Within Viking society, women had a good deal of freedom to  
engage in trade and to become active participants in the political 
lives of their communities,'' Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Iceland, the Viking explorers' homeland, set up a parliament  
called the Althing in the year 930. The Althing still makes 
Iceland's laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton also spoke of the Vikings' wide-ranging voyages  
that brought them not only to North America -- ``a land where the 
frost never came, and the grass hardly withered,'' said an early 
saga -- but also to what are now Turkey and Afghanistan. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you've ever visited Martha's Vineyard, you can see remnants  
of Viking exploration and settlement,'' said Mrs. Clinton, who has 
vacationed on that Massachusetts island with President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Noting that the Vikings transmitted experiences and culture from  
one part of the world to the other, Mrs. Clinton said, ``In a way 
it (the Viking ship) was the Internet of the year 1000.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
