<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Regulators Block Coke Buy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANBERRA, Australia (AP) -- Australian regulators blocked  
Coca-Cola Co.'s initial proposal to acquire several brands of soft 
drinks marketed in Australia from British-based rival Cadbury 
Schweppes. 
</P>
<P>
	But Atlanta-based Coca-Cola said it was already discussing an  
amended proposal with the regulators and was hopeful that it would 
be approved. 
</P>
<P>
	The Australian Competition and Consumer Commission said Thursday  
the U.S. soft drink company's original plan would result in an 
unacceptable reduction of competition in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Commission chairman Allan Fels said Coca-Cola's share of the  
Australian soft drink market would rise to 75 percent from 65 
percent if the original plan went ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	This would threaten other existing or new soft drink companies  
and reduce retailers' sources of supply and was likely to breach 
Australia's competition laws, Fels said. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a statement from Atlanta, Coca-Cola said an amended  
proposal has already been submitted to the Australian regulators 
that is ``substantially different and addresses the ACCC's core 
concerns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The companies had positive discussions with the ACCC earlier  
this year regarding the amended proposal and believe that real 
progress has been made towards a successful outcome,'' the company 
statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola announced in December it would pay $1.85 billion for  
Cadbury Schweppes brands including Dr Pepper and Crush in 120 
countries outside the United States. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
