<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GE's Profit Rises 14 Percent in 1Q </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- General Electric Co.'s profit rose 14  
percent in the first quarter, boosted by strong growth in its 
financial services, aircraft engines and power systems businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	GE earned $2.16 billion, or 65 cents a share, in the quarter  
ended March 31, compared to $1.89 billion, or 57 cents a share, in 
the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The results reported Thursday were in line with analysts  
surveyed by First Call Corp., who had predicted earnings of 65 
cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	But GE shares fell 62 1/2 cents in a rising market to close at  
$113.87 1/2 a share on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues rose 7 percent in the quarter to $24.17 billion, up  
from $22.63 billion a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	GE Chairman John F. Welch attributed the strong results to  
global growth, rapid introduction of new products and expansion of 
the company's product services activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings rose 17 percent at GE Capital Services, the company's  
financial services arm, which had an 11 percent revenue rise. 
</P>
<P>
	The aircraft engines unit's earnings rose 15 percent on a 5  
percent revenue increase. The division won more than 50 percent of 
the orders of large commercial engines during the quarter, winning 
new business valued at more than $800 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The power systems unit's earnings rose 27 percent as revenue  
rose 6 percent and the division won more than $1.1 billion of 
turbine orders. 
</P>
<P>
	But earnings and revenue fell 2 percent at GE Appliances.  
</P>
<P>
	At NBC, earnings increased 12 percent despite a 6 percent  
decline in revenue. 

</P>
</TEXT>
