<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Gains Vs. Major Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar eked out gains against other major  
currencies Thursday as a larger-than-expected interest rate cut by 
the European Central Bank failed to bolster the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading focused on euro-dollar transactions, but the dollar  
captured a minuscule gain on the Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0740, down  
from $1.0772 late Wednesday. The dollar was worth 121.37 Japanese 
yen, up from 121.35 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro spent much of the day strengthening against the dollar  
in anticipation of a modest interest rate cut by the European 
Central Bank as its monetary policy committee concluded a two-day 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Typically, countries or regions cut interest rates to spur  
lending and spending in a sluggish or recessionary economy. The 
downside, however, is that the lower rates also reduce the payoff 
on investments in the local currency and assets, making them less 
attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	Initially, traders saw a small rate cut as positive for the  
euro, the representative currency of 11 countries that has slid 
since its inception in January. 
</P>
<P>
	So when the ECB cut key interest rates by one-half percentage  
point to 2.5 percent, the first reduction since the euro's launch, 
the euro, the yen and other major currencies rose against the 
dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	But within minutes, traders looked at the short-term impact of  
this surprisingly large cut and decided that the interest rate 
differential between the United States and Europe would hurt the 
euro, said Jay Bryson, an economist at First Union Capital Markets 
in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	With that new insight, traders started buying dollars back.  
</P>
<P>
	``When the dollar strengthened against the euro, the dollar  
strengthened against all those other currencies as well,'' Bryson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4878 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4813, and 1.4997 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4993. The British 
pound was quoted at $1.6049, up from $1.5911. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro no  
longer are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed 
rate. Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8212 
German marks, up from 1.8155; 6.1087 French francs, up from 6.0901; 
and 1,801.80 Italian lire, up from 1,798.56. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
