<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ricky Henderson Off to a Hot Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- In March, Rickey Henderson looked old.  
</P>
<P>
	Spring training is a time of renewal, rebirth and rejuvenation,  
but Henderson muddled through the month. He had no pop in his bat, 
no spring in his step. 
</P>
<P>
	He hit .130, and New York Mets fans feared the 40-year-old  
Henderson would be a bust as the team's new leadoff hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, Henderson said, the bell rang to start the season. He  
snickers at the cliche. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard it: ding, ding, ding,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Henderson came out swinging. After three games, he's again  
playing like a future Hall of Famer, and retirement seems far away. 
</P>
<P>
	``He might be around when he's 50,'' Florida Marlins manager  
John Boles said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the season-opening series against Florida, Henderson went  
6-for-11 (.545) with two homers, three doubles, four RBIs, five 
runs scored, three walks and a stolen base. On Wednesday, he went 
4-for-4 with two homers and two doubles, lifting his slugging 
percentage to 1.364. 
</P>
<P>
	His new teammates were impressed.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing,'' John Olerud said. ``To be 40 years old and do  
what he does is incredible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope I'm still walking when I'm 40,'' Mike Piazza said.  
</P>
<P>
	Henderson's fast start was especially dazzling given his  
sluggish showing in spring training. He went 7-for-54, stirring 
speculation that his new one-year, $2.3 million contract was merely 
an advance on a retirement pension. 
</P>
<P>
	``Spring training doesn't mean a whole lot,'' Henderson said.  
``People were skeptical about what was going on. They wanted me to 
go out and show what I was capable of doing, but I was just working 
on some things. Since the season started, I've been more patient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Henderson hit the ball hard four times Wednesday, particularly  
on a 417-foot homer over the center-field wall. The two-homer game 
was the 10th of his career and his first since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``The home runs just come,'' he said. ``They feel good, but  
they're not something I look for. We have the big boys to do 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets want Henderson to get on base and wreak havoc, and he's  
done that, too. On Tuesday, he stole third with two out, an unusual 
move that paid off when catcher Jorge Fabregas threw the ball into 
left field, allowing Henderson to score. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Henderson advanced to third on a balk by Jesus  
Sanchez, then scored on a sacrifice fly. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always good to get off to a good start with a new team,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Henderson's career totals are remarkable: 2,684 hits, 2,019  
runs, 1,893 walks, 268 homers and a major-league record 1,298 
steals. Oddly, he has switched teams eight times, and he faced 
scrutiny joining the Mets after hitting a career-low .236 with 
Oakland in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, Henderson became the oldest player to lead  
the American League in steals last year with 66. And despite his 
poor batting average this spring, the Mets were pleased with the 
effort he made to prepare for the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not in awe too often when I'm around world-class  
athletes,'' manager Bobby Valentine said. ``But it's refreshing to 
see how hard he works and how much he cares about this game. I 
appreciate his offensive skills. He knows what he's doing out 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure glad he's with us.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
