<HEADLINE> Seattle Shortstop Has Knee Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Seattle Mariners All-Star shortstop Alex  
Rodriguez, who hurt himself during an agility exercise in spring 
training, underwent knee surgery Thursday and will miss 4-6 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything went fine,'' Mariners medical director Dr. Larry  
Pedegana said in a statement released by the team. ``The surgery 
went as expected and Alex is already home resting and getting ready 
to start his rehabilitation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pedegana repaired a torn medial meniscus in Rodriguez's left  
knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez played the first two games of the season for the  
Mariners and went 0-for-6. He left Tuesday's game early and did not 
play Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the biggest obstacle in my career,'' Rodriguez told  
The Seattle Times. ``I'll overcome it. I'll work hard and overcome 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez hurt himself while doing an exercise that involves  
jumping over boxes that are about as high as a chair. He hurt 
himself March 30 in Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners haven't put Rodriguez on the disabled list. They're  
expected to do it before Friday night's game with Oakland when they 
make a roster move to replace Rodriguez. 
</P>
<P>
	With Rodriguez sidelined, Carlos Guillen will move to shortstop  
and utility player David Bell will start at second. Guillen was 
supposed to be Seattle's second baseman this season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
