<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., China: No Deal on Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and China have been unable  
to resolve differences on eliminating Chinese trade barriers, an 
administration official said today. That makes it unlikely that 
U.S. approval for China's membership in the World Trade 
Organization will come during Premier Zhu Rongji's visit. 
</P>
<P>
	The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the  
United States had achieved one of its major objectives -- a separate 
deal with China, effective immediately, to remove barriers to the 
sale of American beef, wheat and citrus. 
</P>
<P>
	Trade negotiators from both countries were continuing their  
separate talks even as Clinton and Zhu met at the White House. But 
the White House official said it appeared unlikely that all the 
gaps could be closed in time for Clinton and Zhu to announce a deal 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``In all likelihood, we will reaffirm we have made some  
significant progress towards a strong agreement, but we have some 
gaps on some important issues. We will commit to resolving those 
issues to conclude a strong agreement that will let China into the 
WTO,'' the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Failure to achieve a full agreement today would represent a  
major disappointment for China, which has been trying for 13 years 
to win membership in the WTO or its predecessor organization, the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	China needs approval from the United States and other major  
trading powers for membership, but the administration has insisted 
it will not drop its objections until China agrees to a sweeping 
market-opening document. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration sees these high trade barriers as a chief  
reason for America's soaring trade deficit with China, which last 
year hit a record $57 billion, the largest for any nation except 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Expectations for a deal had grown in the past two weeks as China  
agreed to a number of U.S. demands after years of foot-dragging. 
However, there were areas where China's market-opening offers did 
not meet U.S. demands. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration was fearful that without the strongest deal  
possible it would be hard to get congressional approval, especially 
in the current climate of tense U.S.-Chinese relations. Members of 
Congress are upset over allegations of Chinese thefts of American 
nuclear secrets as well as a recent crackdown on dissidents. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement scheduled to be announced today on agriculture  
products will not be contingent on China's gaining entry into the 
WTO, the administration said. 
</P>
<P>
	China agreed to lift its bans on shipments of wheat from the  
Pacific Northwest and citrus from Florida, Texas and California. 
</P>
<P>
	China had imposed long-standing bans on these products on the  
grounds of worries about plant diseases. U.S. producers, however, 
have long complained that the bans were not based on sound science 
but were hidden trade barriers. The Chinese also agreed to 
eliminate burdensome inspection requirements that had severely 
restricted the amount of U.S. beef that could be sold in China. 
</P>
<P>
	China also agreed to separate deals covering aviation and made  
moves earlier in the week to open up its vast telecommunications 
and insurance markets to U.S. companies. 
</P>
<P>
	On aviation, China agreed to a deal that will double the  
frequency of flights between the United States and China. The 
agreement will add one new American airline and one Chinese airline 
to the three from each nation that currently have permission to fly 
between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
