<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Deliberates in McDougal Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Signaling that Susan McDougal's  
testimony made a deep impression, the jury deliberating her fate 
asked the presiding judge whether they may consider that she had 
good reason to refuse to answer questions in the Whitewater probe. 
</P>
<P>
	A note from the jury focused on a possible ``innocent reason''  
for Mrs. McDougal's refusal to testify, even though she may have 
acted ``willfully'' in violating a court order directing her to 
cooperate with grand juries in 1996 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	During five days on the witness stand, Mrs. McDougal said she  
feared Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr would charge her with 
perjury unless she falsely implicated President Clinton and his 
wife in wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	McDougal lawyer Mark Geragos said that ``obviously'' the jurors,  
who began deliberations Thursday, ``are having trouble with the 
issues. That would lead me to believe they are split in some 
manner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing I have seen today has been negative for us,'' Geragos  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Mark Barrett said he wasn't surprised by the jurors'  
question. ``It's reassuring that they are focusing on the key 
issues,'' he said. The jury resumes deliberations today. 
</P>
<P>
	In closing arguments Wednesday, Geragos told the panel that Mrs.  
McDougal had an ``innocent reason'' for not answering grand jury 
questions, saying Starr's tactics were ``something you expect to 
see in the Third Reich.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge George Howard Jr. tossed the question back  
in the jury's lap, referring the panel to the instructions he read 
earlier in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal would be guilty of criminal contempt if she  
``willfully'' violated a court order to testify and did not act 
``by accident, mistake or other innocent reason,'' the judge 
instructed. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard also stated that Mrs. McDougal's defense that Starr was  
trying to get her to lie could not be applied to criminal contempt 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	In closing arguments, Barrett said ``innocent reason'' does not  
include the fact that a defendant does not like the prosecutor. 
Prosecutor Julie Myers portrayed Mrs. McDougal as a chronic liar 
and publicity-seeker who refused to testify because she hated 
Starr. 
</P>
<P>
	Under federal sentencing guidelines, if convicted, Mrs. McDougal  
faces roughly 27 months in prison on each of three charges -- two 
counts of criminal contempt and one of obstruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
