<HEADLINE> Baker Wants To Play for Auburn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUBURN, Ala. (AP) -- Robert Baker, the former Auburn wide  
receiver who spent 10 months in jail for drug trafficking, is back 
in school and has asked about playing football again, The 
Huntsville Times reported. 
</P>
<P>
	New football coach Tommy Tuberville said it was unlikely Baker  
would be allowed to return, but did not rule it out. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker, convicted last May of cocaine trafficking, was released  
on parole March 22 after serving less than a year of his 15-year 
sentence. He has since enrolled in school and asked Tuberville 
about playing football again. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going there right now,'' Tuberville told the  
newspaper. ``I encouraged Robert to get back in school and get on 
with his life. I told him he should be visible in the community and 
show people he is a good citizen. I told him he should think about 
all of his options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baker, 23, led the Tigers with 1,174 all-purpose yards in 1996,  
including 526 yards receiving and five touchdowns. That was the 
last season he played football. He was academically ineligible in 
1997 and in jail during the 1998 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker was arrested last April for selling cocaine to undercover  
police officers three times. According to arrest reports, the third 
deal was for 111.26 grams of cocaine valued at $5,000 that Baker 
sold for $1,800. 
</P>
<P>
	He was arrested after that sale and offered assistance that  
resulted in the drug-trafficking arrests of Derrick Prince, 21, 
Rahshun Paige, 18, and Jordan Brumbaugh, 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
