<HEADLINE> Two Immigrants Die of Cold in Ariz. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- The bodies of two more suspected illegal  
immigrants have been found in the rural Southwest, raising the toll 
from a weekend snow storm to at least 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Hector Lopez, 30, of Santa Ana, Mexico, and Cesar Fernandez, 44,  
of Hermosillo, Mexico, died of exposure, the Pima County Medical 
Examiner's Office said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight suspected illegal immigrants died of hypothermia being  
caught in the storm late last week. Officials from the U.S. Border 
Control and other agencies rescued more than 50 immigrants Thursday 
and Friday in and around the Cleveland National Forest, about 40 
miles east of San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	The two men who died in Arizona were among at least three who  
crossed the border together over the weekend but split up as they 
grew sick from the cold, Sheriff's Sgt. Brad Foust said. 
</P>
<P>
	Border Patrol agents caught one and returned him to Mexico.  
Border Patrol spokesman Rob Daniels said the man made no mention of 
his companions. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims' families called to inquire about their relatives,  
leading to discovery of their bodies. 
</P>
