<P>
	U.S., China: No Deal on Trade  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and China failed to reach  
final agreement today on a market-opening deal that would have 
cleared the way for China's entry into the World Trade 
Organization. Both nations pledged to complete work by the end of 
the year. President Clinton, speaking after discussions with 
Premier Zhu Rongji, said both sides had made ``significant 
progress'' in clearing away the barriers to China's entry into the 
WTO but ``we are not there yet.'' He said both countries would 
pledge in a joint communique to resolve all the remaining issues in 
time for China to be included in the start of a new round of global 
trade talks in late November. Clinton, however, did announce a 
separate deal in which China agreed to remove barriers to the sale 
of American beef, wheat and citrus. 

</P>
<P>
	Boeing Employment Down 5.4 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- New figures from Boeing Co. show a 5.4 percent  
drop in companywide employment so far this year, reducing the 
number of workers at the troubled aerospace giant from 231,260 down 
to 218,700 workers as of April 1. The biggest declines came from 
the Boeing Commercial Airplane Group, which had 108,300 workers 
April 1, down 7.9 percent from 117,590 at the end of 1998. 
Washington state employment for Seattle-based Boeing stands at 
90,400 people -- down 8.2 percent from the year-end total of 98,440. 
Boeing shares closed down 1/4 at 34 5/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Lockheed Martin Signs Launch Deal  
</P>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Lockheed Martin Corp. said today it will  
supply the Japanese Navy with eight more missile launch systems 
under a $70 million contract with Mitsubishi Heavy Industries. 
Lockheed Martin has been supplying the MK 41 launch systems for 
Japanese destroyers since 1989. The Japanese government decided 
last year to double the number of MK 41 launchers on its 
Muarasame-class ships from two to four. Each launcher can hold up 
to eight missiles. Lockheed Martin, based in Bethesda, Md., is the 
largest defense contractor in the United States. Lockheed Martin 
stock was up 11/16 at 37. 

</P>
<P>
	BMW To Make Cars at Russian Plant  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- BMW plans to make limousines and off-road vehicles  
at a Russian factory in the republic of Kaliningrad, the German 
automaker said today. The first cars are expected to roll off the 
assembly line this summer from the Avtotor plant, said Lueder 
Paysen, head of BWM's executive sales division. The announcement 
came the same day that the Russian government sought to assure 
Western businesses that Moscow's protests against NATO raids on 
Yugoslavia wouldn't hurt their operations in Russia. The Avtotor 
plant will have an annual production capacity of 10,000 units, but 
no date has been set for reaching this target. 

</P>
<P>
	European Bank Cuts Interest Rates  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The European Central Bank cut key  
interest rates by one-half percentage point today to 2.5 percent in 
the first reduction since the euro currency was launched Jan. 1. 
The rate reduction, which affects the 11 nations that adopted the 
euro, exceeded analysts' expectations. Weak economic data released 
earlier today in Germany, Europe's biggest economy, had bolstered 
expectations that the central bank would cut interest rates. 
Analysts were expecting a cut of a quarter of a percentage point, 
matching the move earlier today by the Bank of England which 
trimmed its base lending rate to 5.25 percent from 5.5 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	H&AMP;R Block Discussing Acquisition  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- H&AMP;R Block Inc. is negotiating to buy  
McGladrey &AMP; Pullen LLP, an acquisition that would make Block the 
sixth-largest accounting firm in the country. Both companies 
confirmed today's report in The Wall Street Journal, which said 
Kansas City-based Block hopes to announce a deal by the end of the 
month. 

</P>
<P>
	Humana Expects Lower Earnings  
</P>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Shares of Humana Inc. plummeted today  
after the health maintenance organization warned that higher 
medical costs would mean lower-than-expected earnings for the first 
quarter. The company said operating earnings will be between 20 
cents and 24 cents per share for the first quarter. Wall Street 
analysts were expecting 34 cents, according to a survey by First 
Call. Humana said it will record $90 million in additional medical 
claims expenses during the first quarter, largely because the HMO 
will have to pay considerably higher rates to hospital chain 
Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. as part of a new contract in Florida. 
Humana shares were down 4 at 12 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Salon.com Buys The Well  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Online magazine Salon.com has acquired The  
Well, one of the Internet's first virtual communities, providing a 
larger customer base and a place to hone its image as a marketplace 
for new ideas. No purchase price was disclosed, as both The Well 
and Salon are privately held. The Well, short for The Whole Earth 
'Lectronic Link, features more than 200 online conferences on 
topics ranging from politics and sex to the Grateful Dead. It will 
remain a separate business under its new owners, said Andrew Ross, 
vice president for business development at Salon.com. 

