<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Share Prices Rally / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Share prices rallied today, pushing the Tokyo Stock  
Exchange's main index to its highest level in more than a year. The 
dollar drifted lower against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 292.19 points,  
or 1.77 percent, to close at 16,846.69 -- its fourth straight day of 
gains and the highest close since March 26, 1998, when it finished 
at 16,980.62. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.76 yen in late afternoon trading, down  
0.02 yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo and also below its late New 
York level of 121.35 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese shares were buoyed ahead of the settlement of April  
stock option contracts on Friday, along with continued buying 
interest from foreign investors and some domestic institutions, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Foreigners are still coming in steadily and I think domestic  
institutions, on balance, are net buyers,'' said Chuck Lambert, 
market analyst at Jardine Fleming Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the biggest gainers were shares of computer software  
wholesaler Softbank Corp. and its over-the-counter market 
affiliate, Yahoo Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Softbank soared $16.60, or 12 percent, to close at $151.70.  
Yahoo Japan skyrocketed $83,333, or 32 percent, to $350,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo Japan's gains came after parent company Yahoo! Inc.  
reported better-than-expected earnings for the quarter ended March 
31. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo market fell in early trading on profit-taking, but  
quickly climbed back into positive territory with active buying of 
steel and information-technology stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading volume was heavy, with about 826 million shares changing  
hands on the first section, up from Wednesday's turnover of 709 
million shares. Advancers outnumbered declines 882 to 351, with 95 
issues unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 20.43 points, or 1.54 percent, to 1,345.07 
points. The TOPIX had closed up 2.03 points, or 0.15 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar stayed in a narrow range,  
jostled by profit-taking and position adjustment. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were no big players today, although some Japanese life  
insurance companies started buying at the 121.20 yen level,'' said 
Hajime Sato, assistant general manager of the treasury department 
at Daiwa International Trust Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 120.57 yen and 121.63 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 130.40 yen, up from  
130.20 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 211 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.600 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.685 
percent, pushing its price up to 101.74 yen from 100.99 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
