<HEADLINE> Church To Close Presidents' Graves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	QUINCY, Mass. (AP) -- Financial hard times forced a church to  
close off the graves of Presidents John Adams and John Quincy Adams 
to daily visitors. 
</P>
<P>
	The basement crypt at the Church of the Presidents, which also  
holds the remains of first ladies Abigail and Louisa Catherine 
Adams, is normally open to the public from April through November. 
Under the church's new plan, it would only be open for prearranged 
tours. 
</P>
<P>
	The pastor, the Rev. Sheldon Bennett, said the church needs  
$70,000 to wipe out its deficit, cover operational costs and pay 
for badly needed renovations to the church lobby. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not wealthy people,'' Bennett said. ``We are a small  
congregation of ordinary citizens with modest means, so we can't 
sustain a continuing financial loss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, United First Parish, as it is also known, entered a  
partnership with the city and federal governments to run the crypt. 
Workers on the church payroll operate the site, although National 
Park Service rangers have conducted tours. 
</P>
<P>
	Quincy Mayor James Sheets said he hoped to find a way the crypt  
could remain open. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's too valuable a resource, and belongs to all people of  
this country,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
