<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 12:25:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Police Dep'ts Warned of Car Defect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal safety agency is warning police that  
a wiring change on patrol cars can deactivate a safety device that 
ensures the cars will not surge forward when officers shift out of 
park. 
</P>
<P>
	After a spot check, the National Highway Traffic Safety  
Administration sent the national warning late last week to police 
departments across the country, agency spokesman Tim Hurd said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Some police departments have inadvertently deactivated the shift  
lock by modifying the brake lights to flash on Ford Motor Co. 
police cars and vans when the overhead police lights are on, agency 
officials said. The shift lock prevents drivers from shifting out 
of park to move forward unless they are stepping on the brake. 
</P>
<P>
	The vast majority of police departments use Ford Crown Victoria  
patrol cars and Econoline vans. More than 200,000 of the vehicles 
are driven by law enforcement officers, safety officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-page NHTSA advisory said vehicles that were rewired so  
their brake lights flash during emergencies ``could present a 
safety risk.'' It recommends undoing the rewiring. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials started investigating the problem after an  
accident last December in downtown Minneapolis. A police van 
lurched onto a sidewalk packed with spectators waiting for a 
parade, killing two people and injuring nine others. 
</P>
<P>
	An NHTSA report concluded the officer driving the van had  
mistakenly stepped on the gas pedal rather than the brake when he 
shifted the van out of park. But the report said the accident could 
have been avoided if the shift lock on the Econoline van had not 
been deactivated. 
</P>
<P>
	It was inadvertently disabled by city mechanics using  
aftermarket parts to wire the van's brake lights to flash when the 
overhead police lights were on, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 200 police vehicles in Minneapolis had rewired brake  
lights, and several other police departments in Minnesota have 
discovered they have the same problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal safety investigators are trying to determine how many  
other police departments nationwide have rewired vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	NHTSA investigators found that all three police departments they  
contacted in the Washington area had flashing rear brake lights on 
their Ford patrol cars. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
