<HEADLINE> Salon.com Buys The Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Online magazine Salon.com has acquired The  
Well, one of the Internet's first virtual communities, providing a 
larger customer base and a place to hone its image as a marketplace 
for new ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	No purchase price was disclosed for the deal announced  
Wednesday, as both The Well and Salon are privately held. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Salon Magazine has finally become Salon.com after buying  
the domain name www.salon.com from a Texas hairdresser for an 
unannounced price on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Well, short for The Whole Earth 'Lectronic Link, features  
more than 200 online conferences on topics ranging from politics 
and sex to the Grateful Dead. It will remain a separate business 
under its new owners, said Andrew Ross, vice president for business 
development at Salon.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Ross said he plans to market The Well's conferencing system,  
which costs $10 to $15 a month, to Salon.com readers to help 
increase The Well's membership of 7,000 people, built over 14 
years. Salon.com has 1.2 million members. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will help The Well reach people who may not have known  
about it in its early days,'' Ross said. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of The Well, based in Sausalito, Calif., were ``dancing  
on the keyboards'' upon hearing news of the deal, said the site's 
director, Gail Ann Williams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
