<HEADLINE> Lawmaker Speaks Out on Telecom Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission doesn't  
have the legal authority to impose conditions on SBC 
Communications' planned takeover of Ameritech, contends a key 
telecommunications lawmaker in the House. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., chairman of the House Commerce  
telecommunications subcommittee, which has jurisdiction over the 
agency, made the comment in a letter Thursday to FCC chairman Bill 
Kennard. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC officials have said the agency has authority to impose  
conditions on mergers to protect consumers. It has placed 
conditions on other mergers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am ... concerned that your desire to craft conditions on  
this merger go beyond the commission's legal authority and raise 
fundamental questions of fairness to these merging parties,'' 
Tauzin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tauzin opposes the FCC placing conditions on any merger, said  
spokesman Ken Johnson. He wants to strip the agency of some 
authority to review mergers. 
</P>
<P>
	SBC and Ameritech on Wednesday accepted Kennard's offer to  
discuss possible conditions with FCC staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on Thursday, Ohio regulators approved the deal, which would  
create the nation's largest telephone company. The deal, valued at 
$57 billion when it was announced in May, must still be approved by 
the FCC and Illinois regulators. The Justice Department approved 
the merger last month. 

</P>
</TEXT>
