<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Borrowing at Brisk Pace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- American consumers borrowed at a brisk pace  
during the first two months of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Their credit outstanding, excluding mortgage debt, advanced at a  
7.9 percent annual rate during February to a seasonally adjusted 
$1.32 trillion, the Federal Reserve said Wednesday. That came on 
top of an increase at a 14.1 percent rate -- strongest since 
November 1995 -- in January. 
</P>
<P>
	That borrowing has been reflected in both the vigorous advance  
in retail spending so far this year -- 0.9 percent in February and 1 
percent in January -- and an extremely low rate of personal savings 
-- minus 0.2 percent of after-tax income in February and zero in 
January. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, auto loans showed the strongest increase -- 13.7  
percent at an annual rate. Revolving credit, primarily credit 
cards, rose at a 4.8 percent rate. A catchall category, which 
includes loans for education, vacations, mobile homes and boats, 
advanced at a 5.1 percent rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans have had the confidence to borrow because interest  
rates remain low, the stock market is hitting new highs -- including 
a 122-point gain in the Dow Jones average of industrial stock to a 
close of 10,085 Wednesday -- and they have jobs. Unemployment, 
according to the Labor Department, hit a 29-year low of 4.2 percent 
in March. 
</P>
<P>
	In a discordant note, however, Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas  
Inc., a Chicago-based job-search firm, said Wednesday that publicly 
announced job cuts totaled 68,984 in March, up 11 percent from 
February and nearly triple the 23,028 announced in March 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
