<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The disagreement might seem minor: whether to  
take a religious meal while seated at a table or on the floor. But 
for the world's 20 million Sikhs, the issue symbolizes a power 
struggle between moderates and conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Some say it threatens to split the religion for the first time  
in its 500-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been open war between the moderate leadership in  
North America and those who control the Golden Temple,'' Ajit Jain, 
a Toronto-based correspondent for India Abroad, says of the Sikhs' 
holiest shrine in the western Indian city of Amritsar. 
</P>
<P>
	Sikhism was founded in India's Punjab region as a melding of  
Hindu and Muslim beliefs. 
</P>
<P>
	This month, the religion celebrates the 300th anniversary of the  
forming of the Khalsa, a covenant whereby male followers adopted 
the surname Singh and were bestowed five symbols that would 
distinguish their faith, including a ceremonial dagger, the kirpan, 
and uncut hair. Many male Sikhs are still easily recognizable by 
the carefully wrapped turbans that contain their unshorn hair. 
</P>
<P>
	Major observances of the Khalsa anniversary are planned in  
Washington, D.C., on Saturday and in Toronto April 25. 
</P>
<P>
	But conflict over the issue of how to conduct the community  
meal, known as langar, has muted the festivities. Traditionally 
Sikhs have shared the meal sitting on the floor as a sign of 
equality; but in many temples in North America, tables and chairs 
have been allowed to accommodate the elderly and infirm. 
</P>
<P>
	Tempers first flared in early 1997 when hard-liners at the Guru  
Nanak temple outside of Vancouver, British Columbia, removed 
furniture from the dining hall. When moderates tried to return 
tables and chairs to the temple, there was a near riot. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fundamentalists basically forced the issue. They said 'If  
you don't remove the tables and chairs, we will.''' says John 
Spellman, a professor of Asian Studies at the University of 
Windsor. 
</P>
<P>
	The scene was repeated at the Ross Street temple in Vancouver,  
North America's oldest and largest, and the dispute raged at 
temples in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were several incidents where kirpans were drawn,''  
Spellman says. 
</P>
<P>
	Last April, a religious edict was handed down by the Sikhism's  
highest leader at the Golden Temple, Ranjit Singh, mandating that 
tables and chairs be removed from temple dining halls. 
</P>
<P>
	Singh subsequently ordered the excommunication of six prominent  
moderates at Ross Street for speaking out against his edict. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Singh had been a favorite of hard-liners, critics note  
he was convicted of murdering a rival in 1980, though he was 
pardoned in India. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawsuit filed by moderates of the Ross Street congregation  
forced new leadership elections, and a moderate slate of candidates 
won, but not before more violence. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, Tara Singh Hayer, publisher of a community  
newspaper highly critical of the hard-liners and one of the group 
excommunicated from Ross Street, was shot and killed. Authorities 
believe the shooting, still under investigation, was related to the 
power struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months before Hayer's death, a man in Broward County, Fla.,  
who had vigorously objected to allowing tables and chairs in 
temples opened fire in a local temple, killing one person. 
</P>
<P>
	The conflict cuts to the core of Sikh identity and religious  
authority, says Ken Bryant, a Sikh expert at the University of 
British Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sikhism comes out of a tradition that is anti-hierarchy and  
anti-caste. It was partially a reaction against the notion of 
expensive temples and paid priests,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1984, Sikhs were galvanized by anger over the Indian army's  
storming of the Golden Temple to flush out militants. Prime 
Minister Indira Gandhi's assassination at the hands of her Sikh 
bodyguards was followed by anti-Sikh pogroms. 
</P>
<P>
	An armed struggle to establish an independent Sikh nation, to be  
known as Khalistan, took an estimated 17,000 lives before it was 
brutally suppressed in the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	With that unifying period ended, the power struggle within  
Sikhism has resurfaced. 
</P>
<P>
	The battle is between ``Khalsa Sikhs'' -- those who have been  
baptized and make up the core of the hard-liners -- and the 
religion's rank-and-file, many of whom are so-called cut Sikhs, who 
do not grow their hair and ``don't want to be so conspicuous with 
the turban,'' Spellman says. 
</P>
<P>
	Maintaining the religion in the Western diaspora is proving a  
challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ninety percent already cut their hair. If you read the  
matrimonial ads in our Sikh newspapers now, the women say they 
prefer 'clean shaven,''' says Jarnail Singh Badal, current 
president of Ross Street temple. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not so concerned about the hair,'' he says. ``My aim is  
to get the youth to follow the three basic principles: Pray to God, 
make an honest living and share your earnings with the needy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the Richmond Hill temple in New York City's borough of  
Queens, Punjabi language classes and retreats are efforts to pass 
the religion on to the next generation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have our own schools here, all we have is our  
gurudwara,'' or temple, says Surinder Singh Joshan, Richmond Hill's 
leader. ``We are trying as hard as we can to instill Sikh values in 
our children.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Futures Hit Three-Year Lows  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Coffee futures tumbled Thursday to 3-year lows amid fears  
Colombia will devalue its currency, creating a flood of cheap 
exports. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy futures continued their sharp retreat, while cocoa  
plunged. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee fell for a second day on the Board of Trade of the City  
of New York, losing nearly 5 percent in a single session, amid 
growing complaints from Colombian officials that exports are being 
hurt by an overvalued peso. 
</P>
<P>
	Since coffee is sold for dollars, producers with a weaker local  
currency often step up sales when the dollar is rising. Devaluing a 
currency would immediately cause the U.S. dollar to jump in value 
and provide greater profits to Colombian exporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombia is the single-largest producer of the gourmet-blend  
arabicas favored by American and European consumers and the 
second-largest producer of coffee in the world behind Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said a decision to devalue the Colombian peso could  
produce a ripple effect in other Central American economies, 
prompting other devaluations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colombian talks come at a time when U.S. markets are being  
flooded with cheap coffee as a result of large harvests in Brazil 
and elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Supplies in U.S. exchange-approved warehouses jumped again  
Wednesday, rising by 3,750 bags weighing 132 pounds each to 254,177 
bags. Another 40,000 bags were waiting to be inspected. 
</P>
<P>
	Further pressuring prices Thursday were unconfirmed reports that  
Ethiopia had lowered prices on all grades of its coffee. 
</P>
<P>
	Arabica coffee for May delivery fell $4.90 to $97.70 a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil and refined crude products fell for a second day in  
futures trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange amid increasing 
skepticism about whether world oil producers will honor commitments 
to reduce output. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude retreated below $16 a barrel, giving back more of the  
gains that came after the Organization of Petroleum Exporting 
Countries and other oil producers agreed to cut 2.1 million barrels 
daily from world production beginning a week ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say it may take months to determine whether producers  
are complying, and many market participants are noting that the 
producers never fully met a round of cuts agreed to a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, several key refineries on the West Coast were coming  
back to full service, easing fears about spot gasoline shortages 
across the country before the heavy summer driving period. 
</P>
<P>
	Contracts for May delivery of light, sweet crude fell 20 cents  
to $15.83 a barrel; May unleaded gasoline fell 0.99 cent to 49.52 
cents a gallon; May heating oil fell 0.43 cent to 40.84 cents a 
gallon; May natural gas rose 3.6 cents to $2.060 for each 1,000 
cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures plunged to their lowest in five years on the New  
York Board of Trade amid reports of active selling out of Ghana, as 
world producers rush to unload plentiful crops before prices fall 
even farther. 
</P>
<P>
	With months to come before chocolate makers begin gearing up for  
a new candy season, analysts say the outlook for higher prices 
</P>
<P>
	May cocoa fell $55, or 4.8 percent, to $1,079 a ton.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
