<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Trucker's Ticket Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) -- A Cuban-born trucker who was issued a  
traffic ticket for being ``unable to speak English'' has won his 
fight to have it dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogelio Campos, 62, was driving a dump truck filled with broken  
cement when he was stopped July 16 and cited for not displaying the 
company name on his truck, not producing a card proving he was fit 
to drive the vehicle, and being unable to speak English. 
</P>
<P>
	Yonkers City Court Judge Richard Liebowitz ruled Tuesday that  
because Campos wasn't engaged in interstate commerce, the federal 
language requirement for commercial haulers didn't apply. The other 
two citations are still pending. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law requires that drivers be able to converse with the  
public, understand English traffic signs, respond to official 
questions and fill out reports and records. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge didn't address Campos' claim that the law  
discriminated against non-English speakers. The trucker took his 
driving test in Spanish. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great ending but still we have to get rid of that  
wording in the statute,'' said U.S. Rep. Jose Serrano, a Bronx 
Democrat, who had backed Campos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
