<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 06:09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bell Chiefs, FCC To Discuss Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- SBC Communications Corp. and Ameritech Corp.  
will talk to federal regulators about placing conditions on their 
planned merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Communications Commission Chairman Bill Kennard asked  
the chiefs of both local Bell telephone companies last week to do 
that after raising ``serious concerns'' about whether their merger 
would benefit consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are willing to meet with commission staff to explore the  
issues that you have identified,'' SBC Chairman Edward Whitacre Jr. 
and Ameritech Chairman Richard Notebaert said in a joint letter 
Wednesday to Kennard. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the chiefs said their companies have been providing  
detailed information about their merger to the FCC and continue to 
believe that the merger should be approved without conditions. 
Neither they nor Kennard said what conditions might be set. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard wants discussions to begin this month and to conclude by  
late June. The FCC could make a decision on the matter shortly 
thereafter. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC approval is the last major regulatory hurdle for the deal,  
which has been cleared by the Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger, valued at $57 billion when it was announced last  
year, would create the nation's largest local phone company. It 
would control 57 million, or one-third, of the nation's local phone 
lines spread across 13 states. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard, in letters to the companies' chiefs last week, wanted  
to know how the FCC can be assured that the public will receive the 
benefits the companies say will result from the union. He said 
Wednesday he was ``pleased'' the companies had decided to 
participate in the process he had outlined and looked forward ``to 
resolving this matter expeditiously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, Kennard asked how the commission can be  
assured that the merger won't interfere with the companies' 
willingness and ability to open their local phone markets to other 
companies that want to provide competing local phone and other 
communications services. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitacre and Notebaert, in their letter, said the merger ``can  
only increase our willingness to open our local markets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A key component of the merged company's strategy, the chiefs  
said, would be providing long-distance services to local phone 
customers. To obtain FCC permission to do that, the company must 
open its local markets to rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	The chiefs also said the merged company's plan to provide local  
phone and other services in 30 markets outside its combined 
13-state local region also would boost competition. Such a move 
would have SBC-Ameritech competing against fellow Bell companies. 
</P>
<P>
	By merging, the new company will become more efficient and  
financially able to invade markets outside its region, the chiefs 
said. It will also be in a stronger position to provide new 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	Ameritech and SBC representatives said they expect the FCC to  
approve the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The 13 states involved in the proposed merger are Arkansas,  
California, Connecticut, Kansas, Missouri, Nevada, Oklahoma, Texas, 
Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 18:13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amateur Hoopla Abounds at Masters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Matt Kuchar slumped against the giant oak  
tree that stands before the clubhouse at Augusta National. His face 
was flushed, his legs felt like jelly and he just wanted to find a 
shady place to sit down. 
</P>
<P>
	Sergio Garcia floated up to the 18th green like he was living a  
dream, hardly breaking a sweat in the sweltering Georgia heat. 
Observing the scene, Tiger Woods put his arm around Garcia's 
father-turned-caddy, pointed toward the 19-year-old Spaniard and 
gave a thumbs-up sign. 
</P>
<P>
	Those scenes signalled an amateur changing of the guard Thursday  
during the first round of the Masters. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuchar, who captivated the crowds a year ago with his gee-whiz  
grin and boyish enthusiasm, couldn't get his flu-ridden body to do 
what he wanted in his second trip to Augusta. Rarely smiling, he 
struggled to a 5-over-par 77 and had trouble keeping up with his 
playing partners, Tom Watson and Stuart Appleby, as the thermometer 
pushed toward 90 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year was a little more of a fairy tale,'' said Kuchar,  
the Georgia Tech junior who finished 21st in the 1998 Masters -- the 
highest finish by an amateur in 14 years. ``This year, I'm under 
the weather and it's taking away some of the fairy tale.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia, the Spanish phenom dubbed ``El Nino,'' picked up where  
Kuchar left off, and he took another amateur, South African Trevor 
Immelman, along for the ride. 
</P>
<P>
	Both shot even-par 72s on the first day, impressive scores when  
swirling wind and rock-hard greens made for brutally difficult 
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a little nervous at the beginning,'' said Garcia, who  
earned a spot in the tournament by winning the British Amateur. 
``But after three or four holes, I got so relaxed. I couldn't 
believe how relaxed I was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the amateur hoopla centered on Kuchar, Garcia and  
long-driving U.S. Amateur champion Hank Kuehne, who shot a 2-over 
74. But Immelman quietly put together one of the most solid rounds 
of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Paired with a hero, countryman and three-time Masters champion  
Gary Player, the 19-year-old Immelman saved his best shot for the 
end, salvaging a par at 18 when he chipped to within two feet of 
the hole from some 30 yards away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw a future champion today,'' said Player, who hugged  
Immelman after the round. ``He's got to be the best player in the 
world for a 19-year-old.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, Player didn't get a look at Garcia, who was in the  
threesome with Woods. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spaniard bogeyed the first two holes after errant tee shots.  
He landed in a patch of trees along the left side of the first 
fairway, then hooked his shot at No. 2 into a ditch, forcing him to 
a take a one-shot penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia made the turn at 3-over, but he felt like things were  
about to turn for the better. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just keep playing,'' he said under his breath, ``and the  
birdies will come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They did on the next two holes. At 10, he hit a 9-iron to within  
20 feet of the cup and made the putt. At 11, his 8-iron provided an 
easy -- by Augusta standards -- uphill putt from about seven feet. He 
missed a downhill seven-footer for birdie at 13, but made up for it 
four holes later by using his sand wedge from 127 yards to set up a 
10-foot birdie putt. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuehne, who managed to strike cars on Washington Avenue with his  
booming, practice-range shots, admitted he was nervous going to the 
first tee. But he closed with two birdies on the final four holes 
to put himself in position to make the cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuehne received some helpful advice from his playing partners,  
defending champion Mark O'Meara and Lee Westwood, as they walked 
down the first fairway. 
</P>
<P>
	``They told me the worst was over, it's all downhill from  
here,'' Kuehne recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom McKnight, 44, runner-up to Kuehne in the U.S. Amateur, shot  
a 1-over 73. The sixth amateur in the field, 48-year-old John 
``Spider'' Miller, struggled to an 81 in his second Masters 
appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuchar felt bursts of energy, like his birdie putt from off the  
green at No. 9 that prompted a high-fiving exchange with several 
members of gallery. Most of the day, though, he trudged around the 
course with a towel draped around his neck, looking downright 
wobbly as he struggled up the frequent hills. 
</P>
<P>
	At the eighth hole, he stopped along the ropes to grab a  
weathered, 1998 U.S. Open cap from his Uncle John -- unlike most 
golfers, Kuchar normally eschews headwear. He also got a brief, 
encouraging hug from his mother. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's really not feeling very well,'' Meg Kuchar said. ``He's  
doing the best he can, but it's awful hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kuchar has been suffering from flu-like symptoms for nearly a  
week. He wasn't able to make it through a full practice round and 
went to the hospital emergency room Tuesday night for treatment. 
The 20-year-old felt better Wednesday, actually making a 
hole-in-one during the par-3 tournament, and he hoped to awaken for 
the first round feeling like himself again. Instead, he took a turn 
of the worse. 
</P>
<P>
	``You try to play through it,'' he said with a shrug.  
</P>
<P>
	Immelman won the U.S. Public Links title, which hardly made him  
one of the high-profile players entering the Masters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was so nervous at the beginning,'' Immelman said. ``I was  
just hoping to get it airborne, really.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Player encouraged the youngster all the way around the course,  
and Immelman remembered Kuchar's performance in the previous 
Masters. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Matt did so well last year,'' the South African said,  
``it gave everyone the confidence to know we could come out and 
play with the pros.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Rise on European Rate Cut / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rose Thursday after the European  
Central Bank cut its main interest rate by one-half percentage 
point to 2.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 13/16  
point, or $8.13 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, fell to 5.44 percent from 5.50 percent late 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The ECB's cut was larger than many analysts had expected and the  
first since the euro currency was launched in 11 European nations 
at the beginning of the year. The European cut helped revive hopes 
that U.S. rates might also be headed lower, which would help 
fixed-income investments like bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were up between 3/32 point and 3/16 point, and intermediate 
maturities were up 9/32 point to 21/32 point, reported Bridge 
Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.38 percent as the  
discount fell 0.01 percentage point to 4.27 percent. Six-month 
yields were 4.51 percent, as the discount fell 0.01 percentage 
point to 4.35 percent. One-year yields were 4.61 percent as the 
discount fell by 0.04 percentage point from late Wednesday to 4.40 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.75 percent from 4.38 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose to 124 10/16 from 124 7/16. The average 
yield to maturity fell to 5.21 percent from 5.22 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 05:41:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ripken Misses Start Due to Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- After going 2,632 games without a day off, Cal  
Ripken is suddenly getting in the habit of watching from the 
dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since 1982, the Baltimore Orioles third  
baseman missed a game because of injury Wednesday. Saddled with a 
stiff lower back, Ripken decided it would be better to take a seat 
than to take a chance. 
</P>
<P>
	So he never picked up a bat and watched the Orioles lose to  
Tampa Bay 8-5. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second time in the Orioles' last 10 games Ripken  
failed to play. Last Sept. 20, he voluntarily ended his record 
consecutive games streak by sitting out Baltimore's final home game 
against the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, who left the Orioles' season opener Monday in the third  
inning with painful back spasms, began Wednesday night's game in 
the dugout while Willis Otanez took over at third base. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could beat my head against the wall and go do it today, but  
it doesn't make sense,'' Ripken said. ```We're going to just work 
toward being ready tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hours before the game, Ripken told manager Ray Miller that he  
wasn't quite 100 percent. So Miller decided to give Ripken the day 
off, even though he had already written the third baseman into the 
starting lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him I'd rather err on the side of caution and give him  
another 24 hours,'' Miller said. ``In my heart I know he never 
played a game just because of the streak. Fortunately for us it's 
not there anymore, so we can use a little better judgment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the streak were still alive, it probably would have come to a  
dramatic conclusion Wednesday night. Although Ripken's back felt a 
lot better than it did Monday, it was far from peak condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it was 90 percent, playing would be a no-brainer,'' he  
said. ``Every situation is different, but I doubt I'd play tonight 
regardless if the streak was still alive. ... I want to be able to 
contribute this whole season, and it wouldn't make sense to push it 
just to play one game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Ripken missed a game because of injury was on May  
3, 1982 after he got beaned by Seattle rookie Mike Moore. His 
record streak began later that month and survived two ankle 
injuries, a twisted knee and a herniated disc in his back in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	None of those ailments affected him the way his injury did  
Monday, when he was rendered helpless by stiffness, tightness and 
spasms in his lower back. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't consider myself superhuman. But I never reached a  
point where I couldn't play until the other day,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Otanez, meanwhile, was delighted to get his third major league  
start, but would have preferred it occurred under different 
circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice for me, I was happy to see I'm playing,'' he said.  
``But I don't want my teammate to get hurt like that. That's not 
good. I hope he gets well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Otanez hit his first major league homer and doubled in a 2-for-5  
night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990408.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 05:41:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ripken Misses Start Due to Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- After going 2,632 games without a day off, Cal  
Ripken is suddenly getting in the habit of watching from the 
dugout. 
</P>
