<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Urged To Delay Statehood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's prime minister urged Yasser Arafat today  
not to declare Palestinian statehood before restarting talks with 
Israel, a government official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan has been pushing Arafat not to jeopardize the Middle East  
peace process with such a declaration May 4, the end of the 
five-year interim period of self-rule for Palestinians in the West 
Bank and Gaza Strip. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand the Palestinians do have rights to their  
autonomy, and I strongly hope that an independent state will be 
established in the near future,'' Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi was 
quoted as telling Arafat by a Foreign Ministry official. ``But I 
strongly request that such a declaration of statehood not be made 
at this point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat, who left Japan for Vietnam shortly after the 35-minute  
session with Obuchi, agreed that the decision was a delicate one, 
although he said the end of the interim period would leave the 
Palestinian autonomous region ``in a legal vacuum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are hoping that we'll come to a decision that can satisfy  
everyone,'' he was quoted as saying by the Foreign Ministry 
official. 
</P>
<P>
	The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the  
Japanese government considered the statements a softening of 
Arafat's position. 
</P>
<P>
	He was quoted as telling Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko  
Komura on Wednesday that the PLO Central Committee would convene in 
late April to decide on a statehood declaration -- leaving open the 
possibility that such a declaration could be delayed. 
</P>
<P>
	With Mideast peace talks long bogged down, Israeli Prime  
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has threatened to annex parts of the 
West Bank and Gaza Strip if Arafat makes a unilateral statehood 
declaration. 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat arrived Wednesday in Tokyo as part of a weeklong tour of  
international capitals to discuss the possibility of a statehood 
declaration. 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat has stopped in Turkey and Russia, and was also scheduled  
to visit China, Indonesia, India, Pakistan and African nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat, who is on his third visit to Japan, last traveled to  
Tokyo in September 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
