<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Waste Companies' Asset Swap OK'd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Allied Waste Industries and Browning-Ferris  
Industries Inc. won approval Thursday for their $210 million asset 
swap from the Justice Department and the Illinois and Missouri 
attorneys general by agreeing to sell some waste collection routes 
in the St. Louis metropolitan area. 
</P>
<P>
	The department and the two state attorneys general filed a  
lawsuit in U.S. District Court here to block the original asset 
swap. At the same time, they filed an agreement that would settle 
the lawsuit and eliminate the deal's potential to harm competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The asset swap is separate from the proposed purchase of  
Browning-Ferris by Allied, which continues to be reviewed by the 
department's antitrust division and several state attorneys 
general, the department said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without this divestiture, St. Louis business consumers such as  
stores and restaurants would have paid higher prices and received 
lower quality services for waste collection,'' said Assistant 
Attorney General Joel I. Klein, head of the antitrust division. 
</P>
<P>
	The government argued that the original deal would have  
substantially reduced competition for commercial solid waste 
hauling in the St. Louis market. Allied and Browning-Ferris are two 
of only three companies that provide that service in the city of 
St. Louis and St. Louis County in Missouri and the Illinois 
counties of St. Clair, Madison and Monroe. 
</P>
<P>
	Commercial waste hauling usually entails collecting trash and  
garbage from small metal containers or Dumpsters, by special 
front-end loading trucks, and hauling it to disposal sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Allied and Browning-Ferris agreed to sell 12 commercial small  
container routes in the St. Louis market. Allied also agreed to 
limit its contracts with customers to no more than two years with a 
one-year renewal and to avoid excessive liquidated damage terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Allied and Browning-Ferris are two of the three largest waste  
hauling and disposal companies in the nation. In 1998, 
Browning-Ferris had domestic revenues of nearly $4.7 billion and 
Allied had domestic revenues of $1.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Browning-Ferris is headquartered in Houston; Allied is based in  
Scottsdale, Ariz. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
