<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 07:05:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spacey Makes 'Iceman' Sparkle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Arts and Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Kevin Spacey is at home at Harry Hope's Bar,  
playing the would-be savior of the dead-beat denizens in ``The 
Iceman Cometh.'' As Hickey, he carries off the star role with an 
intensity perfectly shaded for each of his on-stage friends and 
riveting for the audience. 
</P>
<P>
	The play, written by Eugene O'Neill in 1939 and first on  
Broadway in 1946, opened Thursday at the Brooks Atkinson Theater. 
The revival of the work is based on the production at London's 
Almeida Theater, where it opened to acclaim last year. 
</P>
<P>
	When Spacey, as the joke-telling Hickey, first enters the bar,  
he's off-putting with his fast-talk -- like a vintage radio 
personality. But soon Spacey's delivery and pacing become 
mesmerizing. 
</P>
<P>
	Hickey's father was a Midwestern preacher, and he's a salesman;  
it's obvious he has adopted speech rhythms that pull in a listener. 
It's plausible that this Hickey would spur the barflies out of 
their stupor. 
</P>
<P>
	Normally, Hickey tells a joke about his wife and the iceman. But  
now what he wants to do, at Harry Hope's 60th birthday party, is 
make the 15 folks who drink at the bar and sleep upstairs face 
their pipe dreams -- two words that become the play's mantra. They 
all have hope for tomorrow. 
</P>
<P>
	Hickey sends them out -- today -- to act on their oft-stated  
intentions. They all fail, as he expected, but he believes their 
encounters with reality will bring them peace. But peace never 
comes, so Hickey tells them his wife's pipe dream and his solution. 
</P>
<P>
	Spacey, known for dark, mysterious characters in numerous films  
and in TV's ``Wiseguy'' series, is joined in ``Iceman'' by Tony 
Danza. Best known for the TV series ``Taxi'' and ``Who's the 
Boss?'', Danza is excellent as Rocky, an Italian bartender pouring 
and withholding drinks at the whim of Harry Hope. 
</P>
<P>
	A couple of young streetwalkers, played by Catherine Kellner and  
Dina Spybey, work for Rocky. And all three are vehement about not 
using the words ``pimp'' and ``whore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Pigott-Smith, who was Ronald Merrick in TV's ``The Jewel in  
the Crown,'' plays the important role of Larry. He's a former 
anarchist who left ``the movement,'' who now sits in the 
grandstand, observing, caring about nothing. But, despite what he 
says, Larry is often moved to caring and pity. And, while he is 
physically removed from the others, he still manages a lot of 
walking and gestures and twitches not seen in the last revival on 
Broadway in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	It's interesting how both interpretations work. In contrast to  
Jason Robard's 1986 starring role, in which he delivered Hickey's 
last-act monologue with hurricane force, Spacey makes a soliloquy 
seem like a brief conversation. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the audience enter the theater to people dozing  
onstage, at the bar. Director Howard Davies and the actors have 
done an amazing job of making each character distinctive and 
interesting. So the audience is not confused or bored. Where lines 
are meant to be funny, they are delivered so well that they provoke 
big laughs. 
</P>
<P>
	James Hazeldine plays Harry Hope. One man, young Don Parritt,  
joins his regulars. He has betrayed his anarchist mother to the 
police. Robert Sean Leonard is slightly too upscale but properly 
anguished as Parritt. Stephen Singer as Hugo spouts anarchist 
rhetoric. Willie (Michael Emerson) was a brilliant law student. Joe 
(Clarke Peters) recalls owning a gambling house. Patrick L. Godfrey 
and Ed Dixon as old campaigners almost restart the Boer War. 
</P>
<P>
	Jimmy Tomorrow (Paul Giamatti) lost his job to drunkenness. Jeff  
Weiss and Richard Riehle play Hope's closest pals, an old carnival 
ticket-seller and a crooked ex-cop. Katie Finneran plays Cora, a 
tart, and Skipp Sudduth, her burly boyfriend Chuck. 
</P>
<P>
	The play's message, that people need pipe dreams to live,  
produces less gut emotion than intellectual power. 
</P>
<P>
	But power it is.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
