<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Bank Cuts Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Worried about flagging growth and  
double-digit unemployment rates across much of Europe, the European 
Central Bank cut its key interest rate by one-half percentage point 
Thursday to 2.5 percent in the first reduction since the euro 
currency was launched Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, bank president Wim Duisenberg chided political  
leaders in the 11 euro zone nations for not enacting the 
``convincing structural reforms'' that the bank -- and many 
economists -- believe are needed to solve Europe's economic woes. 
</P>
<P>
	He cited notoriously inflexible labor policies in countries like  
Germany, Europe's biggest economy and one of its sickest at the 
moment -- that make businesses reluctant to invest or take on new 
workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope our goal to get governments to pursue a reform policy  
will get a new incentive from the measures taken today,'' he said. 
``If they don't do that, monetary policy is no alternative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of England also cut its base borrowing rate by a  
quarter of a percentage point Thursday, to 5.25 percent, hoping to 
stimulate economic growth there at a time of low inflation. Britain 
is not part of Europe's single currency project. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had expected the European bank to cut rates by at least  
a quarter of a percentage point, noting that inflation -- the bank's 
primary concern -- was steady at less than 1 percent and showed no 
signs of igniting. 
</P>
<P>
	Duisenberg said the decision to cut even further was made to  
keep the market from speculating that it was only a first step. 
``Now you can be sure this is it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts also felt a rate cut could help reverse the slide  
of the euro, which turns 100 days old on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro has lost about 9 percent of its value against the  
dollar since Jan. 1, a drop attributed to everything from the 
continued strength of the U.S. economy to investor jitters over the 
fighting in Kosovo. It was trading Thursday at around $1.08. 
</P>
<P>
	Although a rate cut traditionally weakens a currency because  
investors earn less, analysts said in this case, it could boost the 
fledgling currency if investors believe it will spur growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Worse-than-expected economic data released Thursday in Germany  
added to pressure for the European bank to act: New manufacturing 
orders fell an adjusted 1.7 percent in February, after a big drop 
in January, and seasonally adjusted unemployment in March was 
basically unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Of Europe's two other big economies, Italy is slumping and  
prospects for France are gloomy, said Klaus Kegler, chief economist 
at Delbrueck and Co. bank in Cologne. 
</P>
<P>
	The three countries account for 75 percent of the euro zone's  
output. 
</P>
<P>
	Smaller countries like Spain and Ireland are doing better, but  
Duisenberg said he did not believe lower rates would overheat the 
economies there. 
</P>
<P>
	The reduction is the first since Dec. 3, when key rates were  
lowered to 3 percent among the euro nations to prepare for the new 
currency's introduction. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Duisenberg made a similar appeal for European  
governments to reform their labor policies and tightly regulated 
markets for goods and services. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet center-left governments in Europe have been moving in the  
opposite direction, with Rome and Paris seeking to legislate 
shorter work weeks and Bonn repealing the modest reforms on hiring 
and firing passed by former Chancellor Helmut Kohl. 
</P>
<P>
	Some leftist politicians, led by former German Finance Minister  
Oskar Lafontaine, had campaigned for the bank to lower interest 
rates to help reduce joblessness. 
</P>
<P>
	Ironically, Lafontaine's surprise resignation last month made it  
easier for the new bank to take such a step, since it wouldn't be 
interpreted by financial markets as caving in to political pressure 
or compromising its independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Duisenberg said he hoped the bank's latest move would  
``increasingly focus the attention of policymakers and the public 
on the real causes of the employment problem. Monetary policy is 
not the answer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 11 nations that launched the euro are Austria, Belgium,  
Finland, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the 
Netherlands, Portugal and Spain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
