<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hewlett Packard, EPA Reach Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- Hewlett Packard Co. and the U.S.  
Environmental Protection Agency have reached an agreement that may 
settle a complaint filed against the high-tech firm in September. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement would dramatically reduce the fines HP faces, in  
part because the company admitted problems with chemical records at 
its Corvallis plant before the investigation was complete. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA initially sought $2.5 million in fines. A motion filed  
Friday seeks permission for the EPA to drop one charge and reduce 
the fines to $112,000 on the remaining three charges. The case is 
being heard by a federal administrative law judge. 
</P>
<P>
	HP officials at the Corvallis plant -- the corporation is based  
in Palo Alto, Calif. -- said Wednesday they were pleased that the 
case is moving toward resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA charged that HP didn't let federal officials know about  
a new chemical it began using in its ink in the 1980s. 
Hewlett-Packard officials have described the complaint as a 
paperwork mix-up. 
</P>
<P>
	When the EPA first filed charges, officials said they didn't  
have enough information to tell whether HP ink was toxic. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials have insisted the chemicals in the ink are  
harmless. Friday's amendment didn't directly address the question, 
and company officials said the EPA could have acted more 
aggressively if there had been a problem with the ink. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement comes after more than six months of negotiations  
between the federal agency and HP. 
</P>
<P>
	In the complaint, EPA alleged the company didn't cooperate with  
its two-year investigation. Federal officials charged HP had failed 
numerous times to turn over documents, which stalled the 
investigation. HP has called those charges ``outrageous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	HP submitted the documents investigators wanted only after the  
EPA filed the complaint last fall, the amended complaint says. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did cooperate,'' Corvallis HP spokeswoman Marcy Eastham  
said. ``The original complaint took us by surprise because we felt 
we had cooperated with everything they had requested.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
