<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Accused of Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- An attorney for an aging Rwandan pastor  
charged with genocide argued before a federal appeals court today 
the man should not be surrendered to an international tribunal 
because no treaty exists that would allow it. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, 75, a retired Seventh-day Adventist  
Church pastor from Rwanda, awaits his fate in jail in Laredo, a 
city on the Texas-Mexico border. 
</P>
<P>
	His alleged involvement in ethnic conflicts in Rwanda in April  
1994 are at the root of his federal court case being heard in San 
Antonio by a three-judge panel of the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of 
Appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	The retired pastor was not in court but several of his relatives  
were, as defense attorney Ramsey Clark, former U.S. attorney 
general, argued Ntakirutimana should not be extradited by the 
United States to a United Nations tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's clear ... under our constitution, extradition requires a  
treaty,'' Clark said, pointing out there is no treaty between the 
United States and the tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark also argued today there is not sufficient evidence to send  
Ntakirutimana off to trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Government attorneys, however, said several witnesses have  
identified Ntakirutimana as having been involved in the massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the treaty questions, government attorneys contend the  
United States has an obligation under a federal law -- same as it 
would under a treaty -- to honor the surrender request of the 
tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	State-sponsored massacres in Rwanda in 1994 organized by Hutu  
extremists killed more than 500,000 people, mostly members of the 
minority group the Tutsis. 
</P>
<P>
	Ntakirutimana's arrest came after the U.N. International Crimes  
Tribunal on Rwanda refiled a request that Ntakirutimana be 
extradited to the central African nation for trial. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge John Rainey has ruled Ntakirutimana should  
be handed over to U.N. officials in Arusha, Tanzania. The pastor 
appealed. 
</P>
<P>
	Ntakirutimana was pastor of the Seventh-day Adventist Church in  
Mugonero in the Kibuye district of Rwanda. He is accused of urging 
a large, mostly Tutsi group of men, women and children to seek 
refuge in a church and hospital complex, then taking part in a 
daylong gun and machete attack that resulted in hundreds of deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Ntakirutimana also allegedly was part of a convoy that continued  
to carry out attacks in the weeks that followed against Tutsis who 
escaped the church massacre, the tribunal indictment claims. 
</P>
<P>
	It is not known when the three-judge appeals court panel will  
rule. The decision can then be appealed to the full 5th U.S. 
Circuit Court in New Orleans and to the Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	If Ntakirutimana is sent to Tanzania to stand trial, it will  
mark the first time the United States has surrendered a defendant 
from American soil to a U.N. tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, he could face life in prison.  
</P>
<P>
	Through Clark, the retired pastor has denied the allegations.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's all political,'' Clark has said. ``All it does is it  
feeds into hatreds that caused the violence in the first place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Government attorneys contend the United States has a treaty  
obligation to honor the surrender request of the tribunal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
