<HEADLINE> Marlins' Lowell Gets Rehab Detail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Florida Marlins third baseman Mike Lowell, working  
his way back after cancer surgery, was sent to Triple-A Calgary on 
Thursday for a rehabilitation assignment. 
</P>
<P>
	Plans called for Lowell to start at third base in Calgary's  
season opener Thursday night at Memphis. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell, 25, who grew up in South Florida, was diagnosed with  
testicular cancer after a small mass was found during a routine 
physical exam Feb. 19. He underwent surgery two days later to 
remove one testicle. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins placed Lowell on the disabled list March 26.  
</P>
<P>
	Lowell came to Florida from the New York Yankees in a Feb. 1  
trade for three pitching prospects. The power-hitting rookie had 
been expected to challenge incumbent Kevin Orie for the third-base 
job before the cancer was diagnosed. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past two minor league seasons, Lowell hit .309 with 56  
home runs and 191 RBIs. 
</P>
