<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FAA To Study Engine Backfiring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Pratt &AMP; Whitney has been working for  
years to fix a backfiring problem in engines used on hundreds of 
jets worldwide -- and now government inspectors are intensifying 
their scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the backfiring is mild, but there have been reports of  
flames shooting out of the engines, forcing pilots to shut down 
power. No crashes have been blamed on the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration said Thursday it is stepping  
up evaluations of the PW4000 engines, which power almost 600 
aircraft operated by 60 airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency already has ordered that modified engines be  
installed by June 30. It is preparing a second order regarding 
methods to determine whether the engine should be used at all, said 
Robert Guyotte, manager of the FAA engine certification branch in 
Burlington, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	The East Hartford company has been working on the problem since  
1993. While the incidents of backfires have decreased, the problem 
is not fixed, according to the FAA. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 170 backfires of PW4000s have been reported since  
1992. Less than 20 of those happened with engines that Pratt has 
modified since the problem was reported, Guyotte said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was after series of violent backfires by a PW4000 engine that  
a United Airlines 747 lost power on takeoff from San Francisco and 
nearly struck San Bruno Mountain last June. 
</P>
<P>
	Although pilot error was blamed, the PW4000 has been implicated  
in several other near-disasters. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past three years, about 85 percent of the estimated 2,000  
engines in service have been modified, Pratt spokesman Mark 
Sullivan said. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
