<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: China Stole Bomb Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A U.S. intelligence report suggests that China  
improved its neutron bomb technology with military secrets stolen 
in 1995 from the United States, The New York Times reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The information was provided by a spy working for the United  
States in China, the Times reported, citing unidentified U.S. 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The report calls into question Clinton administration claims  
that there is no evidence of Chinese nuclear espionage after the 
1980s, when China is suspected of having stolen designs of 
America's most modern nuclear warhead, the W-88. 
</P>
<P>
	It also conflicts with statements from administration officials  
that they acted promptly in response to concerns about security 
breaches at the nation's nuclear research labs, the Times said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials have said that China tried to build a neutron  
warhead in the 1980s using secrets stolen from the Lawrence 
Livermore National Laboratory in California. But a 1988 test of the 
weapon proved unsuccessful. 
</P>
<P>
	The spy's 1996 report suggested that Chinese operatives returned  
to the United States in 1995 to gather more secrets and solve 
design problems with the neutron bomb, which kills people with 
enhanced radiation while leaving buildings intact. 
</P>
<P>
	The report prompted an investigation, but American officials say  
they have found no evidence that China has produced an improved 
neutron bomb. 
</P>
<P>
	China has denied stealing military secrets. President Clinton  
was to meet with Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji today to discuss a 
number of topics, including security issues. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials said administration officials were told of the  
neutron espionage report in early 1996, the Times said, but Clinton 
did not issue a Presidential order on laboratory security until 
February 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Wen Ho Lee, a suspect in the theft of W-88 information, was  
dismissed from his job at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New 
Mexico last month. 
</P>
<P>
	He has not been charged with any crime. The Times said the FBI  
has not been able to establish a connection between Lee and the 
neutron bomb investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
