</P>
<P>
 *A tale of a Muslim and a guide dog    	
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A Muslim cab driver refused to pick up a blind  
woman and her guide dog on religious grounds, and now the city must 
issue a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal and state laws guarantee guide dogs access to all public  
places and vehicles, but the First Amendment protects religious 
freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	The city must deal with a complaint filed in February by Annie  
McEachrin against Hassan Taher. McEachrin, blind since birth, has a 
constant companion, a black Lab named Jessica. Taher, who adheres 
strictly to Islamic law, says his religion considers dogs impure. 
</P>
<P>
	Nihad Awad, executive director of the Council on American  
Islamic Relations in Washington, said, ``The driver ... acted in 
good faith. He's acted in accordance with his religious beliefs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. McEachrin, 43, is a talking-book coordinator and public  
relations representative for the Cincinnati Association for the 
Blind. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want it to seem like I'm bitter about this,'' she  
said. ``I'm more concerned about people with disabilities being 
treated fairly.'' 
</P>
