<HEADLINE> Ex-LSU Running Back Avoids Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- NFL prospect Cecil Collins avoided  
prison by pleading guilty Thursday to charges he fondled two women 
in their apartments. 
</P>
<P>
	The running back who dazzled football fans during a brief career  
at LSU will be on probation for four years -- but will probably also 
play in the NFL during that time. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of a plea bargain, Collins pleaded guilty to two  
misdemeanor counts of simple battery and two felony counts of 
unauthorized entry of an inhabited dwelling. He had faced more than 
10 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has learned from this,'' Collins' lawyer Rodney Baum said.  
``Cecil doesn't take anything for granted now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added assistant district attorney Sue Bernie: ``This is  
appropriate since he's a first-time offender and the victims and 
their families are satisfied.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, a possible first- or second-round pick in the NFL draft  
on April 10, must also be tested for drugs every week, give $2,500 
to a women's shelter, perform 300 hours of community service and 
stay away from LSU for the length of his probation. He is allowed 
to leave Louisiana only for employment. 
</P>
<P>
	The 22-year-old Collins said he would meet the conditions but  
refused to comment further. The two women, ages 17 and 18, are LSU 
students and lived in the same apartment complex as Collins. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicknamed ``Diesel'' for his powerful running style, Collins  
played in only four games at LSU before breaking his leg. He gained 
at least 172 yards in each of his three starts for the Tigers. He 
was kicked off the football team in June 1998 following his arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins transferred to McNeese State after leaving LSU, but was  
kicked off that school's team two games into the season when he 
failed a drug test. 
</P>
</TEXT>
