<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ricky Williams Visits Redskins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- One of the byproducts of the latest delay in  
finding an owner for the Washington Redskins is that general 
manager Charley Casserly and coach Norv Turner are finally assured 
they'll conduct next weekend's draft. 
</P>
<P>
	One player they'd love to have, Heisman Trophy winner Ricky  
Williams, visited Redskin Park on Thursday. Given that the top 
three picks could all be quarterbacks, the Texas running back could 
fall to the Redskins, who pick No. 5 overall. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not in a position to trade up, and we will not trade  
up,'' Casserly said. ``However, there is a scenario that he could 
be there at No. 5, and it would very hard to pass up a player of 
Ricky Williams' potential at the fifth pick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Casserly and Williams talked football, communications  
executive Daniel Snyder was across town working the phones to put 
together a group to buy the Redskins. His partners will include 
publishing executives Mort Zuckerman and Fred Drasner, and he hopes 
to have a proposal ready as soon as the bidding is reopened. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder was a junior partner in an $800 million bid that was  
withdrawn at a meeting of league owners in Atlanta on Thursday 
after it became obvious it would not get the votes necessary for 
approval. 
</P>
<P>
	New York real estate developer and New York Islanders part-owner  
Howard Milstein was unable to put together a financial plan that 
satisfied many owners, and others were concerned about Milstein's 
business style and whether he would become a maverick. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder, who had become disenchanted with Milstein because of the  
approval problems, plans to be the top man in his new group. First, 
however, the trustees of the estate of late owner Jack Kent Cooke, 
working with the NFL, must establish the rules for the next round 
of bidding. 
</P>
<P>
	The trustees have the option of throwing open the bidding to  
anyone, limiting it to those who bid last time or taking the first 
bid that matches the $800 million Milstein-Snyder offer. 
</P>
<P>
	A representative of the trustees did not return calls from The  
Associated Press on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Had the Milstein-Snyder group prevailed, Casserly and Turner  
might not have survived the change in ownership, negating the 
hundreds of hours of planning they've put into the April 17-18 
draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Now they at least have the comfort of knowing their plan will be  
put into action. 
</P>
<P>
	``You learn to live with things in life,'' Casserly said of the  
uncertainty. ``You just have to adjust to what happens. You can't 
complain about it. I think it's important for everyone to stay 
focused on the job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Redskins probable first-round choice is Georgia cornerback  
Champ Bailey, but Williams becomes the automatic selection if he's 
still around. If he is, Bailey might be gone anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	That would be a disappointment to Williams, who feels he should  
be the No. 1 overall pick. He recently dropped 20 pounds to satisfy 
concerns that he had put on too much weight, and says his 
appearance -- he showed up Friday sporting nose jewelry and 
dreadlocks -- gives his detractors more ammunition. 
</P>
<P>
	``I may be being foolish,'' Williams said. ``But it seems like  
because I'm the way I am and I do things the way I want to do them 
and I'm not really a conformist, that people don't want to see me 
succeed sometimes.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
