<HEADLINE> Germany's Unemployment Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NUREMBERG, Germany (AP) -- Germany's jobs crisis eased slightly  
in March, with unemployment dropping to 11.1 percent from 11.6 
percent the month before, the Federal Labor Office reported 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	About 4.29 million people were unemployed, 176,400 fewer than in  
February, although joblessness remained more severe in Germany's 
east, which is still recovering from the switch from communism to a 
market economy begun in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Unemployment in the five eastern states was 18.4 percent, or  
1.39 million people, compared with 19.1 percent last month. 
Unemployment in the more prosperous and populous west was 9.3 
percent, or 2.9 million people, a drop from 9.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor office president Bernhard Jagoda attributed the  
improvement in part to the onset of spring weather, a boon to 
outdoor industries such as construction. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from the seasonal factors, however, the labor office said  
the jobs situation in Germany was unchanged from last month. But 
March's figures were still an improvement over the same time last 
year, when unemployment was 12.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder has made job creation a the key  
mission of his first year in office, after winning election last 
September on promises to end unemployment that had risen to 
post-war record highs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
