<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Cross Seeks Albanian Speakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- When Viola Soter's cousin phoned to ask her to  
give up the creature comforts in Florida to help Kosovar refugees 
in Cuba, the retiree didn't give it a second thought. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goodness, with so much of that suffering going on, and the  
need is so great, that anything I can do to help, I'm perfectly 
willing to help,'' Ms. Soter said from her home in Belle Air Beach, 
Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Although she and her husband, Michael, are both in their 60s,  
they're ready to bring their much-needed Albanian language skills 
to the U.S. Naval Base at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Clinton administration announced that as many as  
20,000 refugees will be taken to Cuba in the coming days. Although 
the U.S. government hasn't yet asked the Red Cross for help, a 
spokeswoman said the agency is expecting the request. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Cross chapters in other cities with large Albanian-American  
populations, including New York, Detroit and Philadelphia, may 
follow Boston's lead and request volunteers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Soters, along with a dozen college students, will go through  
a day or two of Red Cross training and then spend a month providing 
meals, clothing, first aid and a sympathetic ear to the refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's difficult when you're handing someone a package of dried  
soup and the instructions are in a language they don't 
understand,'' said Paul Healy, spokesman for the American Red Cross 
in Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, U.S. authorities are busy setting up wood frame  
canvas tents in Cuba and preparing to help Eastern European 
refugees adjust to life in the Caribbean. 
</P>
<P>
	A Naval psychological intervention team staffed with  
psychologists and mental health workers, as well as the military's 
sole Muslim chaplain in the region, have been reassigned to 
Guantanamo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
