<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles' Ripken Sits Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Cal Ripken missed a second straight game  
Thursday, but he said his sore back feels much better and he has no 
intention of going on the disabled list for the first time in his 
19-year career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Absolutely not,'' Ripken said before the Baltimore Orioles  
lost to Tampa Bay 6-3. ``Today I'm bouncing around real well and 
eager to put the uniform on and start swinging. But it just makes 
sense to go one more day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, 38, left Monday's opener against Tampa Bay in the third  
inning with stiffness in his back. He watched Wednesday's game from 
the dugout, the first time he missed a game due to injury since 
1982. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Sept. 20, Ripken voluntarily ended his record consecutive  
games streak of 2,632 by sitting out the Orioles' final home game 
against the New York Yankees. He then played the final seven games 
of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken's back loosened up considerably by Thursday, but he was  
omitted from the starting lineup after discussing his options with 
manager Ray Miller and trainer Richie Bancells. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm popping around and I'm sure I can do a lot of things,''  
Ripken said. ``But when you think about it from an intelligent 
viewpoint, I probably shouldn't do anything dumb and (should) give 
myself one more day. That was the advice given to me and that's 
what I'm going to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken did not take batting practice, and Miller avoided the  
temptation to use him as a pinch-hitter Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him to rest and continue to get treatment. Using him  
tonight would defeat the purpose of giving him another day,'' 
Miller said before the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken had not missed two straight games since shortly after he  
joined the Orioles for the first time in August 1981. He sat out 
the last 12 games of the season, and the following May began his 
record-breaking streak. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken didn't like watching from the dugout then, and he doesn't  
like doing it now. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a very agonizing and tough thing to sit and watch the  
game,'' he said. ``Every minute you want to be in there, though it 
will probably feel even worse tonight because I know I'm better 
today than yesterday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Frank Wren said the Orioles will wait and see  
before determining whether Ripken would be better served by 
spending time on the disabled list. 
</P>
<P>
	``The second five days, if it doesn't make any progress then  
that's when you DL him,'' Wren said. ``That's when you start 
getting serious about saying, `We have to think about replacing 
him.''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
