<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *Frederick W. Carr    	
</P>
<P>
	CLAREMONT, N.H. (AP) -- Frederick W. Carr, a World War II pilot  
and former prisoner of war, died Monday. He was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Carr enlisted in the Army Air Corps when he turned 21 and then  
joined the 8th Army Air Force, 489th Bomber Group and the 846th 
Squadron, flying out of England. 
</P>
<P>
	On June 25, 1944, while flying his 18th mission, Carr was shot  
down near Gisors, France. He survived, and the French Underground 
hid him in Etrepagney, providing him with false identity papers. 
</P>
<P>
	Carr worked for a time with E.J. Hugel, mayor of Etrepagney and  
a leader in the underground. But during an attempt to escape 
occupied territory and rejoin the Allied Forces, he was captured by 
the Gestapo. 
</P>
<P>
	He was incarcerated in Fresnes Prison in Paris, then sent to the  
Buchenwald concentration camp in Germany. After four months, he was 
transferred to a prisoner of war camp in Poland, Stalag Luft III. 
</P>
<P>
	With other prisoners, he walked 500 miles to Munich to be  
liberated by U.S. Gen. George Patton on April 27, 1945. He later 
testified at the Nuremberg trials of Nazi war criminals. 

</P>
<P>
                          *H. Donald Loucks    	
</P>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- H. Donald Loucks, who coached Florida  
State's first men's basketball team in 1947, died Tuesday. He was 
84. 
</P>
<P>
	Loucks also coached tennis for several years at the university  
beginning in 1947, the year Florida State College for Women became 
the coeducational Florida State University. 
</P>
<P>
	His basketball team finished the inaugural 1947-48 season 5-13.  
That was the only year he coached the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Loucks became a member of university's Hall of Fame in 1985.  

</P>
<P>
                        *Robert B. Miller Sr.    	
</P>
<P>
	BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) -- Robert B. Miller Sr., who served as  
publisher of the Battle Creek Enquirer and News for 27 years, died 
Tuesday. He was 92. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller was in the newspaper business for 50 years and also was a  
philanthropist and major investor in rebuilding downtown Battle 
Creek. 
</P>
<P>
	His father, Albert Miller, merged the Morning Enquirer and the  
Evening News into the Battle Creek Enquirer and News in 1918, 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Miller became a reporter for the Battle Creek Enquirer  
and News in 1928. He became publisher in 1952 and held the position 
until 1979, when his son, Robert B. Miller Jr., become the third 
generation of Millers to run the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	He served as publisher until 1990. The paper, now called the  
Battle Creek Enquirer, changed its name in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years the family acquired six other newspapers, forming  
Federated Publications. Federated was purchased by Gannett Co. Inc. 
in 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors also include another son, Allen L. Miller.  

</P>
<P>
                       *Madeleine Haas Russell    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Madeleine Haas Russell, a descendent of  
Levi Strauss who used her family fortune to support the arts, 
cultural groups and liberal political causes, died Friday on her 
84th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with her late brother, Mrs. Russell co-founded the  
Columbia Foundation, which distributed grants totaling about $3.5 
million in the last fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	One of her earliest grants after World War II went to the  
Emergency Committee of Atomic Scientists to help discourage the use 
of nuclear weapons and energy. She later was active in causes that 
included the abolition of the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Russell was a major contributor to Democratic candidates  
and the Democratic Party, supporting U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein, 
President Clinton, Rep. Nancy Pelosi and many others. 
</P>
<P>
	The current home of KQED, San Francisco's public TV and radio  
station, bears her name. 
</P>
<P>
	She was a great-grandniece of the Bavarian immigrant who crafted  
the first pair of blue jeans. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
