<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 01:32:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anniversary of Ala. Tornado Marked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCK CREEK, Ala. (AP) -- The girls' softball team practices on a  
dusty, red field in a park that was littered with debris from a 
deadly tornado last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The coach and her daughter lost their home to the storm. The  
catcher, right fielder and first baseman lost their school. And the 
second baseman attended church with six people who were killed, 
including a 7-year-old boy who played baseball at the same park. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a year of pain and heartache caused by the tornado, the  
girls nodded in agreement this spring when somebody suggested an 
odd name for their team: the Rock Creek Twisters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all just decided on the Twisters, since we all went through  
it,'' said pitcher Cheree Melton, 12. 
</P>
<P>
	Today marks the one-year anniversary of the tornado that killed  
32 people and injured about 260 when it raged through the county 
that surrounds Birmingham with winds of nearly 300 mph. Two more 
people died in a smaller tornado in St. Clair County, to the east. 
</P>
<P>
	The Twisters plan to spend the anniversary at Hoover  
Metropolitan Stadium, where they will get to run on the field 
tonight with Birmingham's minor-league baseball team, the Barons. 
</P>
<P>
	Others will mark the occasion somberly. Carol Blankenship helped  
organize a memorial service and candlelight procession through her 
neighborhood, where seven people died. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope that our event will make a little better memory for  
people on future April eighths,'' said Mrs. Blankenship, whose home 
was destroyed by the twister. 
</P>
<P>
	Mental health workers have encouraged survivors to do something  
to mark the anniversary of the storm. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been doing a lot of work in the school system ...  
talking to (children) about the things they may be feeling,'' said 
Lisa Turley of the county mental health authority. ``Parents, 
seeing their children working to recover, are trying to recover on 
their own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Recovering from the tornado is one thing. Forgetting is another:  
There are too many reminders. 
</P>
<P>
	Trees are budding with new life, but the 31-mile-long path of  
the tornado is still clearly visible. A half-mile-wide swath of 
bare ground and splintered trees is strewn with little pieces of 
housing shingles. 
</P>
<P>
	Cindy Chapman is still amazed by the storm's power as she drives  
past damaged trees and homes while taking her daughter, shortstop 
Curry Chapman, to softball practice. 
</P>
<P>
	The tornado missed the Chapman family, but just being around so  
much death and destruction is an emotional drain. Mrs. Chapman was 
happy when the girls decided to poke fun at their shared experience 
by choosing ``Twisters'' for a name. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a sign of healing,'' she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
