<DOCNO> APW19990408.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 14:55:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pizza Mogul Creates Catholic School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Domino's Pizza mogul Tom Monaghan, who  
sold the business to devote himself to Roman Catholic causes, is 
spending $50 million to establish a new law school stressing 
traditional Catholic values. 
</P>
<P>
	One-time Supreme Court nominee Robert Bork has signed on as its  
first professor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will be the West Point for Catholic laity in the  
years to come,'' said Monaghan, who recently sold Domino's for $1 
billion. ``I'm really disappointed in Catholic education in this 
country. It's been secularized.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Ave Maria School of Law is to open in fall 2000 with about  
40 students but hopes to have more than 400 within six years. Ann 
Arbor, the home of the University of Michigan's main campus, is 35 
miles west of Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	The school's emphasis will be on what the Catholic Church sees  
as moral truths, Monaghan said Wednesday. Ave Maria students will 
be taught to incorporate that philosophy in their legal analysis. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rule of law must be founded in a belief that there is an  
objective, moral order. This is something no law school does 
effectively,'' said Bernard Dobranski, who will be Ave Maria's 
dean. He has the same position now at Catholic University's law 
school in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	There are 24 Catholic institutions among the nation's 181 law  
schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Ave Maria's board of governors includes former Interior  
Secretary William P. Clark and Cardinal John O'Connor, archbishop 
of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Monaghan's strong support for anti-abortion causes led to a  
nationwide boycott of Domino's by the National Organization for 
Women. More recently, he has supervised the construction of a 
cathedral in Nicaragua, built a mission in Honduras and created 
Catholic schools in the Ann Arbor area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
