<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 17:24:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crackdown on Illegal Viagra Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Workers at two Manhattan businesses were  
arrested Thursday on federal charges they sold Viagra without a 
prescription, part of an effort to curb illegal sales of the male 
impotence drug. 
</P>
<P>
	Yao Shen, Victor Yin and Wei Zhang were brought to U.S. District  
Court in Manhattan, where lawyers arranged their release on $20,000 
bail after a brief appearance before U.S. Magistrate Judge Kevin 
Nathaniel Fox. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart Magee, special agent in charge of the FDA office in  
Jersey City, N.J., said the investigation was continuing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're seeing more and more cases that involve Viagra,'' Magee  
said, describing it as one of many drugs that are diverted to 
illegal markets. ``It's become a very popular drug for diversion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the arrests were necessary to protect the public. ``It's  
a public health issue,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the defendants, all residents of New York City,  
declined to speak to reporters prior to the initial appearances of 
their clients in court. 
</P>
<P>
	On Nov. 30, Yin sold 40 tablets of Viagra at the Gift and Health  
Products Center to an undercover FDA agent for $440 after telling 
the agent that he was a doctor, the FDA alleged in a criminal 
complaint. It said he did not ask for a prescription. 
</P>
<P>
	On Jan. 27 at the International Travel Agency, Shen sold two  
bottles of Viagra to an undercover FDA agent for $620 without 
asking for a prescription, according to the complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	In another instance at the Gift and Health Products Center, on  
March 10 an undercover agent with the New York State Office of 
Professional Discipline bought a bottle of Viagra from Zhang for 
$320, the complaint said. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the drug sold at the businesses was not much higher  
than the wholesale price of $5 to $6 per pill paid by pharmacies, 
investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, the men could face a maximum of three years in  
prison and fines of up to $10,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
